<FIRST>r i AM-India-Pilots     06-22 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Pilots,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Authorities Interrogating U.S., German Pilots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are interrogating two U.S.
and two West German pilots after Indian air force fighters forced
down their small planes near the Pakistani border, the Defense
Ministry said Thursday.
   In Washington, the State Department identified the Americans as
Frank Haile Jr., 57, of Dallas, and Carson Gilmore of Rocksprings,
Texas.
   The two, making an around-the-world trip in a Beechcraft Bonanza,
were intercepted by the Indian jets on June 16 and forced to land at
Bhuj airfield in western Gujarat state, a Defense Ministry spokesman
said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the two men were traveling with two West Germans, whose
Beechcraft also was ordered to land at Bhuj, about 500 miles
southwest of New Delhi.
   A West German Embassy official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, identified the Germans pilots with only their last names
as Kuhlmann and Kuffner.
   The Defense Ministry spokesman said the planes had strayed about
310 miles off the assigned course and intruded into restricted
airspace over Bhuj, a marshy wasteland near the border with Pakistan.
   Civil aviation authorities cleared the planes to fly from New
Delhi to Bahrain via Bombay, he said.
   The pilots were first questioned by air force officers and later
handed over to federal intelligence officers, he said.
   A U.S. Embassy offical said a consular officer attended the
interrogation. The U.S. Privacy Act prevented disclosing more
information about the pilots, said the official who cannot be
identified under briefing rules.
   Haile and Gilmore departed from the suburban Addison airport in
Dallas three weeks ago.
   Haile, the owner and president of a Dallas-based engineering
firm, has flown around the world twice and is an experienced
long-distance pilot, according to his wife, Joan.
</TEXT>
