<FIRST>r a AM-HUDProbe-Austin 1stLd-Writethru a0732 06-22 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe-Austin, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0732,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Looking Into Apparent Diversions in Austin Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 6th graf, `Lee refused...,' to UPDATE
with developments in Indianapolis. Picks up 7th graf, `Last week...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are looking into the
apparent diversion of up to $90,000 in housing funds intended for
poor families living in federally subsidized apartments here, it was
reported Thursday.
   The money was supposed to cover rent and utility bills in 1986 to
early 1988 for five families who lived in the housing complexes
known as Interregional Apartments, the Austin American-Statesman
said.
   The 99 apartments were shut down by the city in September because
of building code violations.
   ``It may be a while before we can get to it, but it is scheduled
for investigation,'' said Johnny O. Lee, the Housing and Urban
Development regional inspector general in Fort Worth.
   ``Right now, it's waiting in line with a lot of other cases,''
Lee said. ``It's a question of time and manpower.''
   Lee refused to say who might have diverted the funds, saying it's
their policy not to comment on ongoing investigations.
   In another development, HUD officials in Indianapolis said
Thursday that almost a third of the $257,012 that federal auditors
said might be missing from the agency's office here has been found.
   Payments have been received or documentation found for $80,046.95
from the sale of five foreclosed homes during a 4{-year period, said
J. Nicholas Shelley, director of the Indianapolis HUD office.
   In a June 13 report, federal auditors identified 16 Indiana
transactions for which the agency hadn't received payment. Auditors
said the proceeds, plus $30,486 in damages, should be paid to the
government.
   Authorities and Indianapolis Realty, which handled closings on
the sales, are looking for documentation of the remaining 11
transactions, which brought $176,965.50, officials said.
   If the transfer of the money can't be documented, Shelley said,
the government stands to get its money either from Indianapolis
Realty or its bonding company.
   Last week, a private escrow agent from Maryland nicknamed ``Robin
HUD'' told Congress she diverted millions of dollars from government
housing programs.
   The agent, Marilyn Harrell, admitted to investigators that she
did not forward at least $5.5 million to the federal housing agency,
saying she donated much of the money to charitable projects to
provide housing for the poor.
   In Austin, the principal owner of the Interregional Apartments is
San Antonio investor Benard L. Lifshutz, who said he was aware that
some subsidies were taken but he was not involved.
   Another partner in the project, listed in city records as Chuck
McGinnis of Austin, could not be located, the newspaper said.
Lifshutz said he and McGinnis are no longer business partners and he
had not spoken to McGinnis in months.
   According to a letter from the city to the HUD inspector general,
the apparent diversion of federal utility subsidies took place
between August 1986 and February 1988.
   Former acting City Manager John Ware told City Council members in
a memo last year that the exact amount of money taken was hard to
determine because the owners' records for those years ``are
virtually non-existent.''
   City staff at the Department of Housing and Community Services,
which administers the federally subsidized housing program, said
they believe the amount was $80,000 to $90,000.
   The department staff first learned of the problem when
Interregional tenants complained that their electric, gas, and water
services were being disconnected.
   City records show that dozens of the apartments were overrun with
rats and cockroaches; contained exposed and damaged plumbing and
wiring; had holes in some of the floors and ceilings; and could not
meet minimal city building and safety codes.
   Police records also show that by 1986 the apartment complexes had
become a center of criminal activity, including prostitution and
drug dealing.
   At one point, police records show, one tenant at Interregional
offered ``drive-up curb service,'' making drug deals through an
apartment window.
</TEXT>
