<FIRST>r a AM-BoyingtonBust     06-22 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boyington Bust,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monument Dedicated to War Ace `Pappy' Boyington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUMA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military officials and former comrades of Col.
Gregory ``Pappy'' Boyington dedicated a life-size bust Thursday at
the Marine Corps Air Station here to honor the late World War II ace.
   Boyington's widow, Josephine, of Fresno, Calif., and son, Gregory
Jr., attended the ceremonies at the base, the home of VMA-214, the
Black Sheep Squadron. The nickname for the group originated around
the idea that members of the squadron, formed in the Solomon Islands
in 1942, were misfits.
   Boyington shot down 28 aircraft while fighting in the Pacific
Theater, and his squadron accounted for a total of 197 Japanese
planes.
   Shot down Jan. 3, 1944, over Tokyo, Boyington spent the rest of
the war in a prisoner-of-war camp in Omori, Japan. He was mistakenly
presumed dead during the war and awarded the Medal of Honor _ the
nation's highest decoration for military valor _ posthumously.
   Boyington died Jan. 11, 1988. The bust was the idea of his
longtime friend, Raymond ``Hap'' Halloran, who said attending
Boyington's funeral at Arlington National Cemetery gave him the
desire to do something special to commemorate his friend.
   Halloran, an Army Air Corps fighter pilot, was shot down over the
Pacific in January 1945 and met Boyington in a prisoner-of-war camp.
   ``To see him in real life was a comforting thing. I know probably
nothing would happen to us'' because Boyington was there, Halloran
said at the ceremonies.
</TEXT>
