<FIRST>r a AM-RanchoSeco     06-22 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rancho Seco,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility Votes to Take Private Bids to Restart Nuke Power Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of the Rancho Seco nuclear power
plant has decided to accept bids for a private takeover of the
facility, despite a referendum that called for its shutdown.
   The 3-2 vote by directors of the Sacramento Municipal Utility
District on Tuesday angered many of the activists who have fought
for years to shut down the plant, which has nearly a continuous
history of operating problems.
   On March 2, the directors had voted unanimously to abide by the
results of the June 6 referendum, in which voters turned down an
advisory measure endorsing the Sacramento Municipal Utility
District's plans to keep the plant running.
   The plant was taken off line June 7 and so far about 400 contract
workers have lost their jobs.
   Utility directors voting with the majority argued that voters
merely had forbidden SMUD from operating the plant.
   Divestiture of Rancho Seco ``remains a viable option ... that
could free this community from the staggering costs of
decommissioning,'' said Joseph Buonaiuto, president of the utility's
board of directors.
   The utility estimates it will cost about $200 million to close
the plant.
   Sacramentans for Safe Energy, an anti-Rancho Seco group, has said
it will sue to stop efforts to transfer Rancho Seco to private
businesses that might continue to operate it.
   ``We will wait and see what happens in the 10-day period'' that
the utility set to accept bids, said Michael Remy, an environmental
attorney affiliated with the group. ``Our position still is that
enough is enough.''
</TEXT>
