<DOCNO> AP890622-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Timber-NewMill     06-22 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Timber-New Mill,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weyerhaeuser's Got All-New Attitude for Export Lumber</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Timber-Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COOS BAY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One tip that Weyerhaeuser is taking bold
steps with its newest sawmill is the bed of pansies in the log yard.
   Weyerhaeuser, a leading exporter of logs to Japan, has gone a
step further to produce precision-sawn, metric-dimension lumber for
Japanese home builders, for whom the appearance of wood for
traditional post-and-beam construction counts more than the
structural strength valued in the American market.
   ``We want to put out logs to the highest value market. In recent
years the highest value has been offshore,'' said operations manager
Jack Taylor.
   So the company scrapped an aging mill in North Bend on the
southern coast and converted a cedar plant here into ts mill of the
'90s, called CBX.
   ``We're pulling out all the stops,'' said superintendent Sam
Dickey as he showed off the paved log yard, laser-guided saws,
flowers and a new management style that emphasizes teamwork. ``We're
spending $1 million on the upgrade.''
   But high-tech also means fewer jobs. When Weyerhaeuser announced
the CBX project in January, North Bend employed about 200 and
produced about 65 million board feet a year, about 3 jobs per
million board feet. The CBX crew of 69 can produce 45 million board
feet a year, or 1.5 jobs per million feet.
   The mills that survive the current shakeup in the industry must
be extremely efficient, and Dickey expects his hand-picked crew to
lead the way. ``We're aiming to have this site be the model for the
industry.''
   To emphasize that point, Weyerhaeuser has installed catwalks for
visitors.
   ``All the major Japanese trading companies have been here once or
twice,'' said Dickey, who is learning Japanese.
   While Weyerhaeuser took the obvious steps of upgrading the
physical plant at CBX, it also is going where no sawmill has gone
before in its contract with the International Woodworkers of America.
   ``Basically, it lets people work as teams rather than in
individual job situations,'' said Milo Summerville, field
representative for IWA Local 3-261. ``Sometimes you have to give
something like this a trial period to see if it will work.''
   Lumber grader Al Esch is enthusiastic about being able to rotate
through three positions rather than sticking to one job. ``It's kind
of like being an immigrant in a new country,'' he said.
   Cheryl Howell, an 11-year veteran of the company, scored well on
a hand-eye coordination test, and was cross-trained to run
bark-stripping machinery and giant loaders in the yard. ``Before
it's done, I expect to know how to run everything in here,'' she
said.
   The first shift starts at 6:30 a.m., with workers and managers
joining in 10 minutes of exercises, followed by as much as 45
minutes of talk as the crew helps make management decisions. To
emphasize teamwork, Weyerhaeuser scrapped an old cleanup contract
and made everyone, including Dickey, responsible for keeping the
mill clean.
   Dickey is happy to get away from the old-style management
approach he calls ``big brain-little brain.''
   ``Generally you get dissatisfied employees because they are
starved for information,'' he said. ``We're giving them a big piece
of the operation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Timber-NewForestry     06-22 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Timber-New Forestry,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Techniques Approximate Old-Growth Forest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Timber-Economics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the rugged Illahe country where gold
miners still pan creeks running into the Rogue River, the Siskiyou
National Forest is trying techniques from a movement known as the
New Forestry.
   ``I see it as a major philosophical change rather than an
incremental change,'' said Forest Service scientist Jerry Franklin,
a leading spokesman for the movement. ``In terms of forestry
practice, it is revolutionary.''
   The New Forestry is gaining credibility in the midst of debate
over how much national forest can be logged while preserving the old
growth ecosystem. Pressure to log these forests has increased as
private lands have been overcut.
   ``We need to make this crisis the basis for not just resolving
the issue of how much old growth to leave, but perhaps more
important, how do we manage our commodity lands over the long
term,'' Franklin said.
   ``People are looking for ways to harvest the forest and provide
jobs, yet keep values that are important to the public,'' said Gold
Beach District Ranger Kathy Johnson. ``The public is interested in
old-growth forest, interested in the species that inhabit the old
growth forest.
   ``We think there is an opportunity for these New Forestry
techniques to provide that middle ground.''
   While most national forests in Oregon and Washington still are
developing 10-year management plans, the Siskiyou National Forest
has fit the New Forestry into its plan with a goal of balancing
production against a healthy forest.
   The key to New Forestry is to save more of the forest's parts so
what is left after logging has the best chance of surviving radical
climate changes a growing number of scientists predict will come
within the next 50 years.
   On the Siskiyou, the New Forestry is the basis for plans to start
logging in the next couple years the 7,100 acres known as the Illahe
Project, about 40 miles west of Grants Pass in southwestern Oregon.
   ``As we move out from that large block of old-growth forest into
areas previously harvested, we feather out the impacts,'' said
Johnson. ``We'll leave a certain amount of old-growth trees per
acre. That number increases as you get closer to the undisturbed
block of old growth forest.''
   That differs radically from traditional practice of clearcuts of
20 to 40 acres scattered throughout the forest in hopes of diluting
the impact.
   As scientists have learned more about how pieces of the forest
interact they have found that scattered clearcuts fragmented the
ecosystem, breaking it into pieces too small to function. They also
have found it valuable to leave corridors linking the pieces of
forest.
   Instead of clearcutting, New Foresters will leave dead trees and
some live trees standing to give animals places to feed and live.
Some logs will be left to rot and restore organic material to the
soil. Planners say the New Forestry will mean a 5 percent cut in
timber production over the 130-year harvest cycle.
   No decision has been made on how to approach slash burning, in
which debris left by clearcutting is burned to return minerals to
the soil, reduce fire danger, and make it easier to plant seedlings,
Johnson said.
   When it comes to replanting logged-over land, the New Forestry
suggests restoring the mix of species that were cut, to maintain a
diverse genetic base more able to withstand future climatic change,
rather than filling the land with one commercially valuable species
such as Douglas fir.
   Oregon State University forestry professor David Perry, also part
of the New Forestry movement, said, ``The point is that whatever you
do to take trees off it has got to be consistent with the
adaptations of the forest that have evolved over millenia to cope
with disurbance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DavisAppointment     06-22 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Davis Appointment,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Enterprise News Editor Named at AP Washington Bureau</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne Davis has been named news editor for
enterprise in the Washington bureau of The Associated Press.
   The appointment was announced Wednesday by Washington Chief of
Bureau Jon Wolman.
   Davis, 38, has been the supervisor of the AP's Washington news
report for afternoon newspapers. He previously was the AP's news
editor in Charleston, W.Va., and correspondent in Montpelier, Vt.
   Davis will coordinate enterprise coverage from the nation's
capital, including direction of AP's special assignment
investigative team. He also will direct planning for the afternoon
news report.
   A second Washington news editor, Carole Feldman, handles the
bureau's coverage of breaking news.
   Davis is a native of Dayton, Ohio, and a graduate of Dartmouth
College and Boston University. He joined the AP in Montpelier in
1978 after working for the Lebanon (N.H.) Valley News.
</TEXT>
