<FIRST>r a AM-BrushFires     06-22 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brush Fires,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Battle Blazes in 118-degree Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters sweating in 118-degree
temperatures Wednesday contained a 935-acre wildfire that briefly
threatened a national park.
   Residents in 85 homes were advised to evacuate at the height of
the fire near Joshua Tree National Monument, which is dedicated to
preservation of the gnarled desert trees, but only one building was
destroyed.
   ``The residents had cleared the brush around their homes and if
it hadn't been for that clearance the homes would definitely have
burned,'' said Deborah McClellan of the California Department of
Forestry.
   Temperatures reached above 100 inland and into the high 80s and
90-degree mark elsewhere, and gusty Santa Ana winds hampered
firefighters as they fought several other brush fires.
   Fire blackened 175 acres in the hills of San Clemente in southern
Orange County and 35 acres in Santa Clarita in northwestern Los
Angeles County. Firefighters earlier doused a 300-acre blaze in
Ventura County and a 115-acre fire in San Bernardino County.
   Northern California was also subject to the same hot, gusty winds
and low humidity which helped fan 2,600-acre wildfire 50 miles
northeast of San Francisco.
   Heavy smoke from the grass fire forced closure of a 10-mile
stretch of state Highway 12, authorities said. State Route 20 in the
Sierra was closed for 30 miles while firefighters tried to contain a
blaze on both sides of the highway.
   Two families were briefly evacuated from their homes in the
farming community of Denverton, said Marcia Chadbourne, spokeswoman
for the Solano County Office of Emergency Services.
   Other smaller fires were reported in the city of Vacaville, near
the retirement community of Rossmoor and in the Sunol-Castlewood
area near Pleasanton.
</TEXT>
