<FIRST>r a AM-DirectorsVote     06-22 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Directors Vote,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stage Directors Vote Down Contract But Continue to Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the directors union who work in most
of the country's regional theaters have rejected a final contract
offer from the theaters but will go into rehearsal with new
productions until Aug. 8.
   The contract offer was rejected Monday by members of the Society
of Stage Directors and Choreographers, which said it still was
willing to met with the League of Resident Theaters. The last
contract expired in April 1988 but was extended to May 26 of this
year.
   At the time, the union said it would withhold the services of its
members from plays that had not yet gone into rehearsal. It later
decided to allow its members to go into rehearsal until the August
date.
   Among the issues left unresolved are fees and union coverage in
smaller league theaters for the directors and choreographers.
</TEXT>
