<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Stockbridge250th     06-22 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stockbridge 250th,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Town Celebrates 250th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alice doesn't cook here anymore, but
this sleepy western Massachusetts town, captured in paint by Norman
Rockwell and in song by Arlo Guthrie, celebrates its 250th birthday
this weekend.
   Some things have changed since the days when Rockwell made
Stockbridge famous to Saturday Evening Post readers.
   Police Chief William J. Obanhein, whose visage Rockwell used as
the model of the ``perfect Secret Service man'' and whose
enforcement of the litter laws inspired Arlo Guthrie's ballad
``Alice's Restaurant,'' has retired. Alice Brock herself no longer
has a restaurant.
   Dr. Donald E. Campbell, captured by Rockwell while aiming a
hypodermic needle at a bare-bottomed youngster scrutinizing his
medical degrees, made his last house call in February on his 83rd
birthday.
   But the cat and dog fountain still stands. So does the horse
trough proclaiming ``utility is preferable to glamor'' and the line
of cane rockers on the veranda of the Red Lion Inn.
   Stockbridge's charm has proved irresistible to thousands of
tourists, who sometimes turn Main Street into a bumper-to-bumper
traffic jam.
   But for about two hours Saturday, Stockbridge will reclaim the
thoroughfare for a gala parade of brass bands, Boy Scouts, floats,
and more than 500 marchers.
   An old-fashioned picnic and fireworks also are planned.
   Asked to explain Stockbridge's appeal, Selectman Norman
Charbonneau responded: ``The people. And the uniqueness of the
area.''
   Guthrie agreed.
   ``I grew up in Stockbridge and have spent most of my life near
there,'' Guthrie said in a telephone interview from his nearby
Berkshire Hills home. ``Most of the people in town are wonderful and
fabulous ...
   ``It's a place that has retained its turn-of-the-century beauty
and sense of history. It's always accommodated a wide variety of
people _ artists, wealthy ambassadors, mobsters running booze during
Prohibition _ but it does so very reluctantly.
   ``And in some ways that's just fine. When I was young I didn't
understand that kind of small-town politics, but I've learned to
actually like it.''
   Guthrie, now the father of teenagers, said Stockbridge is ``more
a town for older folks,'' adding:
   ``I don't recall there being a whole lot to do for a young person
and there probably still isn't. I don't think my kids ever go to
Stockbridge.''
   But Guthrie, who will sing ``Alice's Restaurant'' at a July 4
concert in nearby Tanglewood, can still cackle gleefully in
anticipation of the town's reaction to his summer plans to market
T-shirts emblazoned ``with the Trail of the Garbage'' that will lead
tourists on the path of his crime.
   ``It will be sort of our own version of the Freedom Trail (in
Boston),'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
