<FIRST>r w PM-USMideast Bjt   06-22 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US Mideast, Bjt,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Skeptical of Soviet Proposal to Consult UN Council on Palestinian
Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is skeptical of a Soviet
proposal to seek advice from the United Nations Security Council's
permanent members on proposed elections among Palestinian Arabs on
the West Bank and in Gaza, administration sources say.
   ``We said we weren't interested,'' an official said late
Wednesday. The official, who spoke on condition that he not be
identified, did not reject the idea outright but said it would not
get anywhere ``as far as we're concerned.''
   The official said the proposal could complicate efforts to hold
elections to choose Palestinian representatives to negotiate
self-rule with Israel.
   ``It would only muddy the waters and distract from the
(elections) idea itself,'' the official said.
   Participation by the council members would guarantee the Soviet
Union a role that Israel fears would be used to the advantage of the
Arabs.
   The five members of the Security Council are the United States,
the Soviet Union, Britain, France and China.
   The Soviets, without committing themselves on Palestinian
elections, made their proposal during a two-day meeting in
Washington last week on the Middle East. It was one in a series of
conferences on various global problems arranged by the two
superpowers.
   The U.S. delegation was headed by John Kelly, assistant secretary
of state for the Near East, and Dennis Ross, head of the
department's policy planning staff. Vladimir Polyakov, senior expert
on the Middle East in the Soviet Foreign Ministry, led his
government's delegation.
   The Soviet idea was first disclosed in Thursday editions of The
Star Tribune of Minneapolis.
   The elections were proposed by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir as a way of breaking the stalemate between the Arabs and
Israel. The idea has qualified U.S. support, provided arrangements
are satisfactory to the Palestinians and the Arab countries.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has rejected Israel's offer
as a subterfuge to block the creation of a Palestinian state. But
the Bush administration is operating on the assumption that the
Shamir proposal still has a chance and in any event is the only
known vehicle for starting negotiations.
   For this reason, the official said, the Soviet proposal to
consult the U.N. Security Council members on a proper framework
received a skeptical U.S. response.
   The official said the Soviets did not endorse or reject Shamir's
proposition. As in the past, the Soviets said only that it was
``worthy of consideration.''
   In the past, as an inducement to Israel, the Soviets have said
they would be prepared to resume diplomatic relations once
negotiations began. But the official said the Soviets did not repeat
this offer in the Washington sessions.
   The Soviet Union broke relations with Israel in 1967 when Israel
defeated a combination of Arab countries in a six-day war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
