<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     06-22 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Confiscate Opposition Leaders' Coffee Plantations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cracking down on its critics, the
leftist Sandinista government says it has confiscated coffee
plantations and other property belonging to three opposition
business leaders.
   The three _ Nicolas Bolanos, Jaime Cuadra and Arnoldo Aleman _
were linked to the Superior Council of Private Enterprise, an
opposition group, and have been sharply critical of government
regulation of the coffee industry.
   The confiscation announcement Wednesday came three days after
coffee growers from all over the country decided to pull out of the
National Coffee Commission, calling the regulatory and
development-oriented panel useless.
   An order signed by Agriculture Development Minister Jaime
Wheelock and read on state-run Voice of Nicaragua radio declared the
properties of the three men of ``public utility and social
interest.'' It did not mention compensation.
   At a meeting Sunday in Matagalpa, 80 miles north of the capital,
coffee growers unanimously decided to withdraw from the National
Coffee Commission. They said the panel, made up of government and
private representatives, had ruined the industry.
   At the meeting, Bolanos accused the government of causing a
severe economic crisis through mismanagement, adding that only a
``government of national salvation'' replacing the Sandinistas could
bring Nicaragua out of recession.
   Coffee is one of Nicaragua's main export items and a principal
dollar-earner.
   Commenting on the confiscation order, the Voice of Nicaragua
accused leaders of the coffee growers of ``urging chaos, disorder,
price gouging, smuggling and speculation'' in the industry.
   The properties were ordered confiscated because these leadaers
``adopted irresponsible attitude that was fomenting anarchy in the
coffee industry at a time when the country is going through an
economic crisis.''
   In a speech Tuesday, President Daniel Ortega said ``all
anti-patriotic coffee growers will not receive a single cent'' in
credit from the State Development Bank.
   Ortega accused the growers of trying to sabotage an economic
austerity plan to reduce inflation, which last year topped 10,000
percent.
   As part of the plan, the Sandinista government earlier this week
ordered a 110 percent devaluation of the cordoba currency, which
sent prices of consumer goods and services skyrocketing.
   Enrique Bolanos, the brother of Nicolas Bolanos, called the
confiscations ``an act of vengeance by the Sandinistas over what
happened at the assembly in Matagalpa.''
   Enrique Bolanos, a former chairman of the Superior Council of
Private Enterprise, had some of his properties in the eastern
province of Masaya confiscated by the Sandinistas some years ago.
   In June 1988, the Sandinista government confiscated the San
Antonio sugar plantation and mills, one of Nicaragua's largest
industries. Sugar is also an important export item.
</TEXT>
