<FIRST>r a PM-Mummy     06-22 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mummy,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antique Dealer Sees Nothing Wrong with Trying to Sell Mummy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harlan Berk doesn't like to think of the dusty,
diminutive Egyptian mummy for sale at his downtown coin and antique
shop as a body.
   ``It's wrapped, and I try to think of it as a piece of
antiquity,'' said Berk, standing near the Plexiglas table that for a
month has been the resting place for the ancient remains of a woman.
``I try to look at the artwork on the outer wrappings and not focus
on the more macabre aspects.''
   He's asking $50,000 for it, adding, ``The market will tell me if
I'm right or wrong.''
   He hopes to sell the mummy to a museum or university.
   John Larson, archivist and Egyptologist at the University of
Chicago's Oriental Institute Museum, said it is illegal to export
mummies from Egypt without Egyptian government permission.
   But until well into this century, more ``laissez faire'' rules
applied.
   Berk, an antique dealer, said he bought the mummy from an
Illinois family a month ago, and considers himself free to sell it
at his shop. He said he was told that a family member brought the
mummy back from Egypt about 60 years ago.
   The mummy, at 4-feet, 1-inch, looks smaller than lifesize as it
rests on the table in a temperature-controlled room.
   On the front are remnants of the pinkish paint and gold leaf used
for decoration, with some pictures of Egyptian gods including Horus,
the god of heaven; and Osiris, the god of vegetation and later of
death.
   The pictures tell a story of life, death and rebirth _ paths the
long-dead woman's loved ones likely envisioned for her, Berk said.
   ``We do have respect for the individual, even though she's been
deceased for several thousand years.''
   Larson said he understands why some are disturbed by the sale of
human remains, particulary those of American Indians only a couple
generations old.
   ``I don't think any of us would want to see our grandparents'
bodies on display in a museum,'' he said.
   But the time and distance involved for the mysterious Egyptians
seem to make viewing them less distasteful.
   ``Letting the rest of the world study and enjoy these things only
creates greater appreciation of the Egyptian culture,'' Berk said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
