<FIRST>u a AM-RoseInvestigation 2ndLd-Writethru a0402 06-22 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rose Investigation, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0402,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rose's Handwriting Was On Betting Slips, Expert Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs to UPDATE with Rose comment. A longer version
moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handwriting expert examined betting slips
contained in baseball's report on Pete Rose and concluded that his
handwriting is on wager slips involving Cincinnati Reds' games, The
Associated Press learned Wednesday.
   In addition, The New York Times reported in Thursday's editions
that the slips have Rose's fingerprints on them as well as being in
his handwriting.
   ``Rose is claiming the sheets are forgeries,'' a federal law
enforcement official, who asked not to be identified, was quoted by
the Times as saying. ``He says he didn't write them but we're as
confident as we could be that he did.''
   The betting slips may support allegations that Rose, who holds
the major league baseball record for career hits, bet on his own
team. If proven, the offense would mean an automatic lifetime ban
from the game.
   Rose, who has sued Commissioner A. Bartlett Giamatti in state
court, has maintained he never bet on baseball. His lawyers also
have said that baseball's report on gambling allegations, written by
John M. Dowd, was based on hearsay and the word of convicted
criminals.
   However, a source familiar with baseball's investigation told The
Associated Press that the betting slips _ and the expert's
verification of Rose's handwriting on them _ give baseball tangible
evidence of Rose's betting. The handwriting expert was hired by
baseball as part of its investigation.
   Rose's lawyers sued Giamatti on Monday in attempts to block a
hearing next Monday with the commissioner in New York. Hamilton
County Common Pleas Judge Norbert Nadel will consider Rose's request
for a temporary restraining order during a hearing Thursday.
   The betting slips were revealed as part of Rose's lawsuit against
Giamatti and currently are in the possession of federal authorities
who have investigated Rose on tax matters.
   Rose's lawyers allege that Paul Janszen, who claims to have run
bets for Rose, stole three pieces of paper from the home of the
Reds' manager. The papers are described as the ``Pete Rose Betting
Sheets'' in Dowd's report.
   Baseball officials declined Wednesday to discuss the handwriting
analysis. Rose's lawyers indicated in their court filing that they
wanted an expert of their own to examine the sheets as well.
   Rose's lawsuit attacks the reliability of one of the betting
slips. The lawsuit says the first of the three sheets ``purports to
set forth a bet made on an April 9, 1987 game where Cincinnati
played at Montreal.''
   ``Incredibly, Dowd places significant emphasis on this sheet of
paper even though April 9 was an off-day for the Reds, and while
they played in Montreal the previous day, the game was in Cincinnati
and not in Montreal,'' the suit said.
   Rose's lawyers make no mention of the other two betting slips.
Lawyer Reuven J. Katz declined to answer any questions about the
betting slips or the handwriting analysis.
   Rose, speaking after the Reds lost a doubleheader to the Braves
in Atlanta, was informed of the reports on the handwriting and
fingerprints.
   ``That's not true,'' he said. ``I'm not commenting on anything
like that. Any other baseball questions? I thought it was in the
courts right now. I'll say it again, I'm not going to talk about
it.''
</TEXT>
