<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     06-22 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tightening of US-China Relations Won't Affect Grain Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. grain market will remain open to China
despite further tightening of relations in the wake of Beijing's
crackdown on pro-democracy forces, says Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter.
   ``I would not see that in any way affecting the present status of
agricultural transactions, either actual or potential,'' Yeutter
told reporters on Wednesday.
   Earlier, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said the United
States deeply regretted China's execution of three protesters but
added that no additional U.S. action is being contemplated.
   Baker said President Bush believes the sanctions already in place
are the proper response to the bloody crackdown by the Beijing
regime and the arrests of more than 1,600 demonstrators.
   Asked about Bush's order curtailing contacts by U.S. officials
with their Chinese counterparts and suspending all high-level
official visits to China, Yeutter said he didn't think that would
have much effect on the agricultural trade situation.
   ``Not in terms of commercial transactions between the two
countries,'' Yeutter said. ``It certainly could have some effect on
the conduct of government-to-government programs, of course,
including such issues as potential Chinese membership in the GATT
(General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade).''
   But while the commercial sales of U.S. grain to China are
expected to be unaffected by Bush's orders, Yeutter said programs
for extending further credit or subsidized sales of wheat to Beijing
are another matter.
   ``There is nothing in the president's statements to date, nor
will there be in the future, that will affect the fundamental
openness of the American marketplace,'' Yeutter said.
   However, when speaking about credit or the subsidy provisions of
the Export Enhancement Program for China, ``that's a separate
question'' and will be addressed as the situation requires, he said.
   China is expected to buy about $1.4 billion worth of U.S. farm
commodities in the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1, compared with
$613 million in 1987-88, according to Agriculture Department
estimates. That would compare with $7.9 billion forecast for Japan's
purchases, traditionally the largest, and $3.4 billion for the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers continue to be the major buyers of
agricultural land, according to a preliminary report by the
Agriculture Department.
   Farm owners and operators were involved in 57 percent of all
farmland purchases in the year that ended on Feb. 1, the report
said. Non-farmers participated in 29 percent of the sales. No
further breakdown was provided, however.
   About 87 percent of the farmland sold was expected to remain in
agricultural use at least five years after purchase, 2 percent in
forestry, and 11 percent in other uses.
   ``About two-thirds of the sales involved credit financing, down
substantially from 90 percent in the early 1980s when farmland
prices were their highest,'' the report said Wednesday.
   The report by the department's Economic Research Service said
farmland values through 1989 and early 1990 ``are expected to
continue increasing at an average rate slightly above this past
year's 6 percent.''
   Higher farm income, lower inflation-adjusted interest rates on
real estate loans, and moderate growth in inflation were cited as
reasons for the forecast. One report last month predicated that
farmland values could rise an average of 7 percent to 9 percent in
1989, compared with the 6 percent gain last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter has named
a career employee, Rolland E. (Bud) Anderson Jr., as head of the
Agriculture Department's Foreign Agricultural Service.
   Anderson, a native of Iona, Minn., and an agricultural economics
graduate of South Dakota State University, has more than 25 years
representing U.S. agricultural interests overseas, Yeutter said
Wednesday.
   ``His distinguished service qualifies him uniquely to lead FAS
during this important period of negotiation for reform in world
agricultural trade,'' Yeutter said.
   Anderson past assignments at U.S. embassies in Britain, the
Netherlands, New Zealand and West Germany.
</TEXT>
