<FIRST>r w PM-SpendingBill     06-22 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets' Programs Threatened as Emergency Bill Locked in Limbo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emergency spending bill Congress has been
debating since April has run into new trouble that threatens to
cause cuts in some veterans' programs as lawmakers prepare to leave
for their Fourth of July holiday.
   The House, in a surprise 218-201 vote, sent the bill back to
committee Wednesday. House leaders immediately asked the Senate to
hold new talks in search of a compromise acceptable to President
Bush and Democrats.
   With warnings of service cuts at veterans' hospitals and with the
Senate scheduled to begin a two-week recess on Friday, there was
increasing pressure on Congress to complete the task and leaders
searched for another way to keep veterans programs running while
other subjects continued in dispute.
   The key dispute is over an $821 million drug law enforcement
amendment which House Democrats were trying to push past the Senate
and President Bush, who has threatened a veto.
   By beating the $3.5 billion emergency spending bill in an early
procedural vote, Republicans were able to avoid voting on the
anti-drug spending, which is opposed by the president as wasteful
despite its political popularity.
   All but five Republicans voted against the bill and 52 Democrats
joined the GOP lawmakers, partly because of a Republican memo
highlighting pork barrel spending in the measure.
   The tally was a surprise defeat for the newly installed
Democratic leadership. Speaker Thomas S. Foley had confidently
predicted they would prevail.
   ``There are going to be times when the unexpected occurs. We will
have our ups and downs,'' said House Majority Whip William H. Gray
III, D-Pa., who said leaders had not pressured Democrats to keep in
line.
   The bill, under congressional budget rules, is supposed to
provide money only for ``dire emergencies'' which the government
must attend to before Sept. 30, the end of the current fiscal year.
   There is no disagreement over the largest single item, $1.2
billion for the Department of Veterans Affairs to cover a shortfall
in money for medical care, compensation and pensions, and in other
areas.
   Congressional leaders Wednesday night began exploring a
short-term bill for only veterans' programs to prevent major
disruptions, according to Democratic and Republican aides who spoke
on condition they not be identified.
   Final details were still being worked out, but such a bill would
carry the Veterans programs through July 22, giving Congress extra
time to iron out the drug and other disputes, the aides said.
   Nearly $900 million would be added to the federal guaranteed
student loan program, $342 million to cover the cost of fighting
last year's widespread forest fires, and $423 million for foster
care and adoption.
   The food stamp program would be increased $225 million, aid to
the unemployed $90 million, and refugee assistance 100 million.
   However, influential lawmakers also used the must-pass
legislation as a vehicle for cherished spending projects for their
constituents. For example, Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., included $75 million to rebuild a
radiotelescope in his state.
   The White House said Wednesday that Bush would sign the bill,
even with most of those constituent projects, if the drug money were
left out and some budget gimmicks which threatened future excess
spending were deleted.
   The gimmicks included moving the dates on paychecks for some
federal workers up one day, so the money would count against this
fiscal year instead of fiscal 1990. Another accounting change would
allow Congress to dodge agreed-upon spending limits for housing and
related agencies.
</TEXT>
