<FIRST>r i PM-Peru     06-22 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vargas Llosa Says He's Bowing Out of Presidential Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrated novelist Mario Vargas Llosa says he
is bowing out of the presidential race in this troubled Andean
nation, blaming political wrangling within the center-right
coalition that has been backing him.
   Vargas Llosa, the front-runner for March 1990 elections and among
Latin America's leading writers, made his decision known in a letter
to leaders of the two principal parties that comprise his Democratic
Front coalition.
   Also Wednesday, the government for the first time appealed for
foreign help to fight Maoist Shining Path guerrillas, whose latest
ambush the military said left 15 soldiers and 20 rebels dead in a
cocaine-producing jungle region.
   Vargas Llosa, 53, criticized the ``mediocre and petty'' motives
of some within his coalition to raise their own interests above
those of the nation.
   In his letter, read during a television broadcast, Vargas Llosa
said he was withdrawing because of the rivalry between former
President Fernando Belaunde Terry of the Popular Action Party and
former Lima Mayor Luis Bedoya of the Popular Christian Party.
   Belaunde and Bedoya had been unable to agree on how to proceed in
November municipal elections. Each party wanted to field its own
candidates, but Vargas Llosa argued that would divide the coalition.
   This ``has obliged me to renounce my candidacy for the president
of the republic,'' Vargas Llosa said.
   ``The collapse of the Front could open the door in our country to
totalitarian Marxism or a bloody military adventure,'' Vargas Llosa
wrote.
   Miguel Cruchaga, secretary general of the Liberty Movement, one
group in the coalition, said the decision appeared to be
``irrevocable,'' but added, ``We are going to mobilize public
opinion so that Vargas Llosa is a candidate.''
   Another leader of the Liberty Movement, speaking on condition of
anonymity, told The Associated Press that Vargas Llosa's resignation
appeared to be aimed at achieving undisputed leadership of the Front.
   Vargas Llosa, who once described himself as a ``specialist in
fantasies, in dreams,'' began his candidacy just 18 days ago in the
southern city of Arequipa, his birthplace.
   He was catapulted into the political arena after organizing a
huge rally against populist President Alan Garcia's plan to
nationalize the banks.
   Garcia's 4-year-old government is beset by an economic crisis,
triple-digit annual inflation and the Shining Path insurgency, now
in its ninth year and plaguing much of Peru.
   Garcia is prohibited by law from running for re-election and his
party's presidential candidate, former Finance Minister Luis Alva
Castro, is given little chance of winning because of voter
discontent with Garcia.
   Nearly 15,000 people have been killed in the conflict with
Shining Path, including rebels, police, soldiers, public officials
and highland peasants.
   In addition to the soldiers slain in the jungle, Shining Path
guerrillas this week assassinated the mayor of a northeastern
tourist town and killed five ex-soldiers traveling on a bus in the
Andean highlands, authorities said.
   The mayor, a member of Garcia's Aprista party, was the 46th
killed in the last two years by guerrillas.
</TEXT>
