<DOCNO> AP890622-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FHALosses     06-22 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FHA Losses,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Mortgage Program Losing Money, Adding to Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials say millions of dollars in
losses in the government's largest program for insuring home
mortgages are probably a ``temporary aberration'' that will improve
as the housing market shores up.
   The Federal Housing Administration, which insures $247 billion
worth of mortgages under its program for single-family homes, lost
$369 million in fiscal year 1988, which ended Sept. 30, and $149.5
million in the first six months of fiscal 1989, ended March 31,
according to the Department of Housing and Urban Development, the
FHA's parent agency.
   The net worth of the fund for the FHA's most popular insurance
program, the Mutual Mortgage Insurance Fund, fell from $3.4 billion
at the end of fiscal 1987 to about $2.8 billion at the end of 1988
and has declined below $2.7 billion so far in 1989, according to a
HUD financial officer who spoke Wednesday on condition of anonymity.
   The HUD official termed the losses a ``serious situation,'' but
said the fund was not in danger of exhausting its net worth, which
would require Congress to step in and rescue the self-supporting
program.
   ``There's nothing we see at this stage that would put us in that
position short of an absolutely severe regional downturn for a
sustained five-to-six-year period,'' the official said.
   Mortgage defaults, particularly in southwestern states suffering
from a depressed oil industry, have largely helped fuel the losses,
according to government officials.
   The official predicted continuing, although diminishing, losses
the rest of this year and in 1990, with profitability returning in
1991.
   Dennis J. Duquette of the General Accounting Office, Congress'
auditing wing, said GAO has examined the situation and ``I'm not so
sure the public needs to be overly concerned. We think it's probably
a temporary aberration.''
   He said FHA holdings are well diversified with mortgages from all
regions of the United States, both ailing and healthy.
   ``What we have here is not a savings and loan crisis,'' he said.
   A report in The New York Times, which quoted FHA officials as
saying the agency had only enough money to cover five months of
claims, is incorrect, said William Glavin, a HUD spokesman.
   However, Duquette said the losses are a matter of concern for
federal budget writers even if they do not threaten the mortgage
program's net worth.
   When the FHA has a cash outflow _ because it pays out more for
insurance claims than it collects in fees _ that adds to the budget
deficit. Conversely, when housing markets are hot and the FHA is
underwriting a lot of mortgages, its fee income jumps and it
actually helps to reduce the budget deficit. That happened in 1987
when the FHA had a profit of $101 million, according to the HUD
official.
   The GAO, which tracks FHA finances on a somewhat different
accounting basis from what the agency uses, showed a cash outflow of
$452 million in fiscal 1988, according to a report it issued last
month. The agency plans to issue a complete FHA audit for 1988 in
about a month, Duquette said.
   The GAO attributes the recent outflows to the cyclical nature of
the FHA's business, said Duquette.
   The residential housing market peaked nationally in 1986 and 1987
and so did insurance premium income. Unlike private mortgage
insurors, the FHA collects all of its premium up front in a single
fee, rather than collecting it monthly over the early years of a
mortgage.
   Also, defaults generally peak two to three years after a mortgage
is written so the FHA is just now experiencing the after effects of
its 1986-87 bulge in business, which fell by 50 percent between 1987
and 1988. Defaults, according to budget documents, are expected to
leap from $2.9 billion in 1986 to $6.6 billion this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-22 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its slide against the Japanese
yen on Thursday while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
inched down.
   The dollar ended the day's trading at 141.40 yen, down 3.55 yen
from Wednesday's 144.95-yen finish. The currency opened at 141.75
yen and fell further while fluctuating between 140.35 yen and 141.75
yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 111.81 points
Wednesday, lost 20.31 points, or 0.06 percent, finishing at
33,324.97. The index, which moved higher during the morning session,
suffered a setback in the afternoon.
   Dealers said the index fell as profit-takers sold issues, while
others stepped off to the sidelines in the absence of
market-affecting incentives.
   A trader said the market, which suffered consecutive losses last
week, has not fully recovered its strength.
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's decline followed
sharp overnight retreats on overseas markets.
   Minori Takeuchi, a dealer with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said the
majority of investors have lost confidence in the U.S. unit after
recent market movements.
   ``Some trust investment companies and foreign investors bought
the dollar when it approached 140.25 yen, but many participants sold
it to reduce the amount of the currency at hand,'' she said.
   Ms. Takeuchi said the market sold the dollar to avoid losing
profits, while watching how far the currency can fall to determine
the market direction.
   ``Nothing has changed in the U.S. economy, so the dollar would
eventually return to its previous level, somewhere around 130 yen,''
she said, ``The market thinks this is what the central bank also
intends.''
   Kyodo News Service quoted a central bank official as saying it is
``desirable'' for the yen to be a bit higher against the dollar to
forestall inflation.
   Attributing the yen's surge to dollar-selling by speculative
investors in the Middle East, Chicago and Asia, the official said
the yen's further rise will help correct the trade imbalance between
Japan and the United States.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly intervened in the market Thursday to
sell the U.S. currency to keep it lower against the yen. Neither the
action nor the amount were confirmed because the central bank does
not comment on its monetary activities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-22 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Industry Has Become Monopoly, Senator, Others Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few major cable television operators are now
the ``godfathers'' of the industry, exacting tribute from start-up
companies and withholding programming from rural viewers, a Senate
panel was told.
   An increasingly prosperous cable industry has raised prices and
stiff-armed microwave and home satellite dish companies that need
programming, while growing into a ``cable Cosa Nostra'' that can do
as it pleases without fear of regulation or competition, Sen. Albert
Gore, D-Tenn., said Wednesday.
   Since 1986, when a 1984 law deregulating cable was fully in
place, only about six new cable program networks have been
successful, and they all are at least partially owned by major cable
system operators, Gore said at a Senate communications subcommittee
hearing on ownership of the cable TV industry.
   In the wake of deregulation, ``We have witnessed an extraordinary
concentration of control and integration by cable operators and
program services, manifesting itself in blatantly anticompetitive
behavior towards those who would compete with existing cable
operators for the right to distribute services,'' Gore said.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>FBI Calls Violent Crime a Top Priority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is making violent crime a nationwide
investigative priority to counter a 40 percent increase in such
offenses in the 1980s, Director William S. Sessions says.
   Sessions told reporters that violent crime will rank with foreign
counterintelligence, terrorism, drugs, organized crime and white
collar crime as major priorities of the FBI.
   ``With the acknowledged 40 percent increase in violent crime, the
American public is understandably outraged by the growing disregard
for human life by criminals,'' Sessions said.
   While state and local police still have jurisdiction to
investigate the vast majority of violent crimes, Sessions said the
FBI can expand its role in this area.
   President Bush has asked Congress to appropriate $19.5 million to
hire 300 new FBI agents as part of his anti-crime package. If
approved, ``we expect to apply those resources directly to the
violent crime problem,'' Sessions said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>---</NOTE>
<NOTE>Federal Reserve Governor Heller Quits, Citing Salary</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H. Robert Heller, citing financial hardships in
living on his $82,500-a-year government salary, has announced his
resignation as one of the seven members of the Federal Reserve Board.
   An expert in international economics, Heller said Wednesday he
would return to California to become an executive vice president of
Visa International, the giant credit card company.
   In a meeting with reporters, he refused to disclose his exact
salary at Visa, saying only that it would be a ``pretty sizable''
increase that would represent a multiple of his government pay.
   Heller specifically cited Congress' rejection earlier this year
of a proposed federal pay raise as one factor in his decision to
leave. Under the proposal, which would have boosted congressional
salaries as well as those of top officials, the pay of a Federal
Reserve governor would have risen to $125,000.
   His resignation will give President Bush his first opportunity to
appoint someone to the Federal Reserve Board. The other six members,
including Chairman Alan Greenspan, were appointed by former
President Reagan.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Hoyer Elected to Democratic Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats have elected Steny Hoyer of
Maryland to their fourth-ranking leadership post, filling the last
major vacancy left from the shake-up that began with the ethics
probe of Speaker Jim Wright.
   Hoyer, 50, defeated Rep. Barbara Kennelly, D-Ct., 165-82, for
chairman of the House Democratic Caucus. Two votes were cast for
others during the closed meeting of all House Democrats.
   Hoyer has served as deputy chairman of the caucus for six months.
   The caucus chairman has few official duties other than to preside
over party meetings, but the post has been a launching pad to higher
positions.
   Hoyer succeeds Rep. William H. Gray III, D-Pa., who moved up to
majority whip last week. Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., resigned as
majority whip rather than face an inquiry into his personal
finances.
</TEXT>
