<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0537EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Mayors     06-22 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mayors,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Conference Ends on Discordant Note</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leader of the nation's mayors is
confident the Bush administration will pay attention to urban needs.
But her optimism wasn't shared by all her colleagues at the end of
their annual conference.
   Houston's Kathryn Whitmire, a Democrat who is mayor of the city
President Bush calls home, assumed the presidency of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors as the group ended its five-day annual meeting
Wednesday.
   The mayors adjourned on a discordant note with an unprecedented
floor fight over future leadership of the conference.
   The contest was decided along party lines with the selection of
Boston's Mayor Raymond Flynn, a Democrat and outspoken critic of the
Bush administration, as a future president of the conference.
   Whitmire maintained an optimistic and conciliatory tone toward
the administration following the meeting and praised Cabinet members
and other administration officials who spoke to the mayors.
   ``After hearing from them, we are optimistic that our issues will
be on their agenda,'' she said.
   But mayors called on the White House to provide support for
increased federal aid to cities and for urban problems of drugs,
crime, homelessness and poverty. The mayors asked Congress for an
immediate $822 million increase in the fight against drugs.
   ``Urban America has been neglected over the last eight years, and
the need is even greater than before,'' said Mayor Arthur Holland
Jr. of Trenton, N.J., outgoing president of the group.
   Flynn's election capped a partisan fight for the job that puts
him in line to be president of the organization _ and leading
spokesman for the nation's mayors _ in 1991.
   Whitmire voted against Flynn and in favor of a Republican William
Althaus, mayor of York, Pa., in a vote that was otherwise decided
largely along party lines.
   Flynn said that at issue in the dispute was whether mayors were
willing to ``have an aggressive voice'' against Bush's urban
policies.
   ``I don't think this is the time for mayors to sit back and just
go along, to say everything's all right in our cities,'' Flynn said.
``Everything is not all right in our cities. ... The Federal
government has walked away from our cities.''
   The mayors devoted scant attention during their meetings to the
unfolding scandals at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development _ the agency that handles most federal aid to cities.
The scandals include evidence of massive embezzlement and the
steering of millions of dollars in grants to projects based on
political favoritism during the Reagan administration.
   ``Frankly, our efforts with HUD will be primarily aimed at the
future rather than the past,'' Whitmire said. ``We do believe it is
the duty of Mr. Kemp (Secretary Jack Kemp) to address the scandals.
... Our goal will not be to chastise someone now gone from the
agency about what was done or not done last year.''
   The conference approved unanimously a policy statement calling on
the administration and Congress to raise federal taxes to reduce the
deficit and to finance greater spending on urban problems.
   The mayors also called for an outright ban on possession, as well
as manufacture and sale, of ``military-type'' semiautomatic assault
weapons. That goes far beyond Bush's ban on the importation of
foreign-made assault weapons and would, if it became law, render
illegal thousands of such weapons now owned by Americans.
   The mayors' resolutions become the new policies that will guide
conference lobbying in Congress.
   They approved a resolution saying mayors ``deplore'' recent
Supreme Court decisions that are weakening affirmative action
programs and ``making it more difficult to ensure equal
opportunities in employment for all Americans.''
   Other resolutions called for tougher action against drugs,
poverty, homelessness and AIDS. But in an earlier committee, mayors
deleted a proposal by Flynn to encourage free distribution of
needles to drug addicts as a way to reduce spread of AIDS.
</TEXT>
