<HEAD>Still More Rain in East; Record Cold, Snow in Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain continued to soak much of the East today, worsening flooding
in several states, while a summer chill brought record low
temperatures and snow to the Rockies.
   Showers and thunderstorms reached from Ohio and western New York
state across western Pennsylvania, West Virginia, the Carolinas,
Georgia, Alabama and Florida. West Union, W.Va., got a soaking as 1}
inches of rain fell in 25 minutes.
   Showers also covered eastern New York state, eastern Pennsylvania
and New Jersey.
   Flood watches were posted in Alabama, Georgia, the Carolinas and
Virginias, Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania and New York.
   Overnight temperatures tied or set record lows in Wyoming and
Colorado. It was 44 degrees in Colorado Springs on Wednesday
evening, 2 degrees below the record for the date set in 1982. Early
today, Casper, Wyo., tied its record low for the date of 40 degrees
set in 1957.
   Light snow was falling by midnight over parts of the Colorado
mountains, with 8 inches of new snow at Echo Lake. Roads were icy in
come moutain areas.
   Rain also was scattered across parts of Colorado and New Mexico.
   Thunderstorms covered much of the Plains early today. Rain
extended from southeast Minnesota across western Iowa, eastern
Nebraska, Kansas, western Oklahoma and the Oklahoma and Texas
panhandles. Storms dropped about an inch of rain at Omaha, Neb., and
small hail at Great Bend, Kan.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in the upper Mississippi Valley and lower Missouri Valley, the
northern and central Plains, Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle and
eastern New Mexico. Showers also were forecast for the northern
Rockies. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast during
the afternoon and evening from the upper Ohio Valley through the
Appalachians and central Gulf Coast to the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast.
   Highs were expected to be in the 70s and 80s across much of the
nation; in the 60s from the northern Rockies through the upper and
middle Missouri Valley into western and northern Minnesota; in the
90s across much of Florida, from the lower Mississippi Valley
through Texas, the southern Rockies, much of New Mexico and Arizona
into interior California and south central Oregon; and to near 115
degrees from the Desert Southwest into the valleys of California.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 32 degrees at Yellowstone,
Wyo., to 89 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 70 foggy; Buffalo 68 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 72 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 69 fair;
Cleveland 68 partly cloudy; Detroit 64 foggy; Miami 78 partly
cloudy; New York 70 foggy; Philadelphia 74 foggy; Pittsburgh 68
cloudy; Portland, Maine 64 foggy; Washington 72 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 47 fair; Chicago 71 partly cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 78 fair; Denver 48 rain; Des Moines 68 cloudy; Indianapolis 68
fair; Kansas City 73 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 66 showers;
Nashville 67 fair; New Orleans 75 fair; St. Louis 76 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 62 windy; Anchorage 54 fair; Las Vegas 76
fair; Los Angeles 65 foggy; Phoenix 89 fair; Salt Lake City 50 fair;
San Diego 63 foggy; San Francisco 70 fair; Seattle 60 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 72 partly cloudy; Toronto 66 showers.
