<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SteinbeckHaunt     06-22 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Steinbeck Haunt,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Author's Admirers Gain Victory in Fight to Save Haunt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preservationists and admirers of author
John Steinbeck have won a temporary victory in their battle to save
a hotel he once frequented.
   Monterey County Superior Court Judge John Phillips ruled
Wednesday the city failed to obtain an adequate environmental impact
report before ordering the Cominos Hotel torn down.
   The building, built in 1874 and remodeled in 1919, was visited
often and mentioned in several works by Steinbeck, famous for such
books as ``The Grapes of Wrath'', ``East of Eden'' and ``Of Mice and
Men.''
   The city decided in April to raze the hotel for a parking lot,
office building and museum.
   But the Monterey County Historical Society sued, saying the
environmental analysis was deficient. The group actively promotes
Steinbeck's connections to the agricultural region.
   Preliminary studies indicate it would cost $4.5 million to
refurbish the hotel.
   Steinbeck, who won the Nobel and Pulitzer prizes, died in 1968.
</TEXT>
