<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--SpecialOlympianDies     06-22 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Special Olympian Dies,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Olympian Collapses, Dies After Winning Swimming Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Special Olympics athlete collapsed and
died after winning a swimming race.
   Edward Richardson, 42, had just won a 25-meter backstroke race
Wednesday when he collapsed in about 4{ feet of water at the
University of Florida. He was pronounced dead about 45 minutes later
at Shands Hospital.
   Richardson, who had Down's syndrome, was under water for no more
than 30 seconds before volunteers pulled him out and attempted to
revive him, said Susan Eisen, a volunteer timer.
   No autopsy is planned and the cause of death has been listed as
an ``apparent heart attack complicated by drowning,'' said Angie
Tipton, spokeswoman for the University Police Department.
   Richardson, of nearby Evinston, had won gold medals at the state
level in other Special Olympics races, she said. ``He was quite a
competent swimmer,'' she said.
   ``He'd been practicing for this for months.''
</TEXT>
