<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     06-22 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panicked Families Crowd Airport in Soviet Desert Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panicked families are crowding the airport of a
Soviet Central Asian desert town where four people have been killed
in ethnic violence, Pravda reported today.
   Two people were hospitalized with gunshot wounds after the unrest
in the Kazakhstan town, Novy Uzen, spread Wednesday to settlements
40 miles away, the Communist Party newspaper said.
   ``The Novy Uzen airport is packed with families'' trying to leave
town, and threats by ``inciters'' of further violence are keeping
the 56,000 residents near the Caspian Sea on edge, Pravda reported.
   Most of the violence in Novy Uzen has been aimed at settlers from
the Caucasus Mountains region, who make up more than a third of the
town's population.
   Native Kazakhs complain the Caucasus settlers dominate the oil
industry jobs on which the town depends and receive preferential
treatment in housing and other benefits.
   The settlers have also set up private businesses that are accused
of selling supplies in the isolated town for exorbitant prices, the
newspaper Izvestia said.
   The Novy Uzen violence, which began last weekend, was the third
outbreak of ethnic rioting fueled by economic hardship in Soviet
Central Asia in the last six weeks.
   In the worst of the violence, about 100 people were killed in the
Fergana Valley of eastern Uzbekistan in attacks by ethnic Uzbeks
against the Meskhi Turkish minority, which was forcibly resettled
there by Josef Stalin in 1944.
   In Novy Uzen, more than 50 police and soldiers were reported to
have been injured while restoring order after a fight at a dance
hall erupted into four days of brawling and arson. Hundreds of
Interior Ministry soldiers were sent in, and a 9 p.m.-6 a.m. curfew
was imposed.
   Izvestia said authorities have ordered increased security for the
town's water, sewer and electricity systems, as well as food stores
and a bread factory _ all targets of rioters who want to ``be able
to dictate their own conditions to the authorities.''
   Pravda said that although Novy Uzen was quiet Wednesday,
disturbances spread to Munaishi, where two people were hurt, and to
Zhetibai, where about 500 people demonstrated.
</TEXT>
