<FIRST>r i PM-China-Diplomats     06-22 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Diplomats,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministry Calls on Defecting Diplomats to Return</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry today urged Chinese diplomats
who defected following the crackdown on dissent to return home,
saying they were led astray by ``malicious instigation.''
   Spokeswoman Li Jinhua said some Chinese diplomats in embassies
and consulates abroad defected because ``they're far away from the
motherland and don't know the truth.''
   She said they had been ``disturbed by malicious instigation.
   ``We expect that they will come back to China and their families
and friends also hope they will come back. We have already contacted
relevant countries and hope they will provide help in dealing with
the relevant matter.''
   More than 20 Chinese diplomats have left their posts or sought
political asylum in the United States, Canada, Australia, Britain,
Japan and other countries following the June 3-4 military assault in
Beijing to disperse pro-democracy protesters and subsequent roundup
of anti-government activists.
   The government variously says 200-300 people, mostly soldiers,
died in the crackdown; Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence
reports indicate up to 3,000 may have died.
