<FIRST>r a PM-Who'sTour     06-22 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Who's Tour,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Who Launches Reunion Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XGLF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENS FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Who _ the guitar- and drum-smashing
rock band that once sneered, ``Hope I die before I get old'' _
launched its 25th anniversary tour, and nothing more than a
tambourine got broken.
   The graying rockers performed ``My Generation'' and 39 other
songs at a small arena here for an audience of about 5,000 people,
some of whom were not even born when the anthem of youthful bravado
was recorded in 1966.
   The Who is just one of a spate of old rock bands hitting the road
this year to coax Baby Boomers back into stadiums and concert halls.
   Ringo Starr, the Doobie Brothers and Allman Brothers will tour
this summer, with the Rolling Stones and Paul McCartney following
this fall.
   The Who splintered after a ``farewell tour'' in 1982-83 but
regrouped for its 25th anniversary.
   Dressed in a baggy gray suit with his hair in a ponytail, Pete
Townshend leaped in the air and banged power chords on his guitar
with his trademark windmill motion. But in a concession to age and
hearing damage caused by years of loud music, Townshend strummed an
acoustic guitar for most of the show.
   Singer Roger Daltrey spun his microphone in the air and banged
two tambourines together until one shattered and he had to toss it
aside.
   The Who performed a series of their hits during the more than
three-hour show, including ``Won't Get Fooled Again,'' ``Who Are
You,'' ``Baba O'Reilly,'' ``Substitute'' and ``Can't Explain.''
   Townshend played three songs from his upcoming album, ``The Iron
Man.'' Bassist John Entwistle also performed solo.
   The three surviving band members were supplemented by 11
musicians, including a five-piece horn section. The Who's original
drummer, Keith Moon, died in 1978.
   Except for two indoor performances of ``Tommy'' in New York and
Los Angeles, the summertime tour is set for outdoor stadiums.
   The band made a last-minute exception in Glens Falls, an upstate
New York city of 20,000 where The Who rented the civic center for
nearly two weeks of rehearsal.
   The tour has been criticized by many in the music community, who
note that Townshend, Entwistle and Daltrey haven't enjoyed the same
financial success with individual tours and records as they did with
The Who.
   The cover of the current Musician magazine features a drawing of
the band members as the centerpiece of a dollar bill.
   The tour moves to Toronto, the city that hosted the last
performance of The Who before their breakup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ScotusRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0487 06-22 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0487,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Speech Advocates Back Court Ruling on Flag-Burning</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 11-12, Robert Spanogle, with reaction.</HEAD>
<HEAD>^With PM-Old Glory Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Free speech advocates are hailing a Supreme
Court ruling in a Texas flag-burning case they say fortifies and
expands constitutional protection for political dissent.
   But conservatives and veterans groups expressed anger and sadness.
   The justices, by a 5-4 vote Wednesday, said burning the American
flag as a form of political protest is protected by the
Constitution's free speech guarantees.
   The court said Texas authorities violated a protester's rights
when they prosecuted him under a state law barring desecration or
destruction of the flag. The justices upheld a lower court ruling
that overturned the protester's conviction, one-year prison term and
$2,000 fine.
   The federal government and every state except Alaska and Wyoming
have similar laws against flag-burning.
   Professor Martin Redish of Northwestern University said the
ruling means ``the government cannot censor a viewpoint based on its
offensiveness.''
   He said he was delighted, and somewhat surprised, that Justices
Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy _ both appointed to the high
court by former President Ronald Reagan _ voted with the majority.
   ``I've been called an extremist for free speech. I'm in good
company now,'' Redish said.
   Arthur J. Kropp, president of the liberal People for the American
Way, said, ``As a nation, we are strong enough to withstand the pain
of seeing our flag burned. What we could not withstand is seeing the
First Amendment cast aside out of a misguided sense of nationalism.''
   But H.F. ``Sparky'' Gierke, national commander of the American
Legion, said, ``As a veteran my first reaction to the decision is
one of anger. Then my anger turns to extreme sadness. This is a sad
day for the United States of America.''
   Robert Spanogle, national adjutant of the American Legion, said
on ``CBS This Morning'' that all Americans should fly the flag and
wear flag lapel tacks ``as a sign of positive protest'' of the
decision.
   ``We're going to seek legislation, and if it comes to the fact of
seeking a constitutional amendment to make desecration of the United
States flag a crime, we'll do that, too,'' he said.
   Alan Slobidin of the conservative Washington Legal Foundation
said, ``for anyone who loves the flag this is an outrage ... a kick
in the teeth.''
   Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., also criticized the
ruling.
   ``In my view, the Constitution, for which millions of men and
women have given their lives to defend, holds no guarantee for
desecration, no basic right to deface,'' he said.
   The closely watched case echoed public-patriotism themes from
last year's presidential campaign and called to mind the political
turmoil during the Vietnam war.
   George Bush, campaigning for the presidency in 1988, attacked
Democratic opponent Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts for
vetoing legislation to require that public school teachers lead
their classes in the Pledge of Allegiance. Dukakis said the
legislation was unconstitutional, and he said he resented Bush's
questioning of his patriotism. Both men made heavy use of American
flags during campaign appearances.
   During the height of U.S. involvement in the fighting in Vietnam
some two decades ago, draft card burning and flags bearing peace
symbols were common forms of protest.
   While Wednesday's ruling broadly limits the power of the state
and federal governments to restrict even offensive dissent, the
decision does not condone flag-burning that could incite a riot.
   The court said there are laws against breaches of the peace that
outlaw incitement to riot, and that those statutes are not affected
by the ruling.
   The central figure in the case was Gregory ``Joey'' Johnson of
New York City, a member of the Revolutionary Communist Youth Brigade.
   He was convicted of flag-burning during a 1984 rally at the
Republican National Convention in Dallas in which protesters
chanted, ``America, the red, white and blue. We spit on you.''
   The demonstration ended with the marchers pouring lighter fluid
on and igniting an American flag that authorities said was taken
from a pole outside a bank building.
   ``I think it's an important victory ... that the Supreme Court
was forced to back off,'' Johnson said. ``I don't consider myself an
American,'' Johnson added. ``I'm not. I'm an internationalist, a
proletarian internationalist.''
   The Korean War veteran who scooped up the fragments of the flag
said he is grieved that the conviction has been overturned. Dan
Walker, 61, a West Point graduate, said the burning was uncalled for
and ``I still do not know what they were protesting.'' He buried
what was left of the flag according to Army regulations and received
a letter of thanks from President Reagan.
   In another important test of the rights of free expression, the
court limited states' power to punish the news media for reporting
truthful, legally obtained information.
   By a 6-3 vote, the court threw out a $97,500 award against a
newspaper, won by a rape victim whose name the paper had published.
   In other decisions Wednesday, the court:
   _Unanimously ruled that a federal law allowing public scrutiny of
governmental advisory groups does not apply to the American Bar
Association's role in picking federal judges.
   _Voted, 5-4, to give railroads more leeway to sell off rail lines
without first entering into collective bargaining about the effect
of the sale.
   _Made it easier, in a case involving a dispute between the
Internal Revenue Service and the Church of Scientology, for the
government to conduct tax-fraud investigations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
