<FIRST>u i PM-Berlin-Release 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin-Release, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0520,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Releases Man After Strong Allied Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to RECAST lede and CORRECT spelling of man
to Notev sted Notve. Pickup 4rd graf, `The guards...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An East German man who swam across a river to West
Berlin only to be dragged back by border guards has been freed by
East German authorities, Allied officials said today.
   The man was turned over to Western authorities one day after the
three Western Allies _ the United States, France and Britain _
threatened to cut off travel by politicians and diplomats to
communist East Germany unless the 21-year-old Martin Notev was freed.
   The Allies said the Notev had swum the Spree River and reached
West Berlin territory when he was seized by border guards on Feb. 14
and dragged back to East Germany by his hair.
   The guards returned Notev to East Berlin and he was later
sentenced to four years in prison. In a statement today, British
military authorities said Notev was released and reported to a
refugee camp in West Berlin on Wednesday.
   The Allies had called the East German guards' action a
kidnapping. They said Notev had already reached West Berlin
territory after swimming the Spree River, which separates communist
East Berlin from West Berlin.
   Notev and two friends used a truck to crash through border
barriers on the communist side of the river, jumped into the river
and swam to the Western side.
   The two friends made it safely up the bank but guards from a
patrol boat seized Notev as he was trying to get over the bank. The
guards pulled at Notev's hair and took him away, according to the
Allies.
   The Allies also said one East German guard violated Western
territory by stepping on the bank.
   Dramatic photographs in West Berlin newspapers showed Notev
trying to pull himself over the top of the steep bank as the guards
from the boat were dragging him away.
   The incident occurred near the old Reichstag building, in the
British sector of West Berlin. The Spree is in East Berlin territory.
   Tuesday's Allied protest, which West German newspapers described
as unusually strong, followed several unsuccessful attempts to win
Notev's release.
   The Allies said East Germany had failed to even acknowledge the
incident, while Soviet authorities said they were not responsible.
   Officials from the European Economic Community had also appealed
on Notev's behalf and his case had been raised by Britain and the
United States in talks with Soviet officials, Allied sources said.
</TEXT>
