<HEAD>Man Convicted of Murdering Wife, Stepdaughter; Evidence Included
Tape</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to ADD quotes from tape; PICKS UP 5th graf
pvs, `Defense attorney ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of murdering his wife and
11-year-old stepdaughter, who taped the slayings on a cassette
recorder later found tucked between the pillows on her bed.
   Prosecutor Tom Hannis said he will seek the death penalty against
Alfred Lavers at sentencing July 20.
   A jury deliberated 2{ hours Wednesday before convicting Lavers,
48, of first-degree murder in the 1988 stabbings of his wife, Mary
Lavers, and stepdaughter, Jennifer Burns.
   The 90-minute tape, played for the jury Monday, culminated in
Mrs. Lavers' screams.
   ``I'm dying. ... Please help me,'' she was heard saying.
   ``You're bleeding just like a stuck hog. I love you so mcuh,''
her husband replied.
   Defense attorney Roland J. Steinle contended Lavers stabbed both
in a rage. If jurors had believed there was no premeditation, they
could have convicted him of second-degree murder or manslaughter,
which carry lesser sentences.
   The couple had quarreled throughout the day about their
deteriorating one-year marriage. The fight spun out of control when
Mrs. Lavers refused to go to bed with her husband.
   In his closing argument, Hannis held up the girl's picture and
said: ``I had some help from Jennifer Burns. She put the tape in the
tape recorder and turned it on.''
   ``I sat and listened to the tape,'' said Judy Walker, a sister of
Mrs. Lavers. ``And I was warned ahead of time that it was going to
be gruesome. And I cried when it was played. We all cried.''
