<HEAD>Young to Pay $200 Weekly to Support Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Coleman A. Young has agreed to pay $200 a
week to support the 6-year-old son he refused to acknowledge until
blood tests proved he was the father.
   The settlement filed Wednesday provides Annivory Calvert, mother
of Joel Loving, with support payments retroactive to Jan. 27, the
day she filed a paternity suit, said her lawyer, Noel Keane.
   The payments will continue until Joel turns 18 in 2000, when
Young, now 71, will be 82.
   Still to be determined is whether Young must pay support dating
to his son's birth in 1982, an amount Keane said would be at least
$50,000.
   Calvert, 34, a former city administrator, left Detroit earlier
this year to become public works director in Fontana, Calif.
   Lawrence Charfoos, an attorney for Young, said the mayor ``will
meet his financial commitment. He's starting to do that and he will
do it in the future.''
   He said Young had no comment on the matter.
   The agreement also says Young will be listed as Joel's father on
the birth certificate, Keane said.
