<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Katyn     06-22 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Katyn,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Media Carry Faculty Statement on Katyn Blame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government-run media today published a
university resolution blaming the Soviet secret police for the
massacre of Polish soldiers at Katyn in World War II.
   It was the most direct statement of blame reported by the
official press.
   The Warsaw University faculty condemned what it called efforts to
obscure ``the basic fact known in Poland and the world for nearly
half a century. Namely: the Katyn crime committed on thousands of
Polish officers interned by the Soviet Union in 1939 was committed
by NKVD (Soviet secret police) bodies.''
   The resolution was carried by the official PAP news agency and
was published in the daily pro-government Catholic Slowo Poszechne
newspaper.
   In recent months, the Polish government has moved toward
rejecting the official version of the Katyn massacre, which says the
4,200 officers were shot by the Nazis in 1941 after Germany invaded
the Soviet Union.
   Although discussion of Katyn was taboo in Poland for four
decades, most Poles and historians in the West believe the slayings
were carried out by the Soviet secret police on Josef Stalin's order
in 1940 while the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany were allied.
   The officers, the cream of Polish society called up from the
reserves and interned by the Soviets shortly after the outbreak of
the war, were shot in the back of the head and dumped in mass graves
in Katyn, near the Soviet city of Smolensk.
   The fate of another 10,000 officers, interned at two other Soviet
camps, has never been revealed. They are also presumed to have been
executed.
   The Polish side of a joint commission investigating ``blank
spots'' in Polish-Soviet history has reported the tentative
conclusion of Soviet responsibility for Katyn, and a government
spokesman has said there is circumstantial evidence.
   But there has been no direct statement assigning blame and no
response from the Soviet side of the joint commission.
   The resolution said, ``The maneuvers around the Katyn crime
consist in attempts to create a false appearance that despite
obviousness, the Katyn case is very unclear and calls for long-term
research.
   ``Unfortunately, the Polish-Soviet commission of Communist Party
historians is also being used as a tool in these maneuvers.''
   The unanimous faculty statement critcized efforts to ``create a
cover and an excuse for all those who for nearly half a century have
tried to falsify the truth about Katyn, thus becoming the supporters
of the terrible crime.''
   The official media in Poland have written about Katyn this year,
and in April, soil from the Katyn graves was sent to Poland by an
official delegation.
   The official tablet on a Katyn monument in Warsaw that blamed the
Nazis has been removed.
</TEXT>
