<HEAD>Plans for Historic Carwash Still High and Dry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 1950s-era carwash with a thing that looks
like a tripod made of boomerangs on its roof lost a bid to be
designated a cultural landmark.
   The Cultural Heritage Commission voted 2-1 Wednesday to declare
the carwash with its eye-catching, 55-foot tower the official
Gateway to the San Fernando Valley and a symbol of Los Angeles' love
affair with the automobile.
   But the carwash needed three votes to become a cultural landmark.
The panel will vote again after a fourth commissioner is confirmed
by the City Council.
   Homeowners are seeking landmark status for the carwash and the
adjoining '50s-style Tiny Naylor's restaurant. Such a declaration
delays demolition for a least a year.
   A developer wants to tear down both buildings and put up a $15
million mini-mall.
   ``In this crazy world of Los Angeles, the carwash gives you 15
minutes to stop and smell the roses, to watch the suds,'' said Jack
McGrath, organizer of the save-the-carwash campaign.
   ``It's a chance for dad and son to talk a little bit while their
car is going through the wash.''
   Developer Ira Smedra, who wants to build the mini-mall, called
the monument idea frivolous. ``This is a terrible abuse of the
system,'' he said.
