<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-US     06-22 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-US,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Reportedly Rejects Mediation Bids with Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has rejected several
recent attempts by third countries to mediate with Washington,
Iran's foreign minister was quoted as saying today.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati's interview in the
Dubai-based Arabic newspaper Al-Bayan was published as Iran's
parliament speaker visited the Soviet Union, the highest ranking
Iranian official to do so in a decade.
   Velayati said Iran was interested in good foreign relations as
long as that doesn't compromise its independence, Al-Bayan reported.
   ``Several countries have approached us for some kind of mediation
with the United States. But we reject that as the Islamic Republic
in Iran has never welcomed such mediations,'' Velayati was quoted as
saying in the interview in Tehran. The newspaper did not say when
the interview occurred.
   Velayati refused to give names of the countries which approached
Tehran for mediation nor to elaborate on relations with Washington,
said the paper.
   He said Iran wanted good relations with other nations, but only
if that doesn't require sacrifices of Islamic principles and
independence.
   He did not say in what way having relations with Washington would
be compromising for Iran. Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who died of a
heart attack June 3, repeatedly referred to the United States as the
``Great Satan.''
   Relations were severed in 1979 after students declaring
allegiance to Khomeini's Islamic revolution seized the U.S. Embassy
and held 52 Americans hostage for 444 days.
   Velayati said Iran wants to improve relations with the Soviet
Union and Arab states on basis of mutual respect among neighbors.
   Iran's professed goal of spreading its Islamic revolution
strained its relations with several Arab nations.
   ``The Soviet Union is our neighbor, and we want to expand
bilateral ties with Moscow on basis of friendship and good
neighborly relations and not on the base of scaring others,'' he
said.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani has been in Moscow since
Tuesday to sign a number of economic and commercial agreements.
   Velayati said his country hoped to have good relations with Arab
states.
   ``At present we have strong relations with a number of Arab
states, but we have problems with others, and normalizing relations
with these depends on the ability of those countries to solve these
major problems,'' he said. Velayati said the problem nations include
Egypt and Saudi Arabia.
   Iran has condemned Egypt for signing a peace treaty with Israel.
   Saudi Arabia broke ties in 1988, and strains persist with Tehran
especially over the restrictions the kingdom imposed on the number
of pilgrims to the annual Hajj to Mecca and Medina.
</TEXT>
