<FIRST>r a PM-SatelliteDamage     06-22 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satellite Damage,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonnell Douglas: Human Error Not Likely in Satellite Mishap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A failed crane badly damaged a $70
million satellite that was to have beamed TV signals to India, says
McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   The accident Monday, in which a heavy hook fell on the satellite
and destroyed an essential antenna, delayed McDonnell Douglas' plans
to be the first American aerospace company to put a commercial
payload into orbit.
   ``It looks like what happened is the cable simply snapped. It was
not lifting anything at the time, and there is no indication of
operator error,'' McDonnell Douglas spokeswoman Sheila Carter said
Wednesday.
   The crane had been used to lift the satellite 116 feet to the top
of a Delta 2 rocket at a launch pad McDonnell Douglas leases from
the Air Force.
   Officials were still figuring the damage to the INSAT-1D
satellite, designed to transmit voice and data, weather pictures and
TV broadcasts to 700 million people on the Indian subcontinent.
   The launch, scheduled for June 29, has been postponed until the
satellite is repaired or replaced by its manufacturer, Ford
Aerospace.
