<SECOND>PM-Airplane Poisoning,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Passengers Suffer Food Poisoning After In-Flight Snack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet made an emergency landing when 98
of the 139 passengers suffered dizziness and nausea after eating a
snack aboard the plane, and seven people remained hospitalized
today, officials said.
   None of the airliner's eight crew members ate the food, said
Dareen Khan, an Emirates Airline spokesman.
   The A-300 Airbus was en route Wednesday from Dhaka, Bangladesh to
Dubai, in the United Arab Emirates, when the people fell ill after
eating a light meal consisting of chicken, Dareen said.
   The meal was catered in Karachi by the Midway Hotel run by
Pakistan International Airlines, he said. Samples of the food on
board were sent to laboratories to be examined.
   Medical officials said the seven passengers still hospitalized
suffered from dehydration but none was seriously ill.
   Fifty-two passengers spent the night in hospitals but 45 were
released today, Dareen said.
   Most of the affected passengers were Bangladeshis, he said.
