<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0504 06-22 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Official Lauds Talks with Gorbachev, Extends Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Rafsanjani extending his
visit, move other comments higher. Pickup 13th pvs, ``Rafsanjani invited.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The highest-ranking Iranian official to visit
Moscow since the 1979 Iranian revolution said today that talks with
Mikhail S. Gorbachev had set once-stormy relations on a path of
close cooperation.
   ``The optimism that we had before the meetings has been totally
justified,'' the official, Hashemi Rafsanjani, told a news
conference after two days of talks with the Soviet leader.
   Asked about a recent series of bloody clashes in traditionally
Moslem Soviet Central Asia, part of which borders Iran, Rafsanjani
said that his country would not interfere in Soviet internal affairs.
   But he added, ``We consider Mr. Gorbachev has a long way to come
in providing freedoms and people's participation in the democratic
process.'' He did not elaborate.
   On other issues, Rafsanjani:
   _said the late Ayatollah Khomeini's order stands for the killing
of Salman Rushdie, British author of the novel ``The Satanic
Verses,'' which many Moslems consider blasphemous. Khomeini's
judgment was based on Islamic law and ``this is not the kind of
prescription that can be reversed. There is no one in Iran who could
reverse it.''
   _accused the United States of unspecified ``plots and
conspiracies'' against Iran when asked about the possibility that
relations would improve after Khomeini's death.
   _said Afghans must be free to resolve their differences without
outside interference after the withdrawal of Soviet soldiers from
their country more than four months ago.
   Rafsanjani originally was expected to leave today but extended
his visit. Tass reported that he left for Leningrad after the news
conference.
   Teheran Radio, monitored in London, said Rafsanjani also planned
to visit the southern republic of Azerbaijan, whose population is
predominantly Shiite Moslem. Iran has a consulate in the republic's
capital, which the Iranian broadcast called ``the Moslem city of
Baku.''
   Gorbachev and Rafsanjani agreed on a broad spectrum of economic
cooperation and Iran and the Soviet Union are expected to increase
joint efforts in areas including atomic energy, space and gas
processing.
   Rafsanjani suggested a joint Soviet-Iranian space voyage during
the visit, and Gorbachev ordered his deputies to begin working out
the details.
   Rail links between the two countries will be restored and another
rail line constructed, the official Tass news agency said.
   Rafsanjani invited Gorbachev to Iran. Gorbachev thanked
Rafsanjani for the invitation and said frequent high-level contacts
would be appropriate.
   No date was set for a Gorbachev visit.
   Topics discussed by the two included arms sales to Iran, but
Rafsanjani sidestepped questions about any deals with the Soviet
Union. He said only that Iran was trying to be self-sufficient in
arms but has some ``technical requirements that we would like to see
met by various sources.''
   Only a handful of Third World leaders have visited Tehran since
the Islamic Revolution in 1979 sent mobs into the streets shouting,
``Death to America, Death to Russia!''
   The Soviet Union was the chief arms supplier to Iraq during its
long war with Iran that ended in a cease-fire last August.
   Rafsanjani emphasized in remarks distributed by Tass on Wednesday
that several months before his death on June 3, Khomeini called for
better relations with the Soviet Union.
   Tass said Gorbachev and Khomeini exchanged messages in February,
and since then their foreign ministers have met four times.
   The Soviet Union has about 50 million Moslems, most of them
living in rapidly growing Central Asia, which borders Iran,
Afghanistan and China.
   The Soviet Union has been troubled in the past year and a half by
outbreaks of unrest among its more than 100 ethnic groups, and the
disturbances have spread in the last six weeks to Central Asia.
   About 100 people were killed in rioting in the Fergana Valley of
eastern Uzbekistan earlier this month.
</TEXT>
