<FIRST>r i PM-AngolaSummit 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0469,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebel Leader Says Summit Will Fail Without Govt-rebel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Angolan president leaving for summit;
reports he will meet Savimbi, list of countries expected at summit. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOA ESPERANCA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African summit to resolve
Angola's 14-year-old civil war will fail without talks between the
rebels and the government, guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi said
before today's meeting.
   Speaking at his bush camp Wednesday, Savimbi also said that
``never in 14 years of war have we come so close'' to peace.
   Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos left the capital,
Luanda, early today for Gbadolite, Zaire, where leaders of 22
African nations were gathering for the conference.
   In an interview with The New York Times published today, Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko said dos Santos would meet Savimbi during
the summit.
   But Savimbi, head of the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, made no mention of talks with dos Santos
during his news conference Wednesday in Boa Esperanca, in southern
Angola.
   Before leaving for Zaire, dos Santos commuted the death sentences
of 50 UNITA rebels condemned for high treason and terrorism between
1981 and 1987, the state news agency ANGOP reported.
   ANGOP reported Wednesday that the government released 700 rebel
prisoners June 2. The prisoners reportedly renounced the rebel
movement and accepted the government's offer of clemency, the
dispatch said.
   The goal of the summit was to clear the way for peace talks
between Angola's Marxist government and the rebels.
   Savimbi said his delegation in Zaire was flexible about
procedures leading to elections and formation of a national
government. But the rebels do not want any amnesty or clemency that
would imply they are criminals, Savimbi said.
   ``Our army, 75,000 men in the field, will not accept amnesty,
clemency or integration,'' Savimbi said. ``That wording has a
political context that means (the rebel army) is considered
criminal. Our army was not defeated and is not going to be
defeated.''
   Savimbi said he had agreed to stay out of the negotiations and
would not demand a role in any transitional government. He said,
however, that he would continue to head his party and also wants to
participate in free elections within two years of a formal
cease-fire.
   The government has rejected elections, saying it wants to
maintain one-party rule, with some rebels participating in the
administration.
   Under a peace plan put forward by dos Santos, Savimbi would go
abroad and recognize the legitimacy of the government, and the rebel
movement would then be integrated into the one-party state.
   Savimbi vetoed all these proposals.
   In six months, half the 50,000 Cuban soldiers who have supported
the Angolan government will have left Angola under a U.S.-mediated
peace agreement reached in December.
   Savimbi's U.S.-backed rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war
to force the Cuban- and Soviet-assisted government to share power
since shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   In addition to dos Santos, leaders from Zaire, Mozambique, Cape
Verde, Guinea-Bissau, Sao Tome e Principe, Botswana, Zambia,
Zimbabwe, Rwanda, Cameroon, Gabon, Ivory Coast, Tanzania, Togo,
Congo, Mali, Chad, Central African Republic, Nigeria and Burundi,
were expected at the summit.
</TEXT>
