<SECOND>PM-Greece, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0534,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mitsotakis Demands Resignation of Papandreou Caretaker Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to ADD comment from bank officer. Pickup
4th graf pvs, `Papandreou's Panhellenic...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece's conservative party leader today
demanded that interim Premier Andreas Papandreou resign immediately
following reports of a new financial scandal linked to his socialist
administration.
   Banner front-page headlines today in the Athens press said the
scandal involved the laundering of $700 million through the Greek
Mortgage Bank and the Atlantic Bank of New York, a subsidiary of the
state-run National Bank of Greece.
   Constantine Mitsotakis, leader of the New Democracy party, and
opposition dailies blamed Papandreou because the Mortgage Bank is a
state institution and its ranking executives are government
appointees.
   ``We have this new terrible scandal, and this usurper of
authority who shames and robs the Greek people must leave
immediately,'' Mitsotakis said at a news conference.
   The governor of the Mortgage Bank, Giorgos Anomeritis, denied
that branches of the bank in the United States had committed any
wrongdoing. ``Our branches are not allowed by law to accept deposits
and consequently they use other American commercial banks.
Therefore, they cannot be responsible either for illegal desposits
or the illegal transfer of funds,'' Anomeritis said.
   Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK, lost its
bid for a third four-year term in Sunday's election, winning only
125 of the 300 seats in Greece's unicarmeral parliament. Previous
financial scandals were blamed for the party's loss.
   New Democracy won 145 seats, six short of a clear majority that
would enable it to form a government.
   The communist-leftist alliance emerged as a power broker with 28
seats, and Mitsotakis is negotiating with the alliance to form a
coalition government.
   The money-laundering allegations were reported a day after
judicial investigators asked parliament to lift the immunity of two
former PASOK ministers so they can be prosecuted on bribery charges.
   Former Public Order Minister George Petsos is accused of
receiving gifts and other unspecified criminal acts.
   Former Deputy Premier and Justice Minister Agamemnon
Koutsogiorgas is accused of receiving a $2 million bribe from George
Koskotas, the fugitive owner of the Bank of Crete. Koutsogiorgas'
wife, Aliki, is accused of depositing the money in a Swiss bank
account shared by the couple.
   Koskotas is charged with offering the bribe and is being held in
a U.S. jail pending a hearing on a Greek extradition request.
   His lawyer, Yannis Mantzouranis, a former secretary to
Papandreou's cabinet, is charged with helping arrange the bribe.
</TEXT>
