<FIRST>r w PM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0442 06-22 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Wants to Meet With Ortega as it Monitors Nicaraguan Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to correct name to Curtin sted Curtis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private panel formed to monitor the upcoming
Nicaraguan elections says it plans to conduct polls in that country
and seek a meeting with President Daniel Ortega.
   However, Curtin Winsor Jr., co-chairman of the Bipartisan
Commission on Free and Fair Elections in Nicaragua, expressed
concern Wednesday about Managua's recent announcement that it will
require American visitors to have visas beginning July 1.
   Visas have not been required of Americans before.
   ``This has an element to it which suggests restriction,
restriction for press and foreign observer presence, and we hope
that will not be the case. It is a matter of some concern,
however,'' Winsor, a former Reagan administration ambassador to
Costa Rica, told reporters.
   In a letter to Leonor Huper, charge d'affaires of the Nicaraguan
embassy in Washington, Winsor and co-chairman Gaylord Nelson, a
former Democratic senator from Wisconsin, said the commission plans
to send its six commissioners and several staff members to Nicaragua
sometime this summer. The letter also asked for visa applications.
   Margarita Suarez, press officer for the Nicaraguan Embassy, said
she assumes the visas will be granted, but ``the official position
is that the only people who will be allowed to be observers are
those that have been invited to be observers by the government.''
   ``There is really no restriction on the visas, unless someone is
really undesirable,'' Ms. Suarez said. ``There is no new
qualification that people must go through simply because they are
Americans.''
   Winsor spoke at a news conference at which the commission
released a report saying international observers, press and
broadcast media must be free to travel throughout Nicaragua during
the campaign to monitor the election process. The Nicaraguan
elections are scheduled for February 1990.
   Ms. Suarez said the embassy had not yet received a copy of the
report.
   Nelson did not attend the news conference but said in a statement
a number of delegation trips are planned to examine Nicaragua's
political climate.
   The first delegation plans to go to Nicaragua in late July or
early August and will request a meeting with Ortega, Nelson said.
   ``Another integral part of the commission's activities will
include a series of polls,'' Nelson said. ``The first poll will
examine the political and economic climate in Nicaragua and how the
Nicaraguan people feel about the possibility of free elections.''
   After that, he said, polls comparing support for opposition and
government candidates are planned.
   The commission released letters seeking meetings with President
Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   Winsor told reporters it was uncertain whether the Supreme
Electoral Council, whose members were chosen by Ortega, ``will
operate fairly.''
   Commission member Sergio Bendixen, a Democrat and international
political consultant, said, ``Even though there are some questions
about the composition of the council which may or may not be valid,
it is by the actions of the electoral council that they should be
judged.''
   ``If we find that the decisions of the electoral council are
being arrived at by consensus, I think that would be a very positive
point,'' Bendixen said. ``If on the other hand most of the votes of
the electoral council are 4-1 or 3-2, always in favor of the
Sandinista position, then I think the entire electoral process in
Nicaragua should be questioned.''
   The commission, which held three days of hearings in Washington
May 9-11, is sponsored by the conservative World Freedom Foundation.
</TEXT>
