<FIRST>r i PM-France-Opposition     06-22 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Opposition,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giscard d'Estaing Calls for Joining of Main Opposition Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing has called
for unifying France's conservative parties and said this is the only
way to wrest power from the Socialists.
   Giscard d'Estaing made the comments in an interview published
today in the newspaper Le Figaro and in comments on television
Wednesday night.
   He is president of the Union for French Democracy, a federation
of five small center-right parties. The other main opposition party
is the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic.
   Giscard d'Estaing's comments came after his party and the Rally
for the Republic joined forces in European Parliament elections
during the weekend. The list of candidates put forward by the
parties finished first with 28.9 percent of the vote, leading
Laurent Fabius' Socialist list which had 23.6 percent. Simone Veil's
separate centrist list won 8.4 percent of the vote.
   ``It was division that caused the opposition to lose'' last
year's presidential and legislative elections, Giscard d'Estaing
said. ``It is union that will cause it to win.''
   Jacques Chirac, the president of the Rally for the Republic who
lost his bid last year to unseat Socialist President Francois
Mitterrand, reacted coolly to Giscard d'Estaing's idea. He told
today's opening session of the party's National Council there would
be no ``fusion'' of the two parties.
   ``We have no intention of fusing with anybody, but reinforcing
the links of solidarity'' between the opposition groups, he said.
   Giscard d'Estaing said a convention of the opposition parties
should be held soon and a new, unified party created before the end
of the year. Such a party, he said, would still be a place where
ideas could be debated.
   The Socialists have the advantage of a single party, and while
that party has its different wings, once decisions are made, or
candidates designated, its leadership usually pulls together.
   It is the lack that cohesiveness that troubles the opposition.
   In last year's presidential elections, Chirac had to battle not
only Mitterrand, but the Union for French Democracy's Raymond Barre
and the National Front's Jean-Marie Le Pen. Mitterrand calmly ran
his own campaign, with only the small Communist thorn in his side.
</TEXT>
