<FIRST>r i PM-Netherlands-Shootout 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Netherlands-Shootout, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0532,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Colonel Killed in Shootout Between Kidnapper, Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to CORRECT suspect's last name, ADDS that he was
serving time in West Germany. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ARN1,2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARNHEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An army officer was killed today in a
highway shootout between a man who kidnapped him and law enforcement
officers, police said.
   It was not immediately clear who shot Col. Karel van de Kieft,
who was kidnapped at gunpoint as he left for work at about 6:45 a.m.
   Police spokesman Bert Albers said the kidnapper was identified as
Stefan Kroger, a 33-year-old from Hanover, in West Germany.
   In Hanover, Justice Ministry spokesman Hartmut Mollring said that
Kroger was serving a five-year jail term in West Germany for several
armed robberies and had been at large since May 10 when he failed to
show up after a one-day prison furlough.
   Albers said the kidnapper forced Van de Kieft, 56, into his car
at gunpoint near the victim's home in Apeldoorn, 10 miles north of
the eastern city of Arnhem.
   Police, alerted by a neighbor, chased the car and caught up with
it at a gas station on the Arnhem-Utrecht freeway, said Albers.
   Police fired at the kidnapper, who was in the car with his
victim, and a shootout ensued in which Van de Kieft was killed,
Albers said.
   The motive of the kidnapping was unclear, although at one point
the kidnapper demanded $450,000 ransom, according to Albers. He said
the victim and the kidnapper were apparently not acquainted.
   Kroger told police he was wanted by West German and Swiss police
in connection with several armed robberies, according to Albers.
   Albers said it was unclear whether Van de Kieft was hit by the
kidnapper or by police.
</TEXT>
