<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Ballet 1stLd-Writethru a0560 06-22 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ballet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ballerina Who Danced With American Wins Gold Medal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to ADD that Shannon from LA. Pickup 3rd, `Contestants...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ballerina won a gold medal today when she
danced with an American in one of the world's top ballet
competitions.
   Galina Stepanenko was paired with Michael Shannon of Los Angeles
in the International Ballet Competition held in Moscow's Bolshoi
Theater.
   Contestants were judged individually, and only Stepanenko won a
medal.
   Dancers Christina McDermott of Switzerland and Vladimir Malakhov
of the Soviet Union also won gold medals, the Soviet news agency
Tass reported.
   For Soviet and American dancers to compete on the same team ``is
really revolutionary in dance and especially in competitions,'' said
Amanda Olmstead, the contest's spokeswoman. ``Think of the Olympics,
where the Americans and Soviets are always the ones hitting heads.''
   The two-week contest is similar to the Olympics, with dancers
competing for gold, silver and bronze medals. No Americans won
medals.
   Jury members said the level of competition was unimpressive this
year.
   Stepanenko and Shannon danced the pas de deux from ``Don
Quixote'' in the final round.
   The International Ballet Competition alternates each year among
Moscow; Varna, Bulgaria; Helsinki, Finland; and Jackson,
Mississippi. Past medalists include Mikhail Baryshnikov and Natalia
Makarova.
</TEXT>
