<FIRST>r w PM-HousingReport     06-22 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Report,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Sees Home Ownership Among Young Americans Declining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home ownership among young Americans is
declining alarmingly and ``threatens to produce a permanent
underclass of disadvantaged renters,'' a Harvard University study
released today said.
   The annual report on the state of the nation's housing, released
by Harvard's Joint Center for Housing Studies, said the
homeownership rate for households in the 25-29 age group fell to
36.2 percent in 1988. In 1980, it was 43.3 percent.
   For households in the 30-34 age group, the rate fell to 52.6
percent, off nearly 10 percentage points from the 1976 rate of 62.4.
   The report also said that 30 percent of the nearly 5.7 million
unsbsidized housing units renting for less than $300 a month are
physically inadequate and ``at risk of loss.''
   It said single-parent households, accounting for an increasing
share of the nation's total population of children, are the most
vulnerable to the cost crunch.
   The median income of a single parent under 25 was $6,223 in 1988,
down 15 percent in inflation-adjusted terms from 1974, the report
said.
   At the same time, it said, 71 percent of all single-parent
households pay more than 50 percent of their incomes for rent.
   ``Because it is rooted in fundamental social, economic and
demographic factors, this trend is not easily reversed,'' the study
said. ``Left unchecked it threatens to produce a permanent
underlcass of disadvantaged renters and to jeopardize the long-term
financial security of future generations.''
   The study offered no specific solutions to the housing problems
it identified, saying that they are ``subject to debate'' but that
``policymakers must act to develop creative approaches to advance
the goal of decent housing for all.''
   The study was co-authored by William Apgar and Denise DiPasquale,
professors at the joint center.
  
</TEXT>
