<FIRST>r a PM-Banished     06-22 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banished,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Traveling Lightning-Rod Seller Banished from State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENCASTLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A traveling lightning-rod salesman has
been ordered to return thousands of dollars bilked from senior
citizens and has been banished from Indiana for five years.
   James E. Sherlock, 47, pleaded guilty Wednesday to
home-improvement fraud for selling shoddy and overpriced rods.
   Circuit Judge William C. Vaughn said it was the first time he had
banished anyone. ``It's a good idea for Indiana,'' he said.
   ``Five years is a fairly long time, and if he steps foot on
Indiana soil he will be arrested,'' said Calvin C. Hultquist, senior
investigator in the consumer protection division of the Indiana
attorney general's office.
   If arrested anywhere in the nation during the five years,
Sherlock could be returned to Indiana to serve the remainder of the
period in prison.
   Sherlock, who has no known address, also made $23,427 in
restitution, about 90 percent of what a dozen Hoosiers paid for
lightning rods.
   Mark C. Webb, one of Sherlock's attorneys, said the agreement was
fair.
   O. Emmitt Griffith, who paid $2,000 for lightning rods and filed
the complaint that led to Sherlock's arrest in April, said he was
pleased with the banishment.
   ``I hope he never comes back,'' he said. ``I know he couldn't do
any good around my house, and most of my neighbors know about him
now.''
</TEXT>
