<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-China     06-22 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-China,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Bill Would Rename Land Near Chinese Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation was introduced in the Senate today
to name a small plot of land across from the Chinese Embassy here
Tiananmen Square Memorial Park.
   ``It would express, silently and reverently, the sorrow Americans
feel for those who were slaughtered in Beijing, those who are now
facing brutal treatment in public trials and those who have or will
become victim to vicious public humiliation and execution,'' said
Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., one of the bill's three principal
sponsors.
   ``Every time Chinese diplomats look out of their windows, they
will be looking on a place of free thought and speech,'' said Sen.
Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill. ``Hopefully, over time, these principles will
sink into the hard hearts of the present brutal regime.''
   Meanwhile, 26 senators asked President Bush not to give in to
demands by the Chinese government to turn over astropohysicist Fang
Lizhi, a prominent dissident who has been granted diplomatic asylum
in the U.S. Embassy in Beijing.
   ``Our nation owes it to those who died in Tiananmen Square and to
those who will live with the silent memories of the brutal massacre
forever etched into their hearts to do all it can to protect this
courageous and noble man,'' the senators said in a letter to the
president.
</TEXT>
