<FIRST>r a PM-HUDProbe-Denver     06-22 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe-Denver,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver HUD Still Searching for $1 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-HUD Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but $1 million of the $7.2 million that federal
auditors said might be missing from the Denver office of the
Department of Housing and Urban Development has been accounted for,
the agency's local director says.
   ``We have got the money,'' Isaiah ``Ike'' Kelley, acting regional
HUD administrator, said Wednesday. ``It's in the Treasury, which has
been substantiated.''
   Auditors from the inspector general's office have given the HUD
office until June 30 to account for the missing records on 173
foreclosed homes sold in the past five years for $7.2 million.
   The HUD central accounting office in Washington has confirmed
that more than $6.2 million of that money was received, Kelley said.
   ``But they want to see the paper records on this. I don't know
why,'' he said.
   HUD auditors in Washington said they were unsure whether the
files and the remaining $1 million were simply misplaced or are
missing.
   The Denver HUD office is a major focus of a nationwide inquiry of
fraud, influence peddling and political favoritism at HUD during the
Reagan administration.
</TEXT>
