<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-RockConcerts     06-22 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Rock Concerts,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier for Communities to Turn Down Volume on Rock
Concerts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier for
communities to turn down the volume on rock concerts, upholding New
York City's effort to avoid ear-splitting noise levels in Central
Park.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, said officials may require sponsors
of rock concerts in the park's Naumberg Acoustic Bandshell to use a
sound system operated by a city-designated engineer.
   That requirement does not violate the freedom-of-expression
guarantees of the Constitution's First Amendment, Justice Anthony M.
Kennedy wrote for the court.
   The decision reversed a federal appeals court ruling that said
city officials had to devise a ``less restrictive'' way to satisfy
their concern over noise levels.
   ``This less-restrictive-alternative analysis has never been a
part of the inquiry into the validity of a time, place and manner
regulation'' on expression, Kennedy said.
   He added: ``The city's sound amplification guideline is narrowly
tailored to serve the substantial and content-neutral governmental
interests of avoiding excessive sound volume and providing
sufficient amplification within the bandshell concertground.
   ``Accordingly, it is valid under the First Amendment as a
reasonable regulation of the place and manner of expression,''
Kennedy said.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Thurgood Marshall said the court
``plays to our shared impatience with loud noise to obscure the
damage that it does to our First Amendment rights.''
   Calling New York's requirement for a city-run sound system at
rock concerts ``an impermissible prior restraint,'' Marshall said,
``Because judgments that sounds are too loud, noise-like, or
discordant can mask disapproval of the music itself, government
control of the sound-mixing equipment necessitates detailed and
neutral standards.''
   Quoting one music critic, the 80-year-old Marshall added, ``New
music always sounds loud to old ears.''
   He was joined in dissent by Justices William J. Brennan and John
Paul Stevens.
   The city's noise-control campaign is aimed at protecting visitors
to the park's neighborhing Sheep Meadow, a 13-acre area decreed a
``quiet zone'' by Mayor Edward Koch in 1985, and residents of a
fashionable neighborhood called Central Park West.
   The city policy was challenged by Rock Against Racism, which
sponsors an annual bandshell program of speakers and musical groups.
   The case is Ward vs. Rock Against Racism, 88-226.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
