<FIRST>r a PM-AirportContracts     06-22 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airport Contracts,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Officials Defend Handling Of Concession Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airport officials defended their handling of a
program in which lucrative contracts intended to help women and
minorities benefited the wife of Rep. Julian Dixon and other
politically well-connected people.
   ``No one's getting any favors here,'' Los Angeles Airport
Commission member Johnnie L. Cochran Jr. said at a meeting Wednesday.
   Betty Dixon and her husband, chairman of the House ethics
committee, earned more than $100,000 last year on a 1986 investment
of less than $15,000 in Peideau and Mir Kanon Inc., according to
Dixon's financial statement.
   The companies are part of a joint venture awarded a concession to
operate duty-free and gift stores at Los Angeles International
Airport.
   John Mack, president of the Los Angeles Urban League, was also
involved in the joint venture. Both he and Mrs. Dixon have
acknowledged that their involvement in running the businesses has
been minimal. Like others in the program, they are backers of Mayor
Tom Bradley, who appoints airport commission members.
   The Disadvantaged Business Enterprise program is intended to
encourage companies to invite women and minorities to become
partners in airport businesses so they can gain experience to help
them compete on their own.
   Under Federal Aviation Administration rules, minority
participants are expected to take on day-to-day responsibilities in
the businesses.
   Airport commission Chairman Samuel Greenberg and others defended
the panel's selection of participants.
   ``All of the processes took place in a forthright and public
fashion,'' said Clifton Moore, executive director of the Department
of Airports.
   But he acknowledged the matter should be looked into in more
detail. The commission hired a consultant to do that.
</TEXT>
