<FIRST>r a PM-MitchellHome     06-22 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mitchell Home,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Raises $50,000 for Civil Rights Matriarch's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP says it has raised $50,000 to save the
home of Juanita Jackson Mitchell, one-time matriarch of Baltimore's
civil rights movement.
   First American Bank of Maryland bank planned a foreclosure sale
Friday of the row house, for more than 40 years a meeting place for
activists who met in the living room to plot strategy with Mrs.
Mitchell, her late husband, Clarence, an NAACP lobbyist, and her
brother-in-law, former Rep. Parren J. Mitchell.
   ``We have no doubt now that we'll be able to save this home,''
said George Collins, a trustee of the Mitchell fund, organized by
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Mrs. Mitchell is bedridden at age 76 after two strokes, and her
sons, former state Sens. Clarence B. and Michael Mitchell, have not
been able to help her because they are in prison for fraud in the
Wedtech corruption case.
   Mrs. Mitchell defaulted on a $60,000, 90-day loan for which she
pledged the three-story house as collateral in 1987. The bank said
it extended the due date six times and waited seven more months
before starting foreclosure.
</TEXT>
