<HEAD>House Panel Calls U.S. Ambassador on Housing Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS grafs 8-9, beginning `Abrams and ...' with 7 grafs to UPDATE
with testimony. Picks up 10th graf pvs `A HUD ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel investigating influence
peddling in federal housing programs wants a U.S. ambassador to
explain how he was named developer on several lucrative projects to
refurbish federally subsidized housing for the poor.
   Philip Winn, ambassador to Switzerland, was one of several
witnesses called today to tell the House Government Operations
subcommittee on employment and housing how contracts were awarded
for the Department of Housing and Urban Development's moderate
rehabilitation program.
   Winn, a former assistant secretary of housing, led a group that
included several other former HUD officials in the Reagan
administration and won development contracts for at least seven
projects in the West and Southwest.
   ``Abuse and favoritism were pervasive at HUD in awarding these
scarce and desirable moderate rehabilitation funds,'' said
subcommittee chairman Tom Lantos, D-Calif.
   ``We are eager to hear from these witnesses how projects they
pushed came to be selected by HUD for federal subsidies over many
competing projects,'' Lantos said before the hearing.
   Among Winn's partners were Silvio DeBartolomeis, former general
deputy assistant secretary for housing; J. Michael Queenan, the
former director of HUD's Denver regional office; and Philip Abrams,
a former HUD undersecretary.
   According to a HUD inspector general's report, one proposal from
the group to develop 202 units of the Windsong Apartments in Tulsa,
Okla., was chosen after Abrams told the local housing authority how
it could obtain funding.
   Abrams was also scheduled to testify today; DeBartolomeis
testified earlier this month.
   Joseph Strauss, a former special assistant to then-HUD Secretary
Samuel Pierce, was the first witness.
   Strauss received $1.3 million in consultant fees in connection
with 13 moderate rehabilitation projects. Former Interior Secretary
James Watt told the panel earlier this month that he instructed a
developer to send Strauss $131,000 of the $300,000 fee Watt was to
receive for a consulting job.
   Strauss testified that he retained Watt in March 1984 as a
consultant to his company, Phoenix Associates, because he had
problems getting responses from HUD for his clients.
   A letter, which Strauss read and said formalized his relationship
with Watt, noted Watt's ``well developed flair for innovation.''
   Lantos asked Strauss if he had hired Watt to use his influence.
   ``That's what this letter says,'' Strauss responded.
   A HUD inspector general's report said the Winn group ``utilized a
number of corporate titles'' to buy projects that might be eligible
for the program. The group would approach local housing authorities,
advise them to apply to HUD for funding and the units and then help
local officials prepare solicitations for proposals on the projects.
   In one instance, Queenan notified the housing authority in
Richland, Wash. it had been awarded 158 units before the HUD
regional office in Seattle was even aware of the funding, the HUD
report said.
</TEXT>
