<HEAD>Surprise Catch in Speed Trap: A Sun-Powered Three-Wheeler</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIENNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A solar-powered car's speed test went
a little too well when police nabbed the driver for going 55 mph in
a 50 mph zone.
   ``I believe it's the first solar vehicle ever caught for
speeding,'' said Rene Jeanneret of the Bienne Engineering School,
the car's chief designer.
   The three-wheeled ``Spider'' was going 5 mph above the speed
limit when police stopped it outside this city Monday, Jeanneret
said.
   The incident occurred during road tests after the vehicle's
gearbox was changed to improve its performance on the Alpine stages
of an upcoming race for solar-powered vehicles through Switzerland.
   Jeanneret said the modification actually makes the car slower.
   ``We were lucky,'' he said, noting that the Spider has a maximum
speed of nearly 65 mph.
   He declined to identify the driver, who was fined 20 Swiss francs
(about $11.75).
