<HEAD>U.N. Soldiers Accused of Chipping Meteorite, a National Treasure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malaysian soldiers serving with the
United Nations force in Namibia were accused Thursday of trying to
chip souvenirs from the world's largest known meteorite, a Namibian
national monument.
   U.N. officials are investigating the incident, which reportedly
involved about 36 soldiers who turned up with a truck and began
trying to cut pieces from the giant slab near the northern town of
Grootfontein.
   The Hoba Meteorite, named for the farm on which it was discovered
in 1920, is a 66-ton boulder of iron, nickel, chrome and other
metals. Although on private property, it has been declared a
national monument and is visited by about 18,000 people a year,
officials say.
   Malaysia has about 900 soldiers in Namibia, one of the two
largest military contingents in the United Nations Transition
Assistance Group supervising the former South African colony's move
toward becoming an independent state.
