<HEAD>Priest Charged With Profiteering From Papal Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic priest appeared in court
Thursday on charges he sold papal souvenir blankets for more than 10
times the legal price.
   The state alleged the Rev. Joseph Musonda, secretary general of
the Catholic Secretariat, and church fund-raiser Valentine Musakanya
engaged in profiteering by selling 220 blankets for about $120
apiece after Pope John Paul II's May 2-4 visit.
   It was also alleged the Catholic Secretariat did not obtain
statutory approval from the trade and commerce ministry to import
the blankets.
   Under government pricing laws, the top price of a blanket was
fixed at about $9.
   Lusaka magistrate Matthew Mukubesa, who recessed the hearing to
June 26, did not ask Musonda to enter a plea on the charges, which
carry the penalty of a fine related to the alleged pricing
infringement.
   Roman Catholic churches in Zambia have said they raised an
undisclosed sum from donations and souvenir sales to finance the
pope's visit.
   Earlier this month, the government's Prices and Incomes
Commission said it was investigating sales of mugs and T-shirts
emblazoned with John Paul's portrait at inflated prices.
