<DOCNO> AP890622-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HousingReport     06-22 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Report,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Finds Home Ownership Among Young Declining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home ownership is declining among young
Americans but increasing among those 65 and older, according to a
Harvard University study released Thursday.
   Harvard's Joint Center for Housing Studies said in its annual
report on the state of housing in the United States that the home
ownership rate for those in the 25-34 age group was 45 percent in
1988, down from 52.3 percent in 1980.
   Among households headed by people 65 and older, however, the rate
increased from 72.3 percent in 1980 to 75 percent in 1988. The
report said that many of those people already owned homes before
housing costs increased in the 1970s and early 1980s.
   Young people, the study found, are increasingly unable to
accumulate the down payment and other costs involved in buying a
house.
   ``This trend is not easily reversed,'' the report said. ``Left
unchecked, it threatens to produce a permanent underclass of
disadvantaged renters and to jeopardize the long-term financial
security of future generations.''
   The study was co-authored by Harvard professors William Apgar and
Denise DiPasquale.
   ``The situation is likely to worsen,'' Ms. DiPasquale said at a
news conference. ``Federal budget cutbacks and expiring use
restrictions threaten the subsidized housing stock.''
   The report said inflation-adjusted rents for poor people living
in unsubsidized units increased 34 percent from 1974 to 1985.
   ``As long as these trends persist, the gap between those who can
afford decent shelter and those who can't will continue to widen,''
Apgar said.
   Single-parent households, which account for an increasing share
of the nation's total population of children, are living in some of
the worst housing, the report said.
   The median income of a single parent under 25 was $6,223 in 1988,
down 15 percent in inflation-adjusted terms from 1974, the report
said. At the same time, 71 percent of all single-parent households
pay more than 50 percent of their incomes for rent.
</TEXT>
