<FIRST>u i PM-Espionage     06-22 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Espionage,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldier-Spy Had No Plan When He Entered East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FULDA, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. soldier who pleaded guilty to
espionage charges says he didn't know what he was going to do when
he crossed the border to communist East Germany, a military
newspaper reported today.
   Spec. 4 Michael A. Peri, 22, of Laguna Niguel, Calif., pleaded
guilty to charges he gave defense secrets to East Germany when his
court martial opened Wednesday. Peri could be sentenced to life in
prison on the espionage charges.
   Peri disappeared from his unit, the 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment
in Fulda, on Feb. 21. He returned voluntarily 11 days later.
   ``I was never really sure what I was going to do at all,'' Peri
told the courtoom after changing his plea from not guilty to guilty,
according to an account in the Stars and Stripes, the Armed Forces
unofficial newspapers.
   ``I really didn't have a plan. My primary reason was to leave
behind all the frustrations and problems at work,'' the newspaper
quoted him as saying about his decision to leave his unit.
   ``Everything had been wrong. I wasn't enjoying myself. I wanted
to start over somewhere else,'' the Stars and Stripes quoted his as
telling the court in response to a question from Col. Craig. G.
Jacobsen, the presiding judge.
   Peri disappeared with a lap-top computer from his unit, where he
worked in the military intelligence section as an electronic signal
interceptor.
   ``I was looking at Soviet forces on paper (at work) and I wanted
to see it firsthand,'' the newspaper quoted his as saying.
   ``I took the computer to run the software because I didn't think
the Soviets would have one. It was a bargaining chip to keep them
from doing something to me. It would show them that I wasn't an
American plant,'' the paper quoted him as telling the court.
   Peri said he used a multipurpose military vehicle to drive to the
East German border because it was a headquarters vehicle and would
not arouse suspicion inside the half-mile zone along the border,
which U.S. soldiers cannot enter without authorization.
   After abandoning the vehicle near the border, Peri said he
climbed over the border fence, using angled support posts as a
ladder, according to Stars and Stripes. Peri said he walked to an
East German border command tower and was spotted by soldiers who
took him to a nearby barracks.
   ``They were surprised when I told them how I came over and got so
far before being seen,'' the Stars and Stripes quoted him as saying.
   He was then taken by unidentified civilians to a house in East
Belrin, where he was questioned about the secret documents he
brought on the computer software, Peri told the court, according to
the paper.
   Peri told the judge he didn't realize how extensive the
information was until he returned to Fulda and was questioned by
U.S. intelligence officials, the newspaper said.
   On March 3, Peri told the East Germans he wanted to leave and was
allowed to go back with the computer and the software, the Stars and
Stripes said.
   He was charged with espionage on March 16.
   Peri's parents, Fred and Winnie, and sister, Desiree, from Orange
County, Calif., were at Wednesday' court session, Stars and Stripes
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
