<DOCNO> AP890622-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Cholesterol-Children     06-22 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cholesterol-Children,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Routine Cholesterol Screening Recommended for Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private research and education organization
urged routine cholesterol testing in children Thursday, saying high
levels go undetected in many youngsters.
   Cholesterol should be checked at some point from ages 2 to 10
``and the sooner the better,'' said Ernst Wynder, president of the
American Health Foundation in New York.
   High cholesterol can lead to disease in the arteries that feed
the heart muscle. That sets the stage for a heart attack in adult
life.
   The American Heart Association recommends childhood cholesterol
testing only if a child's family history suggests he is at risk.
   But that strategy overlooks many children with high cholesterol,
Wynder said in a recent interview. Children are considered at risk
if their fathers have had a heart attack, for example, but a young
father may not have had his heart attack while the child is still
young, Wynder said.
   The health foundation said research shows that some 5 percent to
15 percent of children in industrialized countries have excessive
cholesterol levels, using the adult standard of 200 milligrams per
deciliter or more. Almost a third are above 175 milligrams per
deciliter, which may be a more appropriate marker for children, the
foundation said.
   Wynder said screening all children would be cost-effective
because it would reduce such later costs as those of coronary bypass
operations and time off work from heart attacks.
   The heart association's recommendation was published in 1986.
William Weidman, a member of the committee that developed it, said
it was based on the state of cholesterol-testing technology and
knowledge about childhood cholesterol at that time.
   ``We felt we weren't ready'' for universal childhood screening,
he said in a recent interview.
   Now such screening is being studied by a committee organized by
the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, Weidman said.
   The heart association is awaiting the committee's conclusions
before deciding on any change in its recommendation, said
association spokesman Howard Lewis.
   The health foundation said a feasible target for children's
cholesterol is 140 milligrams per deciliter. Weidman agreed that is
``a goal to shoot for'' but said diet and exercise will not be
enough to reach it in all children. So medications may be needed, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
