<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-US     06-22 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Coast Guard Sailing Ship Arrives in Leningrad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Eagle, the U.S. Coast Guard's three-masted
ship, sailed into Leningrad on Thursday, bringing 300 American
sailors to the former imperial Russian capital at the time of its
``White Nights.''
   It was the first port call of an American warship to a Soviet
city since 1975, said Capt. Peter Huchthausen, the U.S. naval
attache in Moscow.
   The picturesque Eagle doesn't carry any weapons, even though it's
called a warship. Instead, it sails with a crew of 55 and 250 Coast
Guard Academy cadets _ would-be officers learning their seamanship
skills on an annual summer training cruise, Huchthausen said.
   For three days, the cadets will see Leningrad in the midst of the
``White Nights,'' when most of the population spills out onto Nevsky
Prospect and other avenues in a vast street party. It is a time when
the sun just barely sets and the skies never completely darken over
the northern city.
   The Coast Guard Academy band joined the festivities and gave a
concert Wednesday night outside the Kazan Cathedral in downtown
Leningrad, according to the U.S. Consulate. The Eagle, a sailing
barque built in the 1930s, will be open to Soviets for tours Friday
and Saturday.
   Americans will have a similar chance to explore off-limits
territory in July, when a Soviet missile cruiser, destroyer and
tanker sail into Norfork, Va., Huchthausen said.
   Other U.S. warships are scheduled to visit Sevastopol on the
Black Sea in August.
</TEXT>
