<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-AsiaPolicy     06-22 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Asia Policy,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solomon Says Only China Can Say Whether It Can Return to ``Path of
Reform''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration wants to stress U.S.
outrage over China's crackdown on the democracy movement without
pressing that nation to the point where ``its only real prospect for
reaching out to the world is back toward the Soviet Union,'' Richard
H. Solomon said Thursday.
   Solomon, President Bush's nominee for assistant secretary of
state for East Asian and Pacific affairs, said that ``only China can
answer the question whether it can now return to the path of
reform.''
   Solomon, who heads the State Department's policy planning staff,
appeared at an Asian policy conference sponsored by the Heritage
Foundation, a private research organization.
   Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, another speaker, described China
as a ``tragedy of old men holding onto power by executing their own
grandchildren.'' He added that ``I hope I'm wrong but I believe our
relations with China are going to get worse for a long time.''
   Murkowski said that a new leadership in Beijing ``would give
everybody the opportunity for a way out'' of the current situation.
   Solomon said that prospects of continued openness and stability
in China ``are now clouded by repression and possibly turning inward
if not returning to centralized management.''
   He said U.S. policy-makers face a challenge of balancing ``the
totally appropriate outrage our people feel about the violent
massacre inflicted on peaceful Chinese demonstrators'' with the
desirability of not pushing China into Moscow's arms.
   Solomon said that the policy-makers want to express that outrage
without pushing China ``into a situation where its only real
prospect of reaching out to the world is back toward the Soviet
Union.''
   He said another challenge of U.S. Asian policy is to ``better
manage'' relations with Japan, which form ``the keystone of our
dealings in the Pacific,'' and preventing trade and technology
disputes from undermining them.
   Solomon said the administration does not favor a free trade
arrangement with Japan that would exclude other Pacific countries
but seeks a regional consensus on ``some form of appropriate
mutilateral mechanism'' to deal with trade, financial, technological
and environmental issues.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will unveil such proposals
in a New York speech Monday and during an Asian tour, Solomon said.
   He also said the administration is ``gearing up for a major
diplomatic effort'' for a peace process in Cambodia that will spare
the Cambodians from a new civil war and allow them to choose their
own government after the expected end of the Vietnamese occupation
later this year.
   Solomon said the United States also needs to ``reaffirm the
consensus which has been underpinning security'' since World War II
in Asia and the Pacific.
   He said the situation in Korea ``remains highly explosive''
because North Korean leaders are not undertaking the kind of reforms
``we see in much of the communist world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
