<DOCNO> AP890622-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SubmarineRaces Bjt   06-22 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Submarine Races, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human-Powered Submarine Racers Ready To Take A Dive</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the minds of engineers and the
spirits of pioneers, 18 teams are gambling their reputations and
their survival in the first human-powered submarine races.
   ``There's both a fun and serious side to the races,'' said Maggie
Linskey Merrill, director of The H.A. Perry Foundation Inc., a
Hingham, Mass.-based undersea research group that, along with
Florida Atlantic University of Boca Raton, organized the three-day
event starting Friday.
   ``We want to see the type of materials used and what shape
performs the best,'' Ms. Merrill said. ``There could be a commercial
and recreational application for human-powered subs.''
   And for the competitors, who will race their two-person craft
1,000 feet offshore in about 20 feet of water, there's the spice of
a $5,000 overall performance prize and several smaller cash awards
for design and efficiency.
   The lightweight subs _ with one person steering and the other in
the ``crankman'' seat providing the pedal power _ will race
head-to-head over a one-kilometer course. The eight winners of
Friday's first rounds will move on to elimination rounds over the
weekend. The subs will tow surface floats to mark their progress,
about the pace of a brisk walk.
   All the subs are ``wet'' designs that fill up with water and
require the crews to wear scuba gear.
   For most entrants, the nearly 18 months of design and
construction was plotted on computers and bankrolled by universities
or corporate sponsors. A few, however, pulled the car out of the
family garage for their work space.
   Ed Leibolt and two co-workers at the David Taylor Research Center
in Bethesda, Md., combed junk yards for parts. The crew seats are
old plastic cafeteria chairs, and an old 10-speed bike was converted
into the sub's gear system.
   They dubbed the 600-pound fiberglass sub ``The Turtle'' after the
first human-powered sub, built in 1775 but abandoned after its first
unsuccessful mission to sink British ships in New York Harbor.
   ``Hope we have better luck,'' said Leibolt. ``We literally funded
this by passing around a hat in the office.''
   In Concord, Calif., an auto shop donated a pink-and-green paint
job for the independent ``Sub-Human.''
   ``We sort of winged it,'' said crankman Chris Reno, who still
shivers when he recalls the first test run in 46-degree Lake Tahoe.
   While most of the subs resemble sleek torpedos, many teams
boasted of subtle differences.
   ``Ours may look like some of the others, but there's one
difference: Ours is fastest,'' said Paul Friedman, a back-up
navigator for the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's
``Icarus,'' which uses a cable-and-pulley propulsion system rather
than the more common chain-and-gear.
   ``We designed ours in a perfect hydrodynamic shape,'' said
University of Washington mechanical engineering graduate George
Poor. ``It should slice right through the water.''
   The ``Gossamer Albacor,'' built by Lockheed Advanced Marine
Systems in San Diego, was one of two entries using a waving
fish-tail propulsion device rather than propellers.
   ``We're looking at all things: the cleverness of design and the
materials used,'' said engineer Robert Phillips, one of six judges
assigned to award $500 prizes for cost effectiveness and innovation.
``Anyone can build something with a blank check. I'll be looking for
some real imagination.''
   Surely, 73-year-old Calvin Gongwer's ``Knuckle Ball'' will not go
unnoticed.
   Gongwer, president of Innerspace Corp., of Covina, Calif., will
be the navigator inside his 60-inch-diameter plastic sphere.
   ``There are some ideas I want to test out with spheres
underwater,'' said Gongwer. ``Looks aren't everything.''
   On the beach, Perry Foundation President H.A. Perry watched all
the preparations.
   ``The response has been four of five times what we imagined,''
said Perry. ``At first we thought we'd have a few subs, a few races
and a keg of beer. We didn't expect this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
