<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--MilitaryStrength     06-22 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Military Strength,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Active-Duty Strength Up Slightly in May</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The active-duty strength of the nation's armed
forces rose slightly in May with the greatest increase among Army
personnel, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   The Navy, Air Force, Army and Marine Corps reported 2,111,668 men
and women on active duty as of May 31, up from 2,110,287 on April
30. A year ago, the Pentagon reported 2,100,025 men and women in
uniform.
   Three of the services reported increases in strength during May
while the Air Force reported a decrease.
   The Army said it had 763,505 men and women on active duty as of
May 31, up 1,717 from April 30. The Navy reported 580,592 on active
duty, up 119 from April 30. The Marine Corps said its active-duty
strength increased by 261 to 194,845.
   The Air Force reported a drop of 716 to a total of 572,726.
</TEXT>
