<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0577 06-22 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0577,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Touts New Foundation to Boost Volunteerism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; New material, editing throughout with Bush speech.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today called upon all American
citizens and institutions to join a voluntary crusade to fight
poverty, drugs and other societal ills by extending national service
``into every corner of America.''
   Bringing a campaign metaphor to life, he unveiled his blueprint
for a foundation called the ``Points of Light Initiative'' that
would get $25 million a year in taxpayers' funds to spur Americans
to volunteer for social service.
   He made the pitch in a speech for the New York City Partnership,
a civic group, after touring a shelter for runaway youth called
Covenant House.
   Bush also named New Jersey Gov. Tom Kean to head an advisory
committee that will recommend legislation to achieve the
foundation's goals and propose a structure for the organization.
   ``I ask all Americans and all American institutions, large and
small, to make service central to your life and work,'' Bush said.
   ``We know that during the past two decades we have spent more
money, on more social programs, than at any time in our history. And
some problems aren't better. In fact, they're worse.''
   Bush said ``too many Americans still endure a living nightmare of
want and isolation. That must stop.''
   ``The key to constructive change is building relationships, not
bureaucracies,' he said.
   ``Today, more than ever, we need community service to help
drop-outs, pregnant teens and drug abusers; the homeless and AIDS
victim; the hungry and illiterate.''
   Invoking again the guiding metaphor of his campaign, Bush said he
wanted to unleash the energy of every citizen, school, business,
church and synagogue and civic group.
   ``This is what I mean when I talk of `a thousand points of light'
_ that vast galaxy of people and institutions working together to
solve problems in their own back yard,'' he said.
   Bush said he was asking both the public and private sector,
including all branches of government, to ``join this great movement
to extend national service into every corner of America.''
   He urged every church and synagogue to ``become an
around-the-clock community center,'' every restaurant and grocery to
distribute surplus food to soup kitchens and shelters, every
corporation to teach illiterate employees to read, and every college
to start a Big Brother or Big Sister program.
   Bush said that in addition to the Youth Engaged in Service to
America program (YES) announced Wednesday, the new foundation will
include a ``ServNet Project'' that will encourage corporations,
professional firms and other groups to donate the services of their
top talent.
   Bush said the YES program will select annually two college-age
youth from each state to serve as roving service ambassadors and
salespeople. ``We know that volunteerism can help those free-falling
through society,'' Bush said.
   At Covenant House, a shelter near Times Square, Bush and his wife
Barbara heard 11 young residents tell of their lives on the streets.
Mrs. Bush cradled a three-week-old baby of one of the youths as they
spoke.
   Monique, 20, said of her life on the streets, ``You don't want to
be there.'' She said as a child she was beaten at home, ``tied up
and hung over a spiral staircase.''
   Walter, 18, told the president that kids wound up on the streets
because ``It's hard to get good jobs. Working in McDonald's at the
minimum wage _ it just doesn't pay.''
   He said that he could make $100 ``in 15 minutes'' selling drugs.
He said his father was an alcoholic and his mother was dead.
   The White House billed the new community service drive as a
potential panacea for a welter of social problems, from drug abuse
to homelessness, and said it could be `the most comprehensive and
inclusive movement of our time.''
   During his acceptance speech at the Republican convention last
Aug. 18 Bush first spoke of what he called the ``brilliant
diversity'' of volunteerism in America, shining ``like a thousand
points of light'' across society.
   The metaphor drew guffaws from Democratic rival Michael Dukakis,
but Bush returned to the theme repeatedly and promised to help spur
volunteerism with a Youth Entering Service to America initiative.
</TEXT>
