<HEAD>Former Senator From Maine Receives 91 Dozen Roses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SKOWHEGAN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Chase Smith was sent 91 dozen
roses in appreciation for her efforts to make the rose America's
national flower.
   The former U.S. senator, who is 91, accepted the gigantic bouquet
Wednesday. Most of the roses will be given to nursing homes and a
hospital.
   Mrs. Smith said she had campaigned ``for 40 years plus'' in
Washington to make the rose the national flower. It became known as
her trademark.
   ``I always got it passed in the House, but never the Senate,''
she said. Finally winning approval in both chambers, the bill was
signed into law in 1987.
   The long-stemmed ``Samantha'' red roses, arranged in a single
vase, took on the appearance of a 7-foot Christmas tree being
transported through the streets of Mrs. Smith's home town of
Skowhegan on an open, flat-bed trailor.
   A radio station and a florists' group presented the giant bouquet.
