<SECOND>PM-Yates,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Congressman Faints on House Floor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., fainted in a chair
on the House floor today, but the lawmaker's press secretary said he
recovered quickly and did not appear to have suffered any serious
illness.
   The 79-year-old, 20-term congressman from Chicago became dizzy
and fainted for about a minute during a House session.
   Six members of the medical staff that serves Congress placed a
blood pressure cuff on his left arm and what appeared to be a heart
monitor on his chest. They talked to him for about 15 minutes before
wheeling him out of the chamber in a wheelchair.
   ``I feel fine,'' Yates said as he left.
   Press secretary Mary Bain said Yates was soon cracking jokes with
the medical staff and was taken to the attending physician's office
in the Capitol for further examination.
   She said they would probably to an electrocardiogram, but ``there
was no indication he had a heart attack.''
   ``He's been overworking like the devil,'' Ms. Bain said, and
probably was just tired. Yates chairs the House Appropriations
subcommittee on Interior and related agencies.
   House members, who were making one-minute speeches on the subject
of their choice, continued their business as the emergency crew
worked on Yates.
   Several dozen members were present, most of them speaking out
against the Supreme Court decision Wednesday that allowed burning of
the American flag as a means of protest.
</TEXT>
