<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DogReturns     06-22 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dog Returns,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dog Lost On Mount McKinley Wanders Into Camp 18 Days Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sled dog lost in poor weather during a
climbing expedition on Mount McKinley has turned up, weak but alive,
after 18 days on the ice-covered mountain.
   Patricia and Jean-Francois Tuveri of Chamonix, France, assumed
the dog had fallen in a crevasse and died after it disappeared May
31.
   The Tuveris had four dogs in harness when they started mushing up
North America's tallest peak. On the sixth day of the journey, while
descending to their camp at the 11,000-foot level after ferrying
supplies higher, they unhitched the dogs because of treacherous ice
conditions.
   By the time they got around Windy Corner at 13,200 feet, only
three dogs were with them. A 15-month-old Siberian husky named
Oukiok was gone.
   A snowstorm forced the Tuveris to hole up for the next four days.
When they climbed to a medical research camp at 14,200 feet, they
asked other climbers if they had seen the dog. None had and they
assumed he had fallen to his death.
   With only three dogs left, the Tuveris abandoned their sled and
simply climbed to the 20,320-foot summit with the dogs. It was only
the second expedition to reach the top with dogs.
   The Tuveris left the mountain for some sightseeing around Alaska,
then returned to Talkeetna, near the mountain, to pick up the
remaining dogs for the trip back to France.
   That's where they learned that, 18 days after he disappeared,
Oukiok had walked into the high basin where the medical camp is
located. Denali National Park rangers said the dog didn't have any
broken bones, but was exhausted.
   ``It would seem pretty spectacular but it's not impossible,''
said Jim Leach, chief veterinarian for the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog
Race. Snow and ice could provide enough liquid to prevent death
through dehydration, he said.
   The dog was being nursed back to health by staff members at the
research camp. Rangers said he should soon have enough strength to
make the trip to the Kahiltna Glacier base camp at 7,200 feet. From
there he will be flown to Talkeetna, hopefully in time to accompany
the Tuveris and the other three dogs back to France on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
