<FIRST>r a PM-TokenSuit     06-22 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Token Suit,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sues for $20.35 Because Discount Tokens Unavailable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In at least one respect, Paul Schlichtman's
lawsuit is just a token gesture. He'll be happy if it nets him
$20.35.
   The commuter is suing the New Jersey Highway Authority because
its discount toll-booth tokens were always sold out, and when he did
manage to buy some, they sold him a slug. That's what the 35 cents
in the suit is for.
   By the same token, he'll also seek the $11.70 court filing fee.
   ``If you've got a mule, the only way you can get it to do
something is to get its attention first,'' he said Wednesday. ``I'm
filing the suit to get their attention, then I'm going to get them
to do something _ give me the money they owe me.''
   Schlichtman said he tried five times without success to buy rolls
of tokens for the Garden State Parkway. It costs $10 to buy 40
tokens, a savings of $4 over the cash toll.
   ``I spend about $1,000 a year on tolls, counting going into New
York,'' said Schlichtman, a South Orange resident who works in New
York City giving driving lessons to cabbies. ``I spend more time
sitting at toll booths than I do with any other part of my day.
They're ridiculous and obnoxious.''
   Schlichtman said a toll collector refused to reimburse him for
the slug.
   New Jersey Highway Authority spokesman Dennis Ingoglia would not
comment on the case but said if motorists are sold slugs, they can
contact the agency for reimbursement.
</TEXT>
