<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Economy     06-22 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy Expanded at 4.4 Percent Annual Rate in First Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy expanded at a 4.4 percent
annual rate in the first three months of the year, but the overall
growth rate masked a significant slowdown in business activity, the
government reported Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
country's total output of goods and services, rose at the fastest
rate in more than a year during the first quarter.
   However, more than half of the increase resulted from a
statistical rebound from last year's drought, a one-time accounting
change necessary to return expected farm production this year to its
pre-drought levels.
   Discounting this change, the non-farm economy grew at a
lackluster annual rate of 1.9 percent in the first quarter, down
from a non-farm growth rate of 3.5 percent in the final three months
of 1988.
   Economists have been predicting for some time that economic
growth will slow markedly this year under the impact of high
interest rates engineered by the Federal Reserve in an effort to
cool off inflationary pressures.
   On the inflation front, a price index tied to the GNP rose at an
annual rate of 4.6 percent in the first three months of the year, a
less worrisome figure than a 5 percent increase estimated a month
ago. The improvement came from slower price increases for farm
products and industrial supplies.
   The effect of the economic slowdown was evident in a companion
report that showed the after-tax profits of American corporations
fell by 1.1 percent in the first three months of 1989. The decline,
which was revised from an even larger 1.7 percent estimated drop a
month ago, was the first setback for corporate profits since a 2.5
percent fall in the first quarter of 1987.
   Economists said the new GNP report was a generally favorable sign
that the Fed can engineer a soft-landing with slower growth and less
inflation without pushing the country into a recession.
   ``The Federal Reserve seems to be getting precisely what it asked
for,'' said Robert Dederick, chief economist of Northern Trust Co.
of Chicago. ``We have an economy that is continuing to expand but at
a subdued rate.''
   Many analysts believe that the country has now entered what is
termed a growth recession, a period when the economy keeps growing
but at such a sluggish pace that unemployment rises.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with Data Resources Inc. of
Lexington, Mass., predicted that the unemployment rate, now at 5.2
percent, would climb to 5.9 percent early next year.
   She forecast GNP growth in the second quarter of around 1.8
percent, very much like the non-farm increase in the first three
months of the year. In the second half of 1989, she predicted growth
would slow to around 1 percent, but without a recession.
   ``It is still our bet that we can avoid a recession,'' she said.
``The new GNP report provides further ammunition for those arguing
for a soft landing.''
   The primary reason for the slight upward revision in the overall
4.4 percent GNP figure, up from a 4.3 percent estimate a month ago,
was a better performance in trade than previously believed.
   The country's huge trade deficit, which had been getting worse
since last spring, narrowed significantly in the first quarter and
business investment shot up substantially.
   The U.S. trade deficit, as measured by the GNP, narrowed by $19.5
billion in the first quarter as exports shot up by 15 percent and
imports fell by 0.5 percent while business investment advanced by
7.6 percent, rebounding from a 2.9 percent decline in the fourth
quarter.
   The Bush administration is counting on both trade and business
investment to be strong this year to keep the economy moving forward
while consumer spending slackens.
   Consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of all economic
activity, rose at a sluggish annual rate of 1.3 percent in the first
quarter, reflecting in part weak auto sales. Housing construction,
which also has been hard hit by the Fed's anti-inflation campaign,
dropped by 4.6 percent in the first quarter, the poorest performance
in a year.
   The Federal Reserve signaled last week that it had begun lowering
interest rates slightly amid signs that inflationary pressures are
abating somewhat. That move is expected to revive the fortunes of
interest-rate sensitive sectors of the economy such as housing.
   The various changes left the GNP, after adjusting for inflation,
at an annual level of $4.077 trillion in the first quarter.
   The latest monthly survey of 51 top economists conducted by the
Blue Chip Economic Indicators newsletter put the consensus growth
forecast this year at 2.7 percent, down significantly from GNP
growth of 3.9 percent in 1988, the best performance in four years.
   The Bush administration, which needs significant growth to lower
the budget deficit without the need to resort to a tax increase, is
more optimistically forecasting growth this year of 3.2 percent.
That estimate will be revised by mid-July and administration
officials have indicated that they expect to lower their growth
figure somewhat.
</TEXT>
