<FIRST>r w AM-MoonProbe     06-22 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moon Probe,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposals Sought to Search for Water on Moon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private space research organization said
Thursday it has asked for proposals from satellite manufacturers to
build a probe to look for water on parts of the moon that have never
seen daylight.
   Gregg Maryniak, executive vice president of the Space Studies
Institute, said the probe can be built for $5 million, and sent to
the moon in 1992 with a little bit f help from the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   For example, he told a news conference, NASA has in storage an
Apollo-era gamma ray spectrometer that could be dusted off and used
to map the moon's surface and search for water at the poles, areas
of which never face the sun.
   NASA or rocket-launching firms could also carry the probe into
orbit as non-paying cargo, either on the space shuttle or as a
hitchhiker on a rocket taking a satellite to an orbit 22,300 miles
above Earth, Maryniak said.
   He said SSI, a 12-year-old organization supported by 4,000
private members, is looking for financing from aerospace
corporations and organizations.
   The six teams of astronauts who visited the moon in the 1969-1972
period all landed closer to the equator of the moon than to the
poles and the question of whether there is water to be found in the
shadowed area never was answered.
   Finding water, which is composed of hydrogen and oxygen _ the
fuel for chemical rockets _ would be of enormous value to future
space exploration. The National Commission on Space recommended such
a search as its first priority. It takes less than one-twentieth the
energy to lift materials form the moon as it does from Earth.
</TEXT>
