<FIRST>r w AM-IRSCommissioner     06-22 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRS Commissioner,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Commissioner Won't Tolerate Harassment of Whistle-blowers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man nominated as commissioner of the
Internal Revenue Service told Congress on Thursday that he won't
tolerate harassment of whistle-blowers who point out agency problems.
   ``Privates often know ... a lot more about fighting wars than the
generals,'' Fred T. Goldberg Jr. told the Senate Finance Committee,
which is considering his nomination. ``If they can't feel free to
communicate their perceptions, we will lose touch.''
   Goldberg, who served two years as chief counsel to the IRS, also
condemned illegal leaks of confidential tax information, such as
apparently occurred in the case of former House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas.
   While Wright was the subject of an ethics investigation that
eventually led him to resign, news reports quoted unnamed IRS
sources as saying Wright's taxes were being investigated.
   ``The fastest way to lose faith with the American people is to
have them believe we disclose that (confidential) information,''
Goldberg said.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., questioned Goldberg about recent
allegations of IRS wrongdoing, some of which could involve criminal
activity.
   ``Misconduct will not be tolerated in this institution,''
Goldberg said.
   Goldberg praised the new ``Taxpayer Bill of Rights,'' designed to
help taxpayers who run into trouble with the IRS, as ``essential to
sound tax administration.''
   Goldberg, 41, would succeed Lawrence B. Gibbs, who left earlier
this year to resume a private law practice.
</TEXT>
