<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     06-22 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Khomeini's Son Seeks Role in Hierarchy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocaited Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only son of Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini wants a role in Iran's hierarchy following his father's
death but is not sure what to aim for, Tehran Radio reported
Thursday.
   The report, quoting Hojatoleslam Mohammad Ali Ansari, indicates
Ahmad Khomeini won't run in presidential elections scheduled July 28.
   ``When we have been with him (Ahmad) we have never heard a word
which would indicate his participation or his aim of participating
in political issues,'' Ansari said in an interview with Tehran
Radio, which was monitored in Nicosia.
   Ansari is a leading radical clergyman working at the ayatollah's
office and a close friend of Ahmad Khomeini.
   The younger Khomeini allied himself with radicals when his father
unleashed a resurgence of fundamentalism in February, calling on
Moslems to kill British writer Salman Rushdie for allegedly
blaspheming Islam in his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``I think that society expects a person who has been trained at
the side of the imam ... like him (Ahmad) to be always on the stage
in the path of the advancement of the imam's aspirations, and this
is also what he intends to do,'' Ansari said.
   However, he stressed, ``no firm decision has been taken by him.''
   Iranians called the revolutionary patriarch who died of a heart
attack June 3 their imam, or supreme leader. Khomeini was 86 years
old.
   Several officials had predicted the younger Khomeini, who was his
father's closest adviser, would exploit the wave of emotion
engulfing Iran after Khomeini's death to advance his political
ambitions.
   Khomeini's daughter, Zahra Mustafavi, said in a recent interview
that Ahmad had aspired to become president since 1981, but that her
father always insisted on keeping his children out of politics.
   She said she expected Ahmad to run for presidency this year. But
he still had not declared any plan six days before the consitutional
period for announcing candidacy ends June 28.
   The powerful Parliament speaker, Hashemi Rasfsanjani, is the only
candidate for the post.
   Rafsanjani, who also is acting commander in chief of the armed
forces, leads the so-called pragmatists who advocate a more open
policy toward the West and an end to the isolation imposed since
Khomeini's 1979 Islamic revolution.
   Rafsanjani, 55, is allied with Ali Khamenei, Iran's president
since 1981 who cannot run for re-election when his second term
expires next month.
</TEXT>
