<FIRST>u a PM-EcclesiaSentencing     06-22 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ecclesia Sentencing,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Given 20 Years in Child's Beating Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four leaders of an athletics camp for
ghetto children were sentenced to the maximum 20 years in prison
today for beating to death an 8-year-old girl as other youngsters
were forced to count the blows.
   Circuit Judge John Lowe sentenced the four after rejecting a plea
from the victim's father and founder of the Ecclesia Athletic
Association, Eldridge Broussard Jr., to ``release these people until
such time as an appeal comes.''
   The four _ Willie K. Chambers, 35, of San Diego; Constance Z.
Jackson, 38; Brian J. Brinson, 31, and Frederick P. Doolittle, 28,
all of Los Angeles _ were convicted of manslaughter May 12 in the
death of Dayna Broussard.
   Prosecutors said most of the camp's 53 children ranging from 6
weeks to 16 years were forced to watch Oct. 13 as the girl was hit
hundreds of times for stealing food from another child at their
farmhouse about 30 miles from Portland.
   Several children testified that Dayna was slammed against a wall,
kicked, tripped, slapped, dropped on the floor, shoved, bitten, spit
upon and hung out a window.
   Broussard, 35, who said he formed Ecclesia in the Watts area of
Los Angeles to steer children away from crime and drugs and make
them Olympic-caliber athletes, was in Los Angeles at the time of his
daughter's death.
   He previously has denied that the children were beaten or abused,
saying they were only spanked.
   Jackson also was sentenced to 10 years in prison on charges of
beating five other Ecclesia children with a braided electrical cord.
   Witnesses testified that Chambers did most of the beating, while
Doolittle and Brinson held the girl down. Jackson was accused of
striking and biting the child.
</TEXT>
