<FIRST>r a AM-YahwehVerdict     06-22 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yahweh Verdict,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge: Yahwehs Must Pay Tenants Hurt By `Terrorist' Eviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered the Yahweh sect to pay
$940,000 to tenants who lost their homes in a strong-arm eviction
that ended in the deaths of two residents at a crime-ridden
apartment complex.
   The tenants' attorney called Thursday for a police investigation
of the sect, saying the civil trial testimony demonstrated that the
white-robed Yahwehs engaged in a policy of violence against those
who opposed them.
   ``They fire-bombed an entire block in Delray Beach, and they were
involved in slayings in other cities,'' Thomas Equels said. ``I
think the state and federal government need to carefully examine the
judge's findings here.''
   In Delray Beach, after some residents took offense at the
Yahwehs' door-to-door proseletyzing, someone threw firebombs into
apartments. No one was injured and the crime is unsolved. Witnesses
also mentioned slayings, including the unsolved killing of a former
sect member.
   The Yahwehs' attorney, Ellis Rubin, said he would appeal the
ruling, saying the sect should not be blamed for what a few members
did.
   ``We're appealing as a matter of religious freedom,'' Rubin said.
``If a Catholic commits a crime, you don't punish the pope or the
priests because of his wrongdoing.''
   U.S. District Judge James Kehoe issued his decision Wednesday in
the lawsuit filed by 27 former residents of an Opa-locka apartment
complex against the Temple of Love, the Miami-based mother church
run by the sect's leader Yahweh ben Yahweh.
   The church, which takes a strong stand against drugs, moved to
buy the apartments in 1986 after the previous owner abandoned them,
saying crack dealers and criminals had taken over the complex.
   ``They will go into a distressed area that is overrun by drug
dealers and criminal element and they will clean them up, kick out
all the wrong-doers, and then either sell or make housing available
for poor people,'' Rubin said.
   The Yahwehs, who teach that blacks are the true chosen people of
God, run businesses and property in predominantly black
neighborhoods. The Opa-locka apartment building was eventually
abandoned and now is empty.
   In the Opa-locka case, the Yahwehs, many carrying six-foot wooden
staffs, evicted everyone in the complex, threatening residents and
dumping their belongings on the street, according to the lawsuit,
which called the tactics a ``terrorist occupation strategy.''
   On Oct. 30, 1986, two tenants who publicly opposed the evictions
were shot and killed. Sect member Robert Rozier was later convicted
of murder in the case, and testified in the tenants' lawsuit.
   He said Yahweh ben Yahweh had tortured sect members and taught
them ritual murder techniques, but other witnesses disputed his
account. He also recounted acts of violence allegedly committed by
the sect in other communities.
   The judge did not rule on who was responsible for the deaths of
the two tenants, citing conflicting testimony.
   But he found that the church had engaged in running a criminal
enterprise, extortion and assault, and ordered it to pay $10,000 to
each tenant for emotional distrress, as well as reimburse them for
six times the value of the belongings they lost. An additional
$500,000 in punitive damages also will be divided among the tenants.
   Former tenant Shadell Hamilton, brother-in-law of one of those
killed, said he was pleased by the verdict, recalling his initial
sense of helplessness.
   ``I gave up. I said that there wasn't any justice, that nothing
would be done about it, because there were so many things they got
away with before,'' Hamilton said.
</TEXT>
