<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SunDagger     06-22 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sun Dagger,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Shift Moves Solstice Phenomenon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHACO CANYON, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Natural erosion apparently has blunted
a spike of light dubbed the ``sun dagger'' that ancient pueblo
Indians are believed to have used to mark the summer solstice.
   The dagger was formed by light shining between 9-foot-tall
sandstone slabs sitting just below the top of the 500-foot-tall
Fajada Butte in Chaco Canyon in northwestern New Mexico. On the
solstice, the longest day of the year, the light would shine on a
spiral-shaped petroglyph etched on rock behind the slabs.
   But erosion apparently caused a rock to shift, and on Wednesday
the dagger-shaped pattern of light missed its summer-solstice mark
on the petroglyph for perhaps the first time in 1,000 years,
researchers said. Instead, the light shined above and to the left of
the Indian pattern.
   ``We're used to this thing acting like a clock,'' physicist Rolf
Sinclair said Wednesday.
   The dagger widened and lengthened into ``an overgrown carrot,''
said Anna Sofaer, an artist and archaeo-astronomer who discovered
the dagger in 1977 in Chaco Culture National Historical Park, which
contains numerous ancient stone dwellings.
   The rock formation also cast distinctive light patterns at the
winter solstice and the fall and spring equinoxes _ when day and
night are of equal length.
   The petroglyph near the canyon's south entrance was believed to
have been carved between A.D. 950 and 1150, at the peak of the
Anasazi culture that once thrived in Chaco Canyon.
   Sinclair, Sofaer and others contend rocks originally might have
been manipulated to cause the sunlight patterns.
   But on Sunday, a group that included Sinclair discovered that one
of the rock slabs had shifted and had altered the phenomenon.
   ``It's very serious and sad,'' Ms. Sofaer said. ``We knew when we
first saw the site that it had a fragility that was remarkable.''
   Michael Zelik, a physics and astronomy professor at the
University of New Mexico, said the alteration raises questions about
how much or how often rocks have moved previously at the site and
about just how old it really is.
   However, Sinclair said it's clear the rocks have not moved much,
if at all, over the years. He said the erosion which caused the rock
to slip might be due to 10 years of relatively wet weather at Chaco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-Turks     06-22 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-Turks,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>250,000 Apply For Emigration, More Than 50,000 Cross Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bulgaria said Thursday that 250,000 ethnic
Turks have applied to emigrate to Turkey and 150,000 already have
their passports for an exodus from the communist country.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Ivan Ganev, giving the figures at a news
conference, said about 50,000 ``Bulgarian Moslems'' have crossed the
border into Turkey in the past month.
   In keeping with Bulgarian practice, he refused to speak of ethnic
Turks. The estimated 1 million ethnic Turks in Bulgaria, about
one-ninth of the country's population, have been forced to adopt
Bulgarian names since 1984 and had their language and religious
rites banned.
   In Ankara, Turkish officials said Thursday nearly 55,000 people
have crossed into Turkey from Bulgaria since last month, when police
used clubs and dogs to break up demonstrations by the ethnic Turks.
Officials said seven people were killed, but Western diplomats say
up to 30 died.
   Diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said up to 5,000
Turks, many of whom openly protesting ethnic and religious
discrimination, have been expelled since then.
   The mass voluntary emigration began May 29, when President Todor
Zhivkov said any Bulgarian citizen could leave the country. Zhivkov
clearly alluded to Bulgarian Turks, who have been receiving
passports under a new law that was passed in Parliament in May.
   An official in Haskovo, a town in southeastern Bulgaria, told The
Associated Press on Wednesday that his office has issued up to 2,000
passports a day since June 4.
   Thousands of ethnic Turks, many of them farmers and construction
workers, were observed this week on their way out of Bulgaria with
every piece of property they could take.
   Government officials at the news conference indicated the labor
drain is already disrupting agriculture and many industries.
   Ivan Angelov, a government adviser, said those departing had
withdrawn up to $260 million from banks, adding the sum might reach
$1 billion if people keep leaving.
   To cope with the sudden loss of manpower, Ganev said the the
government will order longer working hours, relocate workers,
reschedule summer vacations and start a crash retraining program.
   In addition, manpower is to be moved from ``not critical'' to
``critical'' industries or areas, Ganev told the news conference
without elaborating.
   Bulgaria has been short of labor even before the current wave of
emigration, and at least 30,000 Vietnamese are employed in Bulgarian
factories.
   Throughout the news conference, Ganev and five other senior
government officials blamed the huge outflow of Turks on Turkish
propaganda and ``instigation.''
   ``Turkey has whipped up a psychosis among the Moslem
population,'' Ganev said, accusing Turkish Premier Turgut Oezal of
repeatedly issuing military threats against Bulgaria.
   Bulgaria's Christian Slavs and ethnic Turks have been deeply
suspicious of one another since the five-century rule of Turkey's
Ottoman Empire.
   Asked if Bulgaria would accept the assistance of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees, he said, ``We have no refugees, so we do
not need him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchClosings     06-22 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Closings,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priests Say They Will Defy Orders to Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve Roman Catholic priests say they and their
parishioners will defy orders by Cardinal Edmund C. Szoka to close
their churches by June 30.
   More than 200 Roman Catholics at St. Stanislaus Catholic Church
applauded Wednesday's action by the priests, who said they would
continue to celebrate Masses beyond the closing date.
   ``Take a look at these guys and remember their faces,'' said the
Rev. Norm Thomas, one of the 12 priests. ``Their median age is 50 so
they can only do it for the next 35 years.''
   Archdiocese of Detroit spokesman Jay Berman said priests holding
services past the deadline would be in violation of church policy.
   ``When a bishop establishes a parish, it's established _ when he
closes it, it's closed,'' Berman said. ``You can't go out and erect
(a church) without a bishop establishing a canonical decree, no
matter what Father wants to do.''
   Priests and parishioners also said they would begin a three-day
fast Sunday in hopes of influencing a civil court decision expected
Wednesday.
   Wayne County Circuit Judge James Hathaway will rule on a request
for a temporary restraining order to stop the closings until all
appeals made through the church have been exhausted.
   The threatened parishes have lost an appeal to leaders of the 1.5
million-member Detroit Archdiocese. They also have appealed to
church leaders in the Vatican.
   Szoka ordered 30 churches closed or merged with others, citing
money problems, little active participation by parishioners and a
priest shortage.
</TEXT>
