<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--Scouts-Acid     06-22 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Scouts-Acid,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swimming Girl Scouts Injured by Acid in Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUPACA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30 Girl Scouts suffered minor burns
when a malfunctioning pump on a water theme park slide released too
much muriatic acid, authorities said.
   The girls' injuries ranged from skin irritation to blistering,
according to officials at Riverside Medical Center, where the girls
were examined and treated. Seven required treatment for skin burns
or eye irritation.
   More than 100 Brownie Girl Scouts, ages 7 to 9, went to the
Waupaca Waterthrills Park on Wednesday as part of daylong outing.
   ``The girls started complaining immediately when they got out of
the water,'' said Brownie leader Paulette White. ``Some of the girls
only went down the water slide once and complained that they were
starting to burn and itch.''
   Water park officials said the problem was traced to a
malfunctioning pump that releases acid to maintain a neutral pH
level for the water. The pump was fixed.
</TEXT>
