<FIRST>r w AM-BismarckChronology     06-22 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bismarck Chronology,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Short Life of a Mighty Battleship</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bismarck Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chronology compiled by the National
Geographic Society of the fate of the German World War II battleship
Bismarck:
   1936 _ Construction starts in Hamburg of the 820-foot ship with a
displacement, when fully loated, of more than 50,000 tons, carrying
eight 15-inch guns, 12 5.9-inch guns and 16 4.1-inch guns and a crew
of 2,200 and capable of a top speed of 30 knots.
   Feb. 14, 1939 _ On St. Valentine's Day, Adolf Hitler launches the
ship.
   May 19, 1941 _ After more than two years in fitting and shakedown
cruises, the Bismarck sets sail from Gdynia, Poland with orders to
sink Allied merchant ships in the Atlantic while evading engagement
with allied warships.
   May 20, 1941 _ A Swedish cruiser spots the Bismarck and its
escort, the Prinz Eugen, off the coast of neutral Sweden. Later they
are sighted off the coast of Norway.
   May 21, 1941 _ British Spitfires over the Bergen-Korsfjord region
of Norway spot the two German ships. The British send the battle
cruiser Hood to join other British ships on patrol in the Denmark
Strait.
   May 22, 1941 _ More British forces head for the search zone.
   May 23, 1941 _ In the Denmark Strait beteen Greenland and
Iceland, the British cruisers Suffolk and Norfolk sight the German
ship threading through a minefield. The Bismarck opens fire, but the
British retire safely. The British follow the Germans despite rain
and snow storms and dangerous ice floes. The Hood and the Prince of
Wales are closing in from about 250 miles away.
   May 24 _ At 5:35 a.m., the Hood and Prince of Wales sight the
Bismarck and open fire. The Germans return fire. At 6:01 a.m., a
massive explosion sinks the Hood, leaving only three of its 1,419
crewmen alive. The Bismarck suffers a ruptured fuel tank. The
Bismarck engages the British again in the evening. The Prinz Eugen
escapes. The Bismarck's commander decides to make for a French port
for repairs. A British force heads to the area from Gibraltar.
Around midnight, nine British biplanes attack, causing little damage.
   May 25 _ About 3 a.m., the Bismarck evades its chasers and heads
for the safety of U-boat patrols and Luftwaffe air cover, near the
coast of France.
   May 26 _ A British plane spots the Bismarck. In a last-ditch
effort to stop it before it reaches safety, planes from a British
carrier score two torpedo hits that wreck the Bismarck's steering
gear and jam her rudders, only hours from safety. The Bismarck's
fate is sealed.
   May 27 _ At 8:47 a.m., a British force opens up on the limping
Bismarck, putting its main guns out of action. By 10 a.m., the
Bismarck is a battered hulk. By 10:39 a.m. it has capsized and sunk,
coming to rest upright on the ocean floor with only 115 of its crew
of 2,200 rescued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
