<DOCNO> AP890622-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Iran     06-22 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Iran,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Agree to Religious Contacts With Iran; Indicate Arms Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Thursday strengthened its ties
with Iran, agreeing to exchange delegations of Moslem religious
leaders and indicating it would send weaponry to its Islamic
neighbor.
   The agreement with Iran came as the Soviet Union struggles with a
resurgence of Islamic fundamentalism and conflicts between its
Christians and 50 million Moslems.
   The agreement was part of a broad declaration signed by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Iranian Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, whose visit to the Soviet Union has defrosted a decade
of icy relations.
   It implies future Soviet weapons sales to Iran, by promising the
superpower's cooperation in ``strengthening the defense capacity''
of its southern neighbor. At the same time, the document commits
both nations to strive ``to rid the world of aggression.''
   Rafsanjani later sidestepped questions about arms deals. He said
only that Iran was trying to be self-sufficient in arms but has some
``technical requirements that we would like to see met by various
sources.''
   In Washington, Secretary of State James A. Baker III told the
House Foreign Affairs Committee that U.S. policy toward Iran would
be guided by developments in the country _ and not by its
relationship with the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union was Iraq's major weapons supplier during the
eight-year Iran-Iraq war, but even then, the Soviets arranged for
the sale of arms to Iran through third countries.
   During a state dinner Wednesday, Rafsanjani invited Gorbachev to
visit Iran. If Gorbachev accepts, he would be the first leader of a
major power to visit Tehran since the Islamic revolution in 1979.
   The declaration says both nations ``will strive for a broad
acquaintance with each other's life, culture, convictions, customs
and traditions.'' It specifically called for the governments to
exchange delegations of religious leaders.
   The Soviet Union has been troubled in the past 1{ years by unrest
among its more than 100 ethnic groups, especially the 50 million
Moslems on its southern borders.
   Moslem Azerbaijanis fought with Christian Armenians, resulting in
more than 90 deaths last year, and in recent weeks 100 people have
been killed in the primarily Moslem Central Asian republics in
rioting prompted by ethnic and economic problems.
   An official from one of those republics, Uzbekistan, attributed
the violence to a group trying to create a ``pan-Islamic front''
aimed at hysteria and the ouster of the European population. Soviet
reports occasionally mention Iranian flags and photographs of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini being carried by demonstrators.
   Rafsanjani, asked about the Central Asian clashes at a news
conference Thursday, said his country would not interfere with
Soviet internal affairs.
   However, he added, ``we consider Mr. Gorbachev has a long way to
come in providing freedoms and people's participation in the
democratic process.'' He did not elaborate.
   Rafsanjani, originally expected to leave Thursday, traveled to
Leningrad instead and was reportedly planning to stop in Azerbaijan
on his way home. Iran has a consulate in the republic's capital,
which Tehran Radio called ``the Moslem city of Baku'' in announcing
the changed itinerary.
   At the news conference, Rafsanjani emphasized that the talks with
Gorbachev had gone well.
   ``The optimism that we had before the meetings has been totally
justified,'' Rafsanjani said.
   On other issues, Rafsanjani:
   _ accused the United States of unspecified ``plots and
conspiracies'' against Iran when asked about the possibility that
relations would improve after the death of Khomeini, Iran's
spiritual leader.
   _ said Khomeini's order stands for the killing of Salman Rushdie,
the British author of the novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' which many
Moslems consider blasphemous. Khomeini's judgment was based on
Islamic law and ``this is not the kind of prescription that can be
reversed. There is no one in Iran who could reverse it.''
   _ said Afghans must be free to resolve their differences without
outside interference after the withdrawal of Soviet soldiers from
their country more than four months ago.
   Gorbachev and Rafsanjani agreed to cooperate in several areas,
including atomic energy, space and gas processing.
   Rafsanjani suggested a Soviet-Iranian space voyage, and Gorbachev
ordered his deputies to begin working out the details.
   Rafsanjani emphasized in remarks distributed by Tass on Wednesday
that several months before his death on June 3, Khomeini called for
better relations with the Soviet Union. Tass said Gorbachev and
Khomeini exchanged messages in February, and since then their
foreign ministers have met four times.
</TEXT>
