<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Poindexter     06-22 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Request for Access to Classified Documents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has rejected a request by
former National Security Adviser John Poindexter for access to
classified documents in the Iran-Contra case.
   U.S. District Court Judge Harold Greene also said Poindexter must
narrow his other requests for material.
   The ruling follows statements last week by independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh that prosecutors would abandon substantial portions
of the indictment against Poindexter.
   Poindexter is charged with four counts of obstructing and making
false statements to Congress in connection with Lt. Col. Oliver
North's activities on behalf of the Contras and a November 1985 arms
shipment to Iran.
   Walsh plans to retain portions of the indictment alleging that
Poindexter conspired with North and others in the obstructions and
false statements. He said he would seek dismissal of theft and wire
fraud charges against Poindexter pertaining to the diversion of Iran
arms sale proceeds.
   Poindexter should ``reformulate and limit his demands,'' Greene
said in a four-page order signed Wednesday and made public Thursday.
   The judge rejected a wide-ranging request for classified
documents that Poindexter filed June 12, four days before Walsh
announced his intention to reduce the scope of the indictment.
   An 64-page request for material filed May 15 demanded that the
government give Poindexter ``all documents created between Dec. 1,
1981, and the present'' referring to U.S. support for the Contras.
   Poindexter also demanded notebooks, diaries and other documents
relating to former President Reagan, Vice President Bush, CIA
Director William Casey and former Secretary of State George Shultz,
as well as all material tending to establish that Reagan or Bush
directed the National Security Council staff to ensure that the
Contras would be supported during a congressional ban on military
aid to the rebels.
</TEXT>
