<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--ColumbusMonument     06-22 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Columbus Monument,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Kicks Off Restoration of Columbus Monument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials tossed a life preserver Thursday to
Christopher Columbus to mark the beginning of a restoration project
of the crumbling monument.
   ``This sculpture, excellent in its artistry and priceless in its
symbolism, is among our city's most important cultural artifacts,
and it will be saved,'' said Mayor Edward Koch. He helped attach a
plywood life preserver to its base in a ceremony with other city
officials and prominent Italian-Americans.
   Since 1892, the 13-foot-tall Carrara marble statue of Columbus,
maps in hand, has gazed down from atop a 26-foot granite column. On
the pedestal, a winged figure, now virtually faceless, looks at a
globe.
   The city wants the monument, designed by the Italian sculptor
Gaetano Russo, restored for the 500th anniversary in 1992 of
Columbus' discovery of America.
   The monument has been corroded by sulfuric acid in the air. The
Columbus Citizens Foundation raised the money for the restoration,
which is expected to cost $275,000.
</TEXT>
