<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalTreatment     06-22 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Treatment,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uninsured Patients Who Are Hospitalized Get Less Treatment, Study
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People without medical insurance not only are less
likely to get into hospitals than insured patients, they also get
less treatment once they're there, a new study of Boston hospital
patients has found.
   But the finding doesn't necessarily mean the uninsured get worse
care, because doctors may keep insured patients in the hospital
longer than necessary and may give them more treatment than they
need, researchers said.
   Previous studies have revealed that the poor, minorities and
people without health insurance have less chance of getting medical
care than others.
   But ``there has been a feeling that once you get into the system,
everybody is treated the same,'' said Joel Weissman, a health-policy
specialist at Harvard School of Public Health and a co-author of the
new study. ``What we're seeing is that even after you get into the
hospital, these patterns persist.''
   Weissman and Dr. Arnold M. Epstein, also of Harvard, examined the
treatment of more than 65,000 patients at 52 hospitals in the Boston
area during 1983.
   They found that uninsured patients, on average, underwent fewer
procedures and were discharged earlier than patients covered by Blue
Cross. The uninsured also were discharged earlier than Medicaid
patients, the study said.
   Though the differences were not great, they should serve as a
``red flag'' to spur further investigation, Weissman said in a
telephone interview Thursday.
   More studies will be necessary to determine if the Boston-area
trends reflect those in the rest of the nation, said Weissman, who
added that Harvard is currently working to update the 1983 findings.
   The study also found that people with different types of medical
problems tended to end up at different types of hospitals, with the
major teaching hospitals and public hospitals taking the brunt of
the tough cases among the uninsured.
   ``Although we lacked data on income and housing situation, the
results are consistent with the popular view of the urban public
hospital as the provider of last resort for persons with multiple
problems at the bottom of the socioeconomic scale,'' the researchers
said.
   After correcting statistically for differences in severity of
illness and other factors, the researchers found that uninsured
patients stayed in the hospital half a day less than Blue Cross
patients _ 5.36 compared with 5.79 days.
   The uninsured underwent about 7 percent fewer procedures _
operations or tests _ per stay than Blue Cross patients, 1.16 vs.
1.25, respectively, the researchers said.
   ``The effects we found occurred in all types of hospitals,
including major teaching and public hospitals _ institutions
commonly considered to be relatively blind to payment source,'' the
researchers reported in Friday's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
   Though the results suggest that hospitals or physicians tailor
people's medical care according to ability to pay, or that patients
do so themselves to avoid high bills, it doesn't necessarily mean
the uninsured are getting inferior care, the researchers said.
   ``We know, for example, that lengths of stay have been decreasing
nationwide during the last decade, but so far there is little
evidence that the quality of care has been reduced,'' they said.
   Longer stays and more procedures among insured patients in the
Boston area may represent overuse of medical resources, they said.
   ``Further research is warranted to clarify whether lower
utilization represents inadequate care and whether alternative
financial and organization arrangements can remedy the situation,''
the researchers said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
