<FIRST>r i AM-SovietShip     06-22 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Ship,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crippled Soviet Liner Reaches Arctic Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crippled Soviet ocean liner Maxim Gorky
reached a remote archipelago for repairs Thursday, two days after
its bow was ripped open when it hit an iceberg while on a cruise.
   The ship reached Coles Bay on Svalbard, the largest of the
Spitzbergen Archipelago, said Jan Klyver, an administrative official
for the Norwegian islands. The secluded bay has no wharf or
facilities but offers shelter from wind and waves, he said.
   The 630-foot Maxim Gorky was kept afloat with pumps after a
20-foot gash was ripped in its bow and it took on 18,000 tons of
water during a midnight sun cruise in the Norwegian Sea.
   All of the 575 passengers and 378 crew were rescued. The
passengers and some crew were brought to shelter at Spitzbergen and
flown home from there.
   Soviet spokesman Andrei Romanov told the Norwegian news agency
NTB the Maxim Gorky anchored in the bay with 184 crew aboard.
Temporary repairs were being made there to allow the ship to sail to
Bremerhaven, West Germany, its port of embarkation.
   He did not estimate how long repairs would take. Soviet news
reports said the ship would be back in service in three weeks.
   The Soviet newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya said Thursday the ship
may have rammed a metal object frozen in the ice or that a large old
piece of ice unexpectedly surfaced.
   Norwegian maritime experts said the Maxim Gorky was sailing too
fast for conditions in an area clogged with drifting ice up to 20
feet thick.
   Sigurn Kleiven, commander of the Norwegian coast guard vessel
Senja, which rescued passengers, dimissed claims the Soviet crew was
drunk during the accident or rescue. A Norwegian doctor aboard the
Senja said Wednesday that Soviet sailors were intoxicated.
   ``There was absolutely no drunkenness on the part of the Soviet
crew involved in the rescue,'' Kleiven was quoted as saying in the
daily newspaper Aftenposten. He did say, however, that some waiters,
service personnel and passengers had been drinking.
   Some passengers spent seven hours in open boats among the ice
floes waiting to be taken to safety and were given alcohol by the
crew.
   ``Drinking alcohol during exposure to cold is a bad
combination,'' said Mads Gilbert, the Norwegian doctor.
</TEXT>
