<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0656 06-22 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0656,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Professor Stabbed to Death, Arab Killed in West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Police said...' to UPDATE number of those questioned;
picks up 8th graf, `Army Radio...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Volunteers, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Israeli history professor was
stabbed to death in Jerusalem on Thursday, and police said they were
investigating whether the killing was a terrorist attack.
   In the occupied West Bank, Israeli troops shot a Palestinian man
to death and detained 30 others during a raid on the village of
Silwad, an army spokesman said.
   Soldiers also shot and wounded four Palestinian youths in clashes
with stone-throwers in the occupied Gaza Strip, Arab hospital
officials said.
   The body of Hebrew University professor Menachem Stern was found
by schoolchildren in a park near Israel's Parliament building,
police spokesman Uzi Sandori said.
   Stern, 64, was stabbed several times in the chest, Sandori said.
He said robbery was ruled out as a motive because a watch and money
were found on Stern's body.
   Asked whether investigators believed terrorists were to blame,
Sandori said: ``This direction is also being checked.''
   Israel television reported police have questioned 70 people,
mostly Arabs, and have detained two of the Arabs.
   Army Radio said Israel's Shin Bet secret service was called in to
investigate.
   Stern, a winner of Israel's top prize for academic excellence,
also lectured at Harvard and Oxford universities.
   Jewish academics said he was considered the world's leading
expert on the history of the Jews during the Second Temple period,
166 B.C. to A.D. 70, when Jews in the land of Israel were ruled by
Greek and Roman conquerors.
   During this time, the Jews rebuilt their ancient temple in
Jerusalem for the second time and established their second
independent commonwealth.
   Professor Daniel Schwartz, an associate of Stern's, said he was a
dedicated academician who was ``not involved in anything political.''
   He said Stern ``was aware there were some dangers involved
walking around Jerusalem'' and that his wife was concerned about the
park path he often took to work ``because it was out of sight.''
   The death of the Arab in Silwad raised to 528 the number of
Palestinians killed in the 18{-month uprising against Israeli rule
of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Twenty-three Israelis also
have died in the violence.
   The army spokesman's office said 22-year-old Abdel Raouf Mohammed
Hamad was fatally shot ``after he refused to obey an order to stop''
when troops raided the community, 12 miles north of Jerusalem.
   It was the latest in a series of search-and-arrest missions to
capture Palestinian activists.
   The Arabs detained during the raid were suspected of stoning or
firebombing cars of Jewish settlers on nearby highways, the army
said.
   Palestinians in nearby villages said Thursday they received
unsigned warning notes from settlers threatening retaliatory action
against any attacks.
   ``We are going to be forced to take harsh measures against all
those who are behind the disturbances,'' said the fliers, printed in
Arabic and strewn on village streets.
   Jewish settlers have been blamed for a series of attacks on
Palestinians in recent weeks. The latest incident occured on Tuesday
after the funeral of an American-born Jewish settler, Frederick
Steven Rosenfeld, who allegedly was stabbed to death by Palestinians.
   After the funeral, a settler opened fire with an Uzi submachine
gun on Arab laborers on a street near Tel Aviv, wounding two. The
settler's name and hometown have been withheld by police.
   A Tel Aviv court extended the settler's detention for 15 days in
a closed-door hearing on Thursday. Police said he also was under
investigation for organizing other attacks on Arabs, Army Radio
reported.
   A court convicted a Palestinian man in the stabbing deaths of two
elderly Jews on a Jerusalem street on May 3. Three others were
injured in the attack.
   The court said Nidal Abdel Razik Zaloum, 25, from the West Bank
town of El-Bireh, confessed to the killings. He is to be sentenced
Friday. The prosecutor has asked for two consecutive life terms.
</TEXT>
