<DOCNO> AP890622-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SeabrookTest     06-22 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Test,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valve Problem Stops Low-Power Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Low-power testing of the reactor at the
Seabrook nuclear power plant was halted Thursday because of a
problem with a steam valve, operators said.
   The reactor was running at 3 percent of maximum power at the
engineers shut it down, said spokesman Ron Sher.
   ``The valve remained open longer than it should have, drawing too
much steam away from the plant's steam generators,'' Sher said.
``Under our strict operating procedures, control room operators
manually shut down the reactor.''
   He said the engineers went to work to correct the problem so the
reactor could be re-started.
   He said the valve was on the non-nuclear side of the plant. Hot,
pressurized, contaminated water from the reactor flows through a
heat exchanger and back to the reactor. On the non-nuclear side,
water flows into the heat exchanger, picks up heat from the nuclear
side and becomes steam to drive the turbines that spin the plant's
generators.
   Sher said the valve directs steam that normally would drive the
plant's turbines back to a steam condenser instead. He said the
steam bypasses the turbines during low-power testing.
   Because it stayed open, more steam condensed to water, thus
cooling the system too quickly.
   Sher said the problem wasn't considered serious enough to warrant
notifications to state and federal regulatory officials, but Nuclear
Regulatory Commission observers were in the control room at the time.
   Sher said the valve, one of about 6,000 in the plant, is not
associated with three other valves that malfunctioned earlier this
month, delaying the start of the tests.
   ``The reason we do tests is to ensure that all plant systems are
working as designed. The low-power testing of the reactor in the
past nine days has gone very well, and this is the first
interruption we've had in the schedule,'' he said.
   Seabrook officials won regulatory permission to conduct the tests
despite long opposition from Massachusetts and anti-nuclear
activists who argue nearby beaches and communities could never be
safely evacuated in the event of an accident.
   The plant has not yet won a commercial operating license, but
utility officials predict they will be selling Seabrook power by the
end of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
