<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-US     06-22 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-US,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S.-British Agreement on Developing New Missile for Britain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain has signed an agreement with the United
States to help develop a new air-launched nuclear missile, a Defense
Ministry spokesman said Thursday.
   The spokesman, who refused to be identified, said the agreement
for a U.S. feasibility study on updating one of Britain's key
strategic weapons _ a sensitive issue with the Soviet Union _ was
signed Dec. 1 but not announced at the time.
   Officials acknowledged the agreement after Jane's Defense Weekly
reported it. It said the American company Martin Marietta Corp. is
investigating with British Aerospace PLC the possibility of
developing a new tactical air-to-surface missile.
   The missile with a range of 250-370 miles and fired from Tornado
bombers would replace Britain's aging WE177 free-fall nuclear bomb.
   The spokesman said the U.S. agreement did not mean that the
British were abandoning a possible deal with France.
   ``We have not signed a similar memorandum of understanding with
the French, but both American and French systems remain open as
options for consideration,'' he said.
   However, the Anglo-French project appeared virtually certain of
being abandoned. It involved developing a longer-range version of
France's ASMP nuclear air-to-surface missiles.
   Negotiations began about two years ago, there has been no sign of
progress, and Defense Ministry sources have said in recent months
that the French system is unsuitable for British bombers.
   The strategic importance of air-launched nuclear weapons has
increased following the 1987 agreement between the United States and
the Soviet Union to withdraw all their medium-range, land-based
nuclear weapons from Europe.
   The Soviet Union has complained that updating air-launched
missiles violates the spirit of the 1987 agreement.
   Jane's, an authoritative magazine, said a firm decision on
developing with U.S. companies a new weapon for Britain was expected
in 1992.
   ``The plan is likely to attract criticism from the opposition
United Kingdom Labor Party, the Soviet Union and others who consider
its development inopportune in the present East-West climate,''
Jane's said.
   The magazine said Boeing Aerospace Co. was competing with Martin
Marietta for the British contract.
   Boeing has proposed a variation of its Short Range Attack Missile
II being developed for the U.S. Air Force. Martin Marietta has
signed an agreement to investigate adapting its Supersonic
Low-Altitude Target being developed for the U.S. Navy, Jane's said.
</TEXT>
