<HEAD>Tehran Radio Hints Relations With Britain May Improve</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tehran radio indicated Thursday the
British High Court's decision allowing Moslems to challenge
Britain's blasphemy laws may help ease tension between the countries
over ``The Satanic Verses.''
   In the first Iranian reaction to the High Court ruling Monday,
the official radio said the move ``could perhaps be considered as a
step aimed at correcting previous stances.''
   Also on Thursday, Iranian Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani
said in Moscow the death sentence imposed on British author Salman
Rushdie for writing ``The Satanic Verses'' still is in force,
despite the death of Ayatollah Ruholla Khomeini.
   The sentence, issued by Khomeini, was based on Islamic law, and
``this is not the kind of prescription that can be reversed. There
is no one in Iran who could reverse it,'' Ransanjani told a news
conference after two days of talks with Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   The death sentence, issued Feb. 14, sent Rushdie into hiding and
led to a break in relations between Britain and Iran.
   In Britain, the Moslem Action Group had sought to prosecute
Rushdie, but a court refused to issue summonses on grounds Britain's
law of blasphemy applies only to Christians.
   On Monday, Britain's High Court granted Abdal Choudhury, a
spokesman for the Moslem Action Group, permission to challenge the
lower court's decision.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia, said: ``It seems that in view
of the fact that everyone has conceded that the book is insulting
... and in view of the harm that has been done to that country's
reputation and political standing due to its irrational support for
`The Satanic Verses,' London's conservative government now finds it
appropriate to revise its policies.''
   Many Moslems consider ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemous. British
officials also have conceded that the book contained material that
could be offensive but said this was no excuse for Khomeini to
``incite murder.''
</TEXT>
