<DOCNO> AP890622-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OhioGarbage     06-22 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ohio Garbage,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Told Out-of-Staters Trashing Ohio, Buckeyes Are ``Truly
Engaged''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress was told Thursday that out-of-staters
are trashing Ohio, leaving Buckeyes ``truly enraged'' about having
tons of garbage heaped on them by their neighboring states.
   An Ohio official, saying ``we could become the next New Jersey in
just a few years,'' urged Congress to slap a $40-a-ton fee on
long-haul garbage to discourage interstate trafficking in trash.
   ``We simply do not have adequate disposal capacity to become the
East Coast's dumping ground,'' Richard Sahli, chairman of the Ohio
Solid Waste Management Advisory Council, told a House subcommittee.
   Donald Deieso, assistant commissioner of the New Jersey
Department of Environmental Protection, said ``we understand
completely'' the concerns of states gaining garbage, since New
Jersey had been a dump for New York and Pennsylvania. He suggested
Congress order every state to become self-sufficient.
   Ohio last year took in 2.4 million tons of out-of-state waste,
double what came in the previous year. Nearly 20 percent of the
waste disposed of in Ohio is generated elsewhere and the heap is
growing, Sahli told the transportation and hazardous materials
subcommittee.
   Landfills are filling up or being closed because of pollution
problems, Sahli said.
   ``We in Ohio have a home-grown crisis on our hands,'' he said.
``The importing of wastes has truly enraged the citizens of Ohio.''
   ``We're the dumping ground,'' agreed Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio,
chairman of the subcommittee.
   Witnesses said Ohio isn't alone.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council said 15,000 landfills have
closed over the past 10 years, leaving about 5,000 nationwide. All
of Florida's landfills must close within 10 years because of threats
to groundwater, the environmental group added.
   Paul Templet, secretary of the Louisiana Department of
Environmental Quality, said that state is down to 40 landfills,
compared with 800 in operation in 1980.
   ``Solid waste management in Louisiana has reached crisis
proportions,'' said Templet, who asked the subcommittee to consider
a national recycling program and strict landfill guidelines.
   Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., said his state has been
``victimized by the lack of federal policy'' on solid waste.
   ``States like mine are virtually unprotected,'' he told the panel.
   Richardson asked the panel to consider his bill giving states the
right to reject the interstate transfer of solid waste.
   Rep. Paul Kanjorski, D-Pa., said he was introducing legislation
to treat trash the same way the government treats low-level
radioactive waste. His bill would force states to develop regional
compacts to deal with the garbage problem collectively.
   The Ohio official asked the panel to tax garbage sent long
distances and then use the money to encourage recycling and to
increase Environmental Protection Agency funding for developing
better ways of handling solid waste.
   ``Such a tax would act as an incentive to states to take care of
their own waste disposal needs and not create devastating economic
dislocation and potential environmental problems in communities
located hundreds of miles away,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
