<FIRST>r a AM-LynchTrial     06-22 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lynch Trial,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Woman Guilty On All Counts In Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of ``shopping around'' at
nurseries for a baby to steal was convicted Thursday of killing a
couple she had stalked for days, snatching their 9-day-old son and
trying to pass him off as her own.
   Jurors who found Joyce Lynch guilty on all counts meet Friday to
begin deciding whether she should be executed by lethal injection or
sentenced to life in prison without probation or parole.
   Mrs. Lynch, 36, had accused her husband, Richard, of killing
Beverly and Joseph Gibson Jr. on Christmas Eve 1987, drugging her
and duping her into believing that she had given birth. Lynch, 27,
faces a trial in September.
   Both were charged with two counts of murder, two counts of felony
murder, one count of conspiracy and one count each of possession of
a deadly weapon during the commission of a felony, burglary and
unlawful imprisonment.
   The state contends the Lynches shot the Gibsons and took
9-day-old Matthew Gibson because Mrs. Lynch could no longer have
children.
   Prosecutors accused them of ``shopping around'' at nurseries
``until they stumbled upon Matthew Gibson.''
   ``They hunted the Gibsons down, stalked them for at least a week
and murdered them to get that child,'' Deputy Attorney General
William Nicholas said during closing arguments Wednesday in Kent
County Superior Court.
   During 16 days of testimony, the defense portrayed Mrs. Lynch as
a victim of her husband. She claimed Lynch controlled her by
injecting her with overdoses of a prescription pain-killer she
needed for a back ailment.
   Mrs. Lynch, who had two children from a previous marriage, also
claimed her husband duped her into believing she was pregnant, and
told her she had given birth to Matthew while she was asleep.
   She said she was at the crime scene, but because she was heavily
drugged, she thought it was a dream. When she awakened, there was a
baby.
   The state contended she was the mastermind because she knew she
had had a hysterectomy in 1978.
   Gibson, 32, was found in a pool of blood by his then-5-year-old
daughter, Rebecca, and 1-year-old son, John Gregory.
   Mrs. Gibson, 27, was found slumped over the steering wheel of her
car, clutching the cloth diaper she used when burping Matthew.
   The prosecution said one of the Lynches took Matthew from her
arms. Matthew was with the Lynches when they were arrested Jan. 7,
1988. Matthew and his brother and sister have been raised by their
paternal grandparents.
</TEXT>
