<HEAD>Najib Addresses Military Review</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib on Thursday convened
the first military review meeting since the Soviet withdrawal from
Afghanistan and said the goverment needs ``a new tempo and dramatic
steps'' to fight the guerrillas.
   ``It is too early to talk about final victory,'' Najib told
members of the 22-member Supreme Defense Council and military
commanders from Afghanistan's 28 provinces. ``We should think in
terms of how to get rid of the imposed war and put an end to it.''
   Western journalists were invited to attend the inauguration of
the meeting, held a day after Kabul announced it had a broken a
15-week rebel siege of the eastern city of Jalalabad. Guerrillas
based in Pakistan denied the claim.
   The lifting of the siege would represent the biggest military
victory for the government since the last Soviet troops withdrew in
February, ending their nine-year involvement in Afghanistan.
   The military review was the first since the Soviet withdrawal,
and diplomats say it was called to plan a new strategy against the
rebels.
   Najib used the occasion to renew attacks on Pakistan, which
supports the Moslem guerrillas fighting Najib's Soviet-backed
government.
   ``The grave dangers emanating from the satanic plans of Pakistan
... pose a serious threat to peace, security and stability in the
region,'' he said.
   The president also said Washington and other rebel supporters
``did not want to stop the war, they want to continue the
bloodshed.''
