<FIRST>r w AM-OwlForests     06-22 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Owl Forests,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service Chief Say Owl Data Too Skimpy to Reduce Logging</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Too little is known about the spotted owl to
justify closing off vast portions of the ancient forests of the
Northwest to logging, the head of the U.S. Forest Service said
Thursday.
   ``I don't think we ought to penalize the people of the Northwest,
throw people out of work, close down towns, until a biological
decision can be made properly,'' F. Dale Robertson, chief of the
Forest Service, said as two House subcommittees wrapped up two days
of joint hearings.
   Robertson said his agency has begun a five-year study of the owl,
which is thought to nest only in the old-growth forests of
Washington state, Oregon and northern California.
   He said there was insufficient scientific on the owl to justify a
50 percent reduction in the timber harvest from the national forests
of the Northwest this year.
   A federal judge in Seattle has enjoined the agency from offering
162 timber sales planned during the current fiscal year in those
forests involving 1.4 billion board feet.
   Robertson said that represents roughly 25 percent of the timber
sale program scheduled this year and said the injunction might be
expanded so it would eventually affect sales involving 2.5 billion
board feet or half of the sales planned in the region.
   The injunction was sought by environmentalists who want to have
the owl protected as a threatened or endangered species as part of
their campaign to halt logging in the old-growth forests of the
Northwest. The timber industry has claimed such protection would
create an economic catastrophe for dozens of one-mill towns in the
region.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has proposed the owl for
listing as a threatened species, but it will take between 18 months
and two years before a final decision is made.
   The hearings were held by the national parks and public lands
subcommittee of the House Interior Committee and the forests, family
farms and energy subcommittee of the House Agriculture Committee.
   Robertson said that 60 percent of the timber available for
harvest in western Oregon and Washington was old-growth, much of it
prime habitat for the spotted owl.
   Robertson faced harsh criticism from Oregon Democratic Rep. Peter
DeFazio, who charged the Forest Service had done little since the
injunction was issued four months ago to soften its impact on the
region.
   ``Are you trying to precipitate a crisis in the hope that
Congress will bail you out?'' DeFazio asked, adding that the agency
has yet to appeal the injunction and took two months before it
responded to a letter he wrote asking if there were alternative
sales that could be offered quickly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
