<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Shipyard     06-22 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Shipyard,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Leaders Reject Shipyard's Pay Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor representatives at South Korea's
second largest shipyard Thursday rejected a 20 percent pay increase
negotiated by their union leaders, dimming prospects for the
debt-stricken business.
   Managers of Daewoo Shipbuilding and Heavy Machinery Co. at Okpo,
off the south coast, threatened to shut down the facility if workers
strike.
   Company and labor union leaders had reached a tentative agreement
to give the 13,000 workers an average 20 percent pay rise from Jan.
1 next year.
   But the union's 54-member executive committe turned down the
agreement by a vote of 28-26. Hard-line union leaders demanded an
immediate increase.
   Yard workers earn an average $525 a month and company officials
say large wage increases would put the shipyard out of business.
   Workers demanded a 53 percent pay raise May 9. Management
responded with a wage freeze and threatened to close the yard.
   The shipyard at Koje island was virtually shut down May 29, when
two workers died after setting themselves on fire in protest.
   The trouble started two months after the government deployed
police and used strongarm tactics that left hundreds of people
injured to end a prolonged strike at Hyundai Heavy Industries, the
country's largest shipyard.
   Government officials have urged Daewoo workers and company
officials to continue negotiating and suspended a $600 million
rescue package for the yard, which is about $1.6 billion in debt.
   Daewoo had to raise another $600 million on its own.
   The shipyard opened in 1981 and can build up to 1.2 million tons
of shipping a year _ 30 percent of the country's combined
shipbuilding capacity.
   Daewoo has a backlog of foreign orders worth $1.17 billion.
</TEXT>
