<FIRST>r i AM-Zambia-Bombings     06-22 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zambia-Bombings,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>ANC Accuses South Africa of New Bombing Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The African National Congress said Thursday
three of its officials were wounded in a bomb blast in Lusaka, and
it accused South Africa of starting a new terror campaign.
   Wednesday night's blast in Lusaka was the fourth bombing this
week in the Zambian capital, said ANC spokesman Tom Sebina.
   One official of the guerrrilla organization was seriously injured
in the latest explosion, which destroyed an ANC welfare office, he
said.
   ``A new phase of bombings and assassinations by South African
agents appears to have begun and we are stepping up our security,''
Sebina said.
   In the worst incident, two bombs near the ANC headquarters in
downtown Lusaka damaged a gasoline station and killed one man on
Monday. Police said they believe the victim was carrying the bomb
that killed him.
   No one was killed in the other blasts.
   The ANC, the main guerrilla organization fighting Pretoria's
white-run government, is banned in South Africa and has its
headquarters-in-exile in Lusaka.
   In recent years, ANC facilities in black-governed nations
neighboring South Africa have become regular targets of Pretoria's
military and sabotage attacks.
   Sebina said that after a lull of several months the latest
bombings may have been carried out by a group of agents believed to
have infiltrated Zambia recently.
   One of the aims of South African sabotage is ``to create
conditions whereby our host governments will become jittery about
our presence,'' he said.
