<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Coach     06-22 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Coach,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Narrows Ability to Sue for Discrimination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court added Thursday to a string of
defeats for civil rights forces with a decision that gives cities
new protection against certain lawsuits accusing them of racial bias
and other violations.
   Voting 5-4, the justices used the case of a former Dallas high
school football coach to narrow the scope of a century-old civil
rights law. The coach said he was transferred to another school
because he is white.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, writing for the court, said the 1866
law can be used to sue a city only if it can be proved the alleged
violation of civil rights was part of an official municipal policy.
   It is not enough to show that a city employee, acting in an
official capacity, violated someone's rights, she said.
   ``Once those officials who have the power to make official policy
on a particular issue have been identified, it is for the jury to
determine whether their decisions have caused the deprivation of
rights at issue by policies which affirmatively command that it
occur,'' she said.
   The high court previously limited a civil rights law enacted in
1871 _ a statute also known as the Ku Klux Klan Act _ in the same
way.
   Thursday's ruling is particularly significant because of the
potential big-money damages the 1866 law provides for winners of
such suits.
   The ruling is the latest in a series of defeats handed civil
rights plaintiffs this year by a newly solidified conservative
majority on the court.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice William J. Brennan said the
latest decision is ``astonishing'' because the court did not allow
pro-civil rights forces to present their side fully.
   ``It is not only unfair to decide the case on this basis,'' he
said. ``It is unwise.''
   The court ruled against Norman Jett, longtime coach and athletic
director at South Oak Cliff High School in Dallas. He sued the
Dallas Independent School District and others.
   A federal jury awarded Jett $850,000 in damages, reduced by a
federal trial judge to about $563,000. A federal appeals court
overturned the award.
   The Supreme Court said Thursday that Jett could get a new trial
to determine whether he can recover any money from the school
district.
   But the decision makes his case considerably more difficult to
prove.
   O'Connor said a federal appeals court could grant Jett a new
trial against the city only if it determines that the school
superintendent who ordered him transferred had policy-making
authority granted by Texas law in the area of employee transfers.
   Jett had coached the South Oak Cliff football team since 1962
when, in the spring of 1983, he was transferred to another city high
school.
   Jett had been named head coach and athletic director at the
school in 1970, the year the racial composition at South Oak Cliff
changed from predominantly white to predominantly black.
   Frederick Todd, South Oak Cliff's black principal who held that
job since 1975, was also sued by Jett for replacing him with a black
coach.
   According to court records, the relationship between Todd and
Jett grew more tense after South Oak Cliff lost to Plano in the
state high school championship in November 1982.
   Jett said Todd believed that the only way for South Oak Cliff to
compete was to hire a black coach who in turn would recruit black
players.
   Jett said that school officials violated his due-process,
free-speech and equal-protection rights.
   Brennan was joined in dissent by Justices Thurgood Marshall,
Harry A. Blackmun and John Paul Stevens.
   Joining O'Connor were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Byron R. White, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
