<FIRST>u a AM-NYSDeathPenalty 1stLd-Writethru a0716 06-22 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYS Death Penalty, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0716,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator: Death Penalty Override Plans Scrapped</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to add history of vetoes, picking up at the
2nd graf previous.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to attempt an override of Gov. Mario
Cuomo's latest veto of legislation to restore the death penalty in
New York state were scrapped Thursday because of a key senator's
illness.
   New York governors have vetoed death penalty bills every year
since 1977.
   State Senate Majority Leader Ralph Marino said the override vote,
which had been expected Tuesday, was being postponed indefinitely
because of new cancer surgery for state Sen. James Donovan.
   Donovan issued a statement saying he would enter Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York City on Monday for surgery
Wednesday.
   The bill's chief sponsor, state Sen. Dale Volker, had said
earlier that without Donovan's support he had almost no chance of
winning the override test in the Senate.
   Donovan, 65, who underwent surgery in early May for colon cancer,
went to New York City on Wednesday for tests at Sloan-Kettering.
   A consistent death penalty supporter in the past, Donovan stunned
his colleagues last week when he said his bout with cancer had
caused him to have second thoughts about the death penalty.
   On Monday, Donovan had returned to Albany for the first time
since his May surgery and Cuomo sent a state helicopter to Donovan's
home to pick him up for a lengthy lunch at the Executive Mansion.
   Emerging from that lunch, Donovan said he still wasn't certain
how he would vote on the override attempt.
   But he added: ``If you were standing where I am and your life was
in danger, you would have some second thoughts.''
   For the past four years, the Republican-controlled state Senate
has successfully voted to override Cuomo's death penalty vetoes but
the effort has repeatedly fallen short in the Democratic-controlled
Assembly.
   This year, death penalty supporters felt they were within one
vote of winning in the Assembly before problems began appearing in
the Senate.
   In February, state Sen. Israel Ruiz was convicted of a federal
felony that eventually cost him his seat. The Democrat had voted for
the death penalty in recent years.
   With Ruiz gone, Volker could only count on 41 votes for an
override, the exact number needed in the 61-member Senate. And that
assumed that Donovan would vote for the death penalty.
   New York's electric chair hasn't been used since 1963.
</TEXT>
