<FIRST>r w AM-HouseLeadership     06-22 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Leadership,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Californian Fazio Elected Vice Chairman of House Democratic Caucus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats filled a vacancy in their new
leadership lineup Thursday by electing Rep. Vic Fazio of California,
an ethics committee member, to serve as the vice chairman of their
party's caucus organization.
   Fazio defeated Reps. Martin Frost of Texas, Marcy Kaptur of Ohio
and Richard Durbin of Illinois to fill the last vacancy remaining
from the party leadership shake-up triggered by the resignations of
House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and Majority Whip Tony Coelho,
D-Calif.
   Fazio won a majority on the second round of balloting with 147
votes to 74 for Frost and 32 for Kaptur. On the first ballot, it was
Fazio 113, Frost 69, Kaptur 37 and Durbin 34. Durbin dropped out for
the second round.
   With the addition of Fazio, the Democratic-elected leadership
contains no women and no Southerners or members of the
more-conservative wing.
   Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said Thursday that the leaders
plan to ``consider some additional appointments that might be made
to broaden participation in the leadership.''
   Following Foley, the top Democratic leaders of the House now are
Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, the majority leader; William H.
Gray III of Pennsylvania, the majority whip; and Steny H. Hoyer of
Maryland, the caucus chairman.
   Fazio is 10-yar House veteran and a member of the ethics
committee, formally known as the Committee on Standards of Official
Conduct, that brought the charges that led to Wright's resignation.
Frost, a member of the House Rules Committee, was among Wright's
defenders.
   Coelho resigned from the House June 15 rather than face an
inquiry into his personal finances such as the one that cost Wright
his speakership. On May 31, Wright announced he was quitting as
speaker and said he planned to resign from the House by the end of
June. Foley was elected speaker on June 6.
   Fazio is also co-chairman of a bipartisan task force studying
changes in the House rules of ethical conduct.
</TEXT>
