<FIRST>r w AM-GeneticRice     06-22 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Genetic Rice,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Permit Approved for Field Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Thursday it has
approved a permit for Crop Genetics International, Hanover, Md., to
begin immediate field tests of rice plants containing a genetically
engineered organism to ward off insects.
   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, said the tests will be conducted in
Queen Anne's County, Md. Last month the agency approved the
company's plan to test the same genetically altered microorganism in
corn.
   A soil organism, Bacillus thuringiensis, contains a gene for a
protein that becomes toxic when eaten by caterpillars. This gene was
added to a second bacterium, Clavibacter xyli (subspecies
cynodontis), which can live within the rice plant.
   By combining the two, scientists hope rice plants can have
built-in protection against insect pests.
</TEXT>
