<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     06-22 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Members Acknowledge Party Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading Politburo reformers, saying the
Communist Party is sharply divided, prepared for a crucial meeting
Friday at which some seek the ouster of centrist party chief Karoly
Grosz.
   Politburo member Imre Pozsgay, considered a reformist challenger
to Grosz, told the state news agency MTI on Thursday that the
Central Committee meeting will be advised to keep on Grosz until a
party congress this fall.
   But he said Friday's session ``may not be able to arrive at
lasting solutions'' on personnel or policy.
   ``In these rapidly changing times, there can be unexpected
factors, and questions may arise concerning the party leaders'' and
makeup of the Politburo, Pozsgay said.
   His remarks follow weeks of increasingly open struggle between
reformers and more orthodox Communists. Grosz has been party general
secretary for only 13 months and seems to have lost the center
ground he sought between the two factions.
   Poszgay and other reformers meanwhile have backed new ``reform
circles'' inside the party and, outside, a Movement for a Democratic
Hungary in anticipation of a possible party split.
   Politburo member Reszoe Nyers told Thursday's Nepszabadsag party
daily that he does not expect a formal split Friday.
   But he admitted that ``personal cooperation'' in top party
echelons has sunk to a minimum.
   ``The party is undoubtedly in crisis because of a lack of
clarification in the concepts of internal trends,'' Nyers said.
``There is no determined core in the party capable of integration,''
he added, blaming ``extreme views'' for the lack of unity.
   Three regional reform groups this week openly called for Grosz's
ouster at Friday's meeting.
   Western analysts following Hungary's rapid embrace of democratic
reforms over the past year say that replacing Grosz before President
Bush's visit next month could damage the image of stability Hungary
seeks in the West.
   Budapest is looking to the Bush visit to cement efforts to gain
badly needed Western aid to restructure the stagnating economy and
help pay off a $17-billion foreign debt.
   But a weekly in western Gyoer city this week quotes a local party
reformer as saying Grosz should go now because he is ``a reformer in
word, and not in deed.''
   Influential party reformists in the southern areas of Csongrad
county and Szeged city issued separate calls for Grosz' replacement.
   The power struggle comes as the party is negotiating with
opposition groups over a timetable and regulations for multiparty
elections to be held by next summer.
</TEXT>
