<HEAD>Hearing Delayed on Woman Who Swallowed Jewelry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTCLAIR, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who swallowed four stolen rings
and a diamond necklace pleaded guilty Thursday to charges of theft
and possession of stolen property.
   Linda Riddick, 21, also admitted passing one of the rings. Police
Capt. Thomas Russo said an officer was sent to the woman's home to
pick it up.
   Municipal Judge Golden Johnson postponed sentencing until June 27
to allow prosecutors time to seek a grand jury indictment against
Ms. Riddick, said Pherese Fusco, a court clerk.
   Ms. Riddick told police she swallowed the jewelry June 15 after a
friend told police about a theft of $2,500 in jewelry from her
apartment.
   Ms. Riddick agreed to an X-ray, which revealed the rings and a
chain in the lower part of her stomach, police said. She refused to
have surgery to retrieve them.
   Ms. Riddick also pleaded guilty to possession of drug
paraphernalia and was fined $500. She was released on her own
recognizance.
