<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Socialists     06-22 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Socialists,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist International Ousts Noriega's Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialist International suspended
Panama's ruling party Thursday on grounds it rigged elections.
   The 81-member congress of Western socialist parties also said it
deplored the ``bloody repression'' in China and called for an
international conference on the Middle East.
   At the end of a three-day congress, delegates unanimously
approved a Latin American proposal to suspend the Democratic
Revolutionary Party of Gen. Manuel Noriega, the de facto leader of
Panama.
   Delegates condemned the ``manipulation of the electoral process
in Panama and demand that the democratic will of the people is
respected.'' Panama's government said its candidate won the May 7
presidential election, but international the observers alleged
widespread fraud and said the opposition won handily.
   Israel's Labor Party, led by Finance Minister Shimon Peres,
boycotted the meeting after the the Socialist International allowed
members of the Palestine Liberation Organization to attend as
observers.
   ``The PLO should take part in the peace process in the region. An
international peace conference under the auspices of the U.N.
Security Council is urgently needed,'' a congress resolution said.
   Swedish daily Dagens Nyheter has reported secret meetings between
unidentified Israeli Labor Party members and PLO delegates during
the conference.
   In addition, Swedish officials sought to mediate at separate
meetings with PLO delegates and members of Israel's Labor Party, the
junior partner in a coalition led by Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc.
   ``We can express careful optimism after our talks,'' Swedish
Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson told a news conference after the
meetings. He refused to elaborate.
   But PLO delegation leader Yasser Abdrabbou said there has been no
shift in official Israeli positions.
   ``They are still saying no to everything _ no to an international
peace conference, no to the PLO, no to withdrawal (from the occupied
territories),'' Abdrabbou told reporters.
   Former West German Chancellor Willy Brandt was re-elected
president of the Socialist International, a post he has held since
1976.
   Brandt said the organization is closely following changes in the
Soviet Baltic republics of Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia. The small
republics, which are claiming broad rights of self-determination,
sent ``consultative'' representatives to the congress along with
other Soviet bloc countries.
   ``All of us wish all the best to the people who are working to
improve society'' in the Baltic republics, Brandt told reporters.
   A congress resolution said: ``The Socialist International
supports the struggle in Central and Eastern Europe, including the
Baltic, for self-determination, democracy and economic and
ecological recovery.''
</TEXT>
