<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PrisonArtists     06-22 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Artists,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Inmates Join Prison Officials At Opening Of Inmate Art Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two inmates at the J.B. Gates
Correctional Unit used their skills to get out of prison for four
hours Thursday and attend a wine-and-cheese reception.
   Their only tools were pencils and felt-tip pens.
   Inmates Robert DuBois and Dan Simmonds were special guests at the
formal opening of an art gallery's three-week exhibition of 32
drawings and paintings by Connecticut inmates.
   Prison officials, including Gates Warden Dennis T. Guay, and some
of the families of the inmate-artists also attended the reception at
the Vangarde Gallery.
   ``This is just the thing he might need to get him going in the
right direction again,'' said DuBois' mother, Janice Canning of
Wallingford, who greeted her 22-year-old son with a big hug. ``He's
certainly got the talent.''
   Sticking to a vow she had made not to visit her son in prison if
he got in trouble again, Canning had not seen him since he was
sentenced last October to 18 months for robbery.
   The works on display range from an oil painting of a barnyard
scene and a colored pencil drawing of a tearful boy holding a fluffy
white dog to surrealistic portrayals of prison life and frightening
renderings of skulls and bones, blood and death.
   The inmates, who will get to keep all the proceeds, have priced
the paintings and drawings anywhere from $25 to $4,000, for a copy
of a Rembrandt. The show opened Saturday and two drawings had sold
in the first five days.
   One of Simmonds' works _ a stylized drawing of a dog _ was the
second to be sold. The price was $100.
   ``I wasn't too sure on my work. I didn't know I had the artistic
talent. I was content just having my work be good enough to be
entered in an art gallery,'' said Simmonds, 30, who is serving time
for narcotics possession and is due for release this October.
   Simmonds said drawing has become ``a whole new way of relief for
me. it lets me channel my feelings.''
   Inmates like DuBois and Simmonds have been taking art classes as
part of the 5-year-old Arts in Correction program run by the
private, non-profit Connecticut Prison Association, said Allyson
Holtz, the program's coordinator and one of the inmates' art
teachers.
   Nine professional artists hired by the organization have been
going into nine prisons across the state to provide 12-week courses
on such subjects as drawing, creative writing, dance and music.
   ``It gives us a very therapeutic activity that reduces idle time,
which benefits inmates and staff alike,'' said Doug Kulmacz,
director of volunteer services for the Department of Correction,
which helps fund the program.
   This is the second year an exhibition of inmates' work has been
staged at a private gallery, but the first that any inmates
attended, Holtz said.
</TEXT>
