<SECOND>AM-Bush-Homeless,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Told It's More Profitable to Sell Drugs Than Work for Minimum
Wage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young man who lives in a homeless shelter told
President Bush on Thursday that it's more profitable to sell drugs
than work for the minimum wage.
   ``$100 a week, that's no money,'' said 18-year-old Walter. ``I
can make $100 in 15 minutes'' selling drugs.
   Another resident agreed.
   ``Working in McDonald's _ at the minimum wage _ it just doesn't
pay,'' Monique, 20, told Bush after he asked why young people ended
up on the street.
   Bush recently vetoed an increase in the minimum wage from $3.35
an hour to $4.55, saying he'll support an increase to $4.25 an hour
with the stipulation of a lower training wage for new employees.
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, met for about 30 minutes with 11
residents of Covenant House, a shelter for homeless youths located
three blocks from Times Square.
   Covenant House asked that the residents be identified only by
their first names.
   ``You don't want to be there,'' Monique told Bush when he asked
about the problems of living on the street. She said she had no home
and had been abused as a child.
   Walter, who said his mother was dead and his father an alcoholic,
also said he had no home.
   Bush asked Walter what he wanted to do with his life. Walter said
he hoped to learn electronics, carpentry or plumbing.
   ``I want a good job _ so I can get a house, a dog, a rabbit and
babies,'' Walter said.
   Mrs. Bush cradled a 3-week-old baby, Crystal, whose mother was a
resident of the shelter, as Bush spoke with the youths.
</TEXT>
