<HEAD>Chicago Congressman, 79, Receives Emergency Medical Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney R. Yates, a 20-term Democratic
congressman from Illinois, received emergency medical attention
Thursday after bumping his knee in the House chamber. He later said
he ``almost fainted because the pain was so intense.''
   Six white-coated members of the congressional medical staff
rushed to the aid of the 79-year-old lawmaker from Chicago at about
12:30 p.m. EDT when he fell forward in a seat after voting on the
House floor.
   They put a blood-pressure cuff on his left arm and what appeared
to be a heart monitor on his chest, and talked to him for about 15
minutes before taking him out of the chamber in a wheelchair. He
said he felt fine, though he was pale, when he left for more
examination at the attending physician's office in the Capitol.
   ``I'm feeling very well,'' he said later by telephone from his
office. ``I voted and I was on my way back, turning up the aisle and
bumped my knee. I almost fainted because the pain was so intense.''
   He said there was no permanent damage to his knee, but he was
keeping an ice pack on it to ease the pain.
   Yates had just participated in a parliamentary vote approving
Wednesday's House work. The vote was followed by brief speeches,
which continued while the emergency crew worked on Yates in a chair
toward the rear of the chamber.
