<FIRST>r w AM-CornQuality     06-22 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corn Quality,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drought Had Little Impact on Quality of Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought a year ago bit deeply into the 1988
corn crop but didn't do much damage to the grain that was harvested,
an Agriculture Department report said Thursday.
   W. Kirk Miller, administrator of the department's Federal Grain
Inspection Service, said the drought had little impact on the
``quality characteristics'' of last year's corn, including test
weights, moisture and kernel damage.
   The annual report did not include statistics for aflatoxin
content of the 1988 corn harvest. Aflatoxin is a cancer-causing
substance that can result from certain kinds of fungus under drought
stress conditions.
   Some corn harvested last fall had been reported as having high
levels of aflatoxin, prompting fears that the tainted grain could
cause harm in the U.S. food chain.
</TEXT>
