<FIRST>r w AM-B-2-Krings     06-22 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-2-Krings,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Official Confident Bomber Will Perform as Anticipated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon official in charge of testing new
weapons said Thursday he is confident the B-2 bomber, set to be
flown in a few weeks, will perform as anticipated.
   ``I don't see any indications the B-2 can't do what it intends to
do,'' John E. Krings, director of the Defense Department's
Operational Test and Evaluation office, told reporters.
   However, Krings, who is leaving at the end of the month, refused
to discuss whether he thought the B-2, the so-called Stealth, was
worth the money, a question raised by some members of Congress.
   Krings said politicians and defense analysts will have to decide
if they're willing to pay for the bomber.
   Each B-2 bomber is expected to cost over $500 million and there
are plans to build 132 of them. Northrop Corp. is building the plane
at its Palmdale, Calif., plant.
   The plane, described as resembling a ``flying wing'' without
conventional fuselage, is designed to penetrate Soviet borders
without being detected by radar.
   The plane has no sharp angles and relies on the use of
radar-absorbing coatings on its surface, officials have said.
   Krings said the B-2 has not been operationally tested in the
field yet, but individual systems were tried out along the way. The
Air Force says the B-2 will not be deployed before 1991.
   Meantime, Krings defended the record of his office, which has
been criticized by some lawmakers who say it has failed to test
weapons adequately and is too cozy with defense contracting firms.
   Krings said his office had succeeded in forcing the services to
improve the weapons before they are deployed.
   ``The list that didn't go into production because of our
arguments, there were many, but they are sometimes hard to find,''
he said. For instance, some contractors have delayed testing in
order not to fail, he said.
   They say, ``We are delaying because we don't want to fail the
test,'' he said. As an example, he cited the testing of cellular
radios that were postponed for about four months.
</TEXT>
