<FIRST>r w AM-FemaleVeterans     06-22 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Female Veterans,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Female Veterans Often Feel Unentitled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Female veterans often miss out on benefits for
which they qualify because they have a low opinion of their service
records, witnesses told a House subcommittee Thursday.
   ``They don't see themselves as veterans,'' said retired Rear Adm.
Frances Shea-Buckley, chairwoman of the advisory committee on women
veterans for the Department of Veterans Affairs. ``They feel that
only men are veterans. They say things like `I only served two
years. I didn't go overseas.'''
   Women can get all the benefits available to male veterans as long
as they have spent one year in service, said Dr. Susan Mather, chief
of women's programs for the Department of Veterans Affairs. One
estimate says women make up 4 percent of all veterans.
   Among those benefits are extensive health care opportunities,
educational assistance and housing loans.
   Rep. Lane Evans, D-Ill., chairman of the Veterans Affairs
subcommittee on oversight and investigations, called the hearing as
a follow-up to the first hearing on the subject two years ago.
   ``We want to learn what progress has been made during the last
two years in realizing the equitable provision of benefits and
services to women veterans,'' said Evans.
   Linda Caldwell, a military nurse who is chairwoman of the
advisory commission on women veterans in New Jersey, told of a
veterans hospital in her state is ill equipped to give women even
basic service.
   Caldwell said Lyons Veterans Hospital had only men's pajamas, no
personal sanitary supplies and no gynecological clinic for
out-patients.
   She said by contrast, the East Orange VA Hospital, provides women
those basic medical needs.
   ``Not all VA hospitals are created equal in terms of facilities,
supplies or services provided veterans,'' said Caldwell.
   Mather said that in the last six or seven years the attitude of
the government toward female veterans has improved, though ``it may
not have filtered down to every level.''
   Caldwell shared Shea-Buckley's opinion about getting women to
come forward as veterans.
   ``In particular, certain Vietnam era women veterans speak of
being ridiculed by family and friends upon their return to the
United States,'' Caldwell said.
   She said they don't act proud of their service or use it to gain
benefits rightfully theirs.
   ``When pressed for details, they often reply, `I'd rather forget
that part of my life,''' she said.
   She said World War II veterans are most vocal about their needs,
primarily nursing care since they are now among the aging population.
   The 1980 Census, the first to ask women if they were veterans,
counted 1.13 million women had served in the armed forces. That was
3.1 percent of the veteran population. Female veterans' now are
believed to comprise about 4 percent of the veteran population, said
Mather.
</TEXT>
