<FIRST>r i AM-China-WorldReaction     06-22 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-World Reaction,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governments Protest Executions in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congress of 81 Western socialist parties said
Thursday it deplored the ``bloody repression'' in China. Belgium
protested by banning all official visits and by suspending a loan.
   The Vatican roundly attacked the executions in China, and Spain's
parliament said that death does not block ideas.
   In Washington, Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
urged President Bush to condemn the executions in China more
forcefully. Secretary of State James A. Baker III asked Congress,
however, to mute criticism of administration reaction, saying the
United States must ``speak with one voice.''
   Chinese authorities executed seven more people on Thursday,
bringing to 27 the number reported put to death in two days. Others
have been sentenced to die on charges they led student protests for
democratic reform in April and May.
   Condemnation from the Socialist International came at the end of
its three-day congress in Stockholm, Sweden. China has said it acted
to suppress efforts to overthrow its socialist system.
   Belgium banned all official visits to and from China, barred new
Belgian-Chinese projects and suspended a $7.3 million loan because
of China's ``flagrant violation of human rights,'' Foreign Affairs
Minister Mark Eyskens said.
   Eyskens summoned Chinese Ambassador Liu Shan on Thursday and
``vigorously protested the executions and bloody repression that
continue to spread in China,'' a statement from his ministry said.
   Prime Minister David Lange of New Zealand said Thursday that his
nation will lodge a formal complaint in Wellington and Beijing to
make clear its ``revulsion'' over the executions. New Zealand
diplomats in Beijing may be recalled for consultations, he said.
   Vatican Radio said, ``The world witnesses with dismay the
chilling chain of executions carried out by Chinese authorities
against the young protagonists of the demonstrations for democracy.
   ``The horror and indignation expressed by so many governments
testifies to the isolation of a line so brutal in the face of the
civilized community of nations.''
   Spain's lower house of Parliament declared that ``death, blood
and violence have never been able to block the path of ideas.''
   A statement read by Felix Pons, president of the 350-seat
chamber, said: ``There is nothing more valuable than human life.''
   In Tokyo, Prime Minister Sousuke Uno of Japan said that China's
proceeding with the executions ``amid rising international criticism
is extremely regrettable,'' Kyodo News Service reported.
   Uno told reporters Japan was not planning sanctions against China.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino expressed sadness over
executions in China, but ``conceded that the matter is within the
domestic jurisdiction of China's courts,'' a statement in Manila
said.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Thursday she would
not consider economic sanctions against China, adding that to do so
might prove dangerous to Britain's subjects in Hong Kong. On
Wednesday she said she was ``utterly appalled'' by the executions.
   Britain has canceled ministerial visits to China and suspended
talks on a new constitution for its colony of Hong Kong after 1997,
when it reverts to China.
   In East Germany, Joachim Herrmann of the Communist Party's
policy-making Politburo said the government published all official
Chinese statements with the purpose of denying ``Western horror
stories'' and to present ``objective information.''
   In a speech distributed by the state-run news agency ADN,
Herrmann said the ``peaceful student demonstrations'' in Beijing
were to be used for a ``counterrevolutionary overthrow of people's
power in China.''
</TEXT>
