<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ExxonValdez     06-22 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crippled Tanker To Be Moved Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly three months after it caused the
nation's worst oil spill, the damaged tanker Exxon Valdez will be
towed out of Prince William Sound on Friday for a $25 million repair
job in San Diego, authorities said.
   The Coast Guard said the 987-foot vessel will leave the shelter
of Outside Bay on the southwest side of Naked Island in the heart of
the sound during the morning, weather permitting.
   The Exxon Valdez has been undergoing temporary repairs at Outside
Bay since about two weeks after it ran aground at Bligh Reef on
March 24, ripping its hull and spilling nearly 11 million gallons of
crude oil drawn from wells on Alaska's North Slope.
   Eight of the vessel's 13 tanks were penetrated by the reef and
divers reported finding rocks as large as small cars in the cargo
hold. But the tanks have been cleaned to the point that small
schools of herring and salmon have been reported living in them. The
hull also has been steam-cleaned.
   Divers drilled numerous holes along many cracks in the hull and
plated over them to keep the cracks from spreading. One crack was
said to run through the hull until about midship. The cracks had to
be immobilized with plates out of concern that rough seas could
break the vessel in half.
   Several of the vessel's tanks remain unsealed, Exxon spokesman
Joe Tucker said. Coast Guard and salvage officials said air pressure
in the tanks would keep seawater at maneageable levels.
   The tanker will be towed by two tugs, and accompanied by a
salvage vessel and a third tug. But Tucker said the tanker's engines
are in working order and will be be used at the skipper's discretion.
   Since the spill, oil has soiled more than 700 miles of Alaska's
southern coastline. Some of the oil has flushed out of the sound and
traveled with Gulf of Alaska currents some 400 miles to Kodiak
Island and the Alaska Peninsula.
   Workers have recovered more than 26,000 birds killed by the oil,
although biologists say the figure probably represents 10 percent or
less of the overall toll. Other casualties have included more than
50 eagles and nearly 800 sea otters.
   The spill forced closure of numerous herring and salmon fisheries
and severely curtailed others.
   Exxon has more than 9,000 people, backed up by 800 boats and a
small air force, working to clean up the spill. Exxon said this week
it already has spent more than $200 million on the job, and the
state has billed Exxon more than $12 million for oil-spill expenses.
   Under a procedure established two weeks after the spill, the
state sends its bills to Exxon, which pays most of the suppliers and
contractors directly and reimburses the state for out-of-pocket
costs, said Michael Nizich, administrative services director for
Gov. Steve Cowper's office.
   Batches of invoices have been sent almost daily to Exxon. ``Some
of them were pretty hefty in size,'' Nizich said.
   A Coast Guard officer will be on board the Exxon Valdez until it
leaves Prince William Sound, about 60 miles from Naked Island, and
again when the vessel nears San Diego, where the ship was built.
   Tucker said seven Exxon officers and four salvage experts would
be on board throughout the voyage, expected to take about 20 days,
at about 6 mph.
   One worker was killed during the cleanup, and there have numerous
injuries in boat and plane accidents as well as from falls on
oil-slickened beaches.
   The former captain of the Exxon Valdez, Joseph Hazelwood, has
been charged with six criminal counts arising from the spill. Among
other things, the state alleges he was drunk at the time.
   Hazelwood has pleaded innocent to all charges. Court officials
say it is unlikely his trial will take place until fall or early
winter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MagneticTrain     06-22 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Magnetic Train,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Urges U.S. Commitment To Magnetically Levitated Trains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States can regain the lead in
developing magnetically levitated trains with a 300 mph potential,
but if it doesn't act soon Japan or West Germany will dominate the
field, according to a report released Thursday.
   ``Mag-lev'' will be an important transportation mode by the year
2000, and decisions made in the next five years will determine which
country gets the patents and leads the industry, said an advisory
committee to the Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works.
   ``Because of the overseas competition evolving in this
technology, America's window of opportunity is already beginning to
close,'' the committee wrote.
   Now is the chance for the United States to leapfrog the
competition by creating the second generation of mag-lev trains
using superconducting electromagnets, according to the committee.
   It did not mean the new high-temperature superconductors, but
rather the well-understood, extremely low temperature technology
used over the past 10 years or so for medical imaging devices,
particle accelerators and other devices in high-tech firms around
the world.
   The advisory group prepared the study at the request of New York
Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, second-ranking Democrat on the committee
and sponsor of legislation authorizing the Department of
Transportation to develop such trains.
   The report recommends that the U.S. government allocate $750
million over six years to develop, test and demonstrate several
mag-lev prototypes.
   James Powell and Gordon Danby of the Brookhaven National
Laboratory in New York, co-developers of mag-lev trains, outlined
the pluses at a news conference.
   Among them: they are faster than cars or conventional railroads;
they consume less energy than automobiles or airplanes; they pollute
less; they can run in any weather and they experience little wear.
   Mag-lev trains run on a cushion of air above a guideway,
suspended by magnets on the train and in the guideway whose like
poles repel each other. A moving magnetic field in the guideway
attracts a magnet on the train of opposite polarity, pulling the
train at high speed.
   Current magnets hold the train about three-eighths of an inch off
the rails; superconducting models could offer higher stability with
a six-inch elevation.
   The United States pioneered mag-lev transportation in the 1960s
and 1970s, but went only as far as building prototypes and scale
models, said the report. The effort was abandoned in 1975 for lack
of federal funds, ``but was picked up and carried on in a spirit of
raging incrementalism by the Japanese.''
   ``That America walked away from this effort more than a decade
ago is demonstrative of the commercial technology lapses our country
is prone to stumble into, characterized most visibly by the
forfeiting of billion-dollar markets in consumer electronics and
dynamic random access memory semiconductors _ two American
inventions commercially exploited by Japan,'' the report said.
   ``We see many benefits. We don't see any serious drawbacks,''
Powell said.
   At present, the Japanese are testing a full-scale 325 mph
vehicle. West Germany has tested a similar 256 mph system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-VargasLlosa     06-22 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Vargas Llosa,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Novelist Vargas Llosa Drops Bid For Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Celebrated Peruvian novelist Mario Vargas Llosa
for Europe on Thursday after abandoning his bid for the presidency.
   His decision, announced late Wednesday, sent shock waves through
political circles and strengthened the chances of a Communist Party
victory in next year's election.
   Opinion polls showed the famed writer was a solid favorite to
defeat former Lima mayor Alfonso Barrantes, a Marxist, in the
presidential election.
   Vargas Llosa, candidate for a center-right coalition, said in a
letter released to the press that he was stepping out of the race
because of internal disputes within the coalition.
   Vargas Llosa criticized the ``mediocre and petty'' motives of
some within the coalition who raised their own interests above those
of the nation.
   ``The collapse of the Front could open the door of our country to
totalitarian Marxism or a bloody military adventure,'' Vargas Llosa
warned in the letter.
   The letter was directed to former President Fernando Belaunde
Terry, leader of the centrist Popular Action Party, and Luis Bedoya
Reyes, leader of the conservative Popular Christian Party.
   Along with Vargas Llosa's Liberty Movement, the parties are the
most important components of the Democratic Front, which nominated
the 53-year-old writer June 4.
   Belaunde's party has vowed to present its own candidates in
municipal elections in November. Vargas Llosa has argued instead for
single candidates to avoid political warfare among coalition members.
   The presidential election is expected to be held in March, but an
exact date has not been set. The winner will take office on July 28.
   The writer refused to receive any visitors Wednesday night and
left early Thursday for a month-long tour of Europe, an aide said.
   Vargas Llosa, best-known as the author of ``Aunt Julia and the
Scriptwriter'' among other novels, entered the political arena after
organizing a huge demonstration against President Alan Garcia's plan
to nationalize the banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
