<FIRST>r w AM-Fiske     06-22 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fiske,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thurmond Urges Fiske to Bow Out of Consideration for Job at Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond urged Robert B. Fiske Jr.
to withdraw from consideration as deputy attorney general to avoid a
divisive debate in the Senate, the South Carolina Republican's
office said Thursday.
   Thurmond, top Republican on the Senate Judiciary Committee, made
the appeal to Fiske at a meeting with other senators that was
convened by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas on Wednesday.
   ``Senator Thurmond is very concerned that a divisive, protracted
debate about this nomination would not be in anybody's best
interests,'' said Christopher Simpson, the senator's press
secretary. Thurmond told Fiske that conservative opponents of his
nomination might wage a filibuster to block confirmation.
   Thurmond is among 14 GOP senators who signed a letter last week
urging President Bush not to nominate Fiske. They contend that as a
chairman of the American Bar Association's judicial screening panel,
Fiske used ideological criteria to thwart several of President
Reagan's judicial nominees.
   Eighteen moderate or liberal Republicans, meanwhile, sent letters
to Bush this week urging him to nominate Fiske, a prominent Wall
Street lawyer who was once U.S. attorney in New York.
   The GOP surfaced following a report that Bush inadvertently
plugged Fiske for the position during a gathering of U.S. attorneys
at the White House last Friday.
   Noting that a number of former U.S. attorneys held key jobs in
his administration, Bush said: ``We hope to see yet another _ Bob
Fiske of New York _ joining our ranks here soon.''
   The Washington Post, in Thursday's editions, quoted anonymous
White House sources as accusing someone from the Justice Department
of slipping the remark into Bush's speech.
   David Runkel, Thornburgh's chief spokesman, disputed the report
saying: ``I just don't think it happened the way it was described.''
   But a White House source, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said presidential aides were ``flabbergasted'' when they heard about
Bush's remarks because the issue of whether to nominate Fiske is
still under debate there.
   The source said that the remark about Fiske was not part of the
speech draft after it had been cleared Thursday night.
   Any change in the speech would have had to be cleared by an
elaborate approval process in the White House, the source said.
   The Post reported that the remark was given for insertion to the
``card writer'' who digests speeches onto index cards for delivery
by the president.
   During the meeting with Fiske, Thurmond did not identify the
senators who might mount a filibuster nor did he threaten himself to
wage one, Simpson said.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., another opponent of Fiske who
attended the meeting, said that he had not heard any word of support
for Fiske from the White House.
   ``Based on our concerns, the White House so far has declined to
make such a nomination,'' Humphrey said. ``It is the Justice
Department which is lobbying for this candidate, I haven't heard boo
from the White House.''
   Humphrey said Fiske was accompanied to the meeting by Carol
Crawford, the new assistant attorney general for legislative affairs.
   Crawford told the senators that Fiske would have no role in
selecting nominees for the federal bench, Humphrey said.
   Others attending the meeting included Sens. John Danforth, R-Mo.,
and Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., both supporters of Fiske, Humphrey said.
   Runkel said Fiske ``is replying to the senators' concerns. I
still believe that he is going to be nominated and confirmed.''
</TEXT>
