<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Flag     06-22 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Flag,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Members of Congress Denounce Supreme Court Flag Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats and Republicans rushed to Old Glory's
defense Thursday as the Senate passed a resolution condemning the
Supreme Court decision giving First Amendment protection to those
who desecrate the American flag.
   In addition to the resolution urging the high court to reconsider
Wednesday's decision, a variety of bills aimed at circumventing the
ruling were tossed into legislative hoppers.
   ``Congress has believed that the act of desecrating the flag is
clearly not `speech' as protected by the First Amendment,'' said the
Senate resolution, co-sponsored by Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, and Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan.
   The resolution, which passed 97-3, voiced alarm that the ruling
may invalidate federal law and statutes in 48 states prohibiting
destruction of the flag.
   Sens. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts and Howard Metzenbaum of
Ohio, both Democrats, and Gordon Humphrey of New Hampshire, a
Republican, voted against the resolution.
   Kennedy said the Supreme Court ``has the last word on the meaning
of the Constitution'' and that the Senate shouldn't go on record
criticizing the Supreme Court for carrying out its duty.
   Humphrey said that while he didn't like anyone burning or
defacing the flag, he asked, ``What defines desecration?''
   ``This seems to me to be an exercise in silliness and a little
bit of hypocrisy,'' he said. ``It strikes me as intellectually
dishonest.''
   The high court, in a 5-4 vote, threw out the conviction of
Gregory ``Joey'' Johnson, who was sentenced to a year in jail and
fined $2,000 for burning the flag in Texas.
   The court said the flag burning at a demonstration in Dallas
during the 1984 Republican National Convention was a form of
expression protected by the Constitution's guarantee of freedom of
speech.
   The decision was greeted with virtually universal outrage on
Capitol Hill.
   ``Shame on these judges,'' said Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind. ``Shame
on you, shame on you!.''
   ``We must stand for America. The flag, the flag. America,
America. For us!'' bellowed Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   ``The First Amendment guarantees everyone the freedom to speak,
but it guarantees no one an audience for his words,'' said Mitchell,
a former federal judge. ``I do not believe that Americans have to
see the flag, that symbolizes their freedom to speak, devalued and
cheapened in the cause of preserving that freedom.''
   ``The act of flag burning is not meant to convey any political
idea,'' said Rep. Robert Dornan, R-Calif., who was among those
introducing legislation to amend the Constitution to prohibit
flag-desecration. ``It is an act that is solely meant to provoke and
offend.''
   ``With this decision, the court cloaks the most offensive
behavior as political expression,'' said Rep. Owen Pickett, D-Va.,
who introduced a resolution aimed at nullifying the court decision.
   Rep. Doug Applegate, D-Ohio, shouted on the floor of the House:
   ``I'm mad as hell. We've witnessed the greatest travesty in the
annals of jurisprudence, when the Supreme Court allowed the
destruction of the greatest of American symbols. What in God's name
is going on?''
   Rep. Les AuCoin, D-Ore., said he was ``deeply offended'' by the
ruling.
   ``The Reagan court has given us ... constitutional protection for
the burning of Old Glory,'' he said. ``This liberal Democrat says,
`For shame!'''
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said he was disappointed with the ruling.
   ``In my view, the American flag represents the pre-eminent symbol
of our republic and all for which it stands,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
