<FIRST>r w AM-Osprey     06-22 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Osprey,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Adds Funds To Save V-22 Osprey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee approved an amendment in
closed session Thursday seeking to save the V-22 Osprey aircraft by
pumping $351 million of research and development funds into the
program, House members said.
   The amendment was approved 11-7 by the Armed Services research
and development subcommittee, according to Reps. Curt Weldon, R-Pa.,
and Thomas Foglietta, D-Pa.
   Sponsored by Weldon and Foglietta, the amendment was backed
despite opposition by the subcommittee chairman, Rep. Ron Dellums,
D-Calif., and by Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., the panel's ranking
Republican, according to Weldon press aide Doug Ritter.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, in overseeing cuts in the fiscal
1990 budget promised by President Bush, announced in April that he
was scuttling the V-22 program as too expensive.
   The V-22, described by the Marine Corps as its most important
weapons program, is a revolutionary aircraft designed to take off
like a helicopter and fly like a plane.
   Weldon said the amendment would pull $351 million from research
and development money initially earmarked for the B-2 bomber. He
said he would soon introduce an amendment in the full committee to
``switch accounts,'' replenishing the B-2 research funds by taking
the money from B-2 procurement.
   On Tuesday, Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, urged Cheney to suspend
production of the B-2 because the aircraft has yet to undergo flight
testing. The radar-evading aircraft is the most expensive plane in
history.
   Weldon made no predictions on whether his amendment would survive
in the full committee.
   ``This is one battle in a continuing series of what is going to
be a prolonged effort. It's the first recorded effort to oppose the
secretary on the V-22,'' Weldon said.
   The two contracting partners developing the V-22 are the Boeing
Helicopter Co. in Pennsylvania and Bell Helicopter Textron Inc. in
Texas.
</TEXT>
