<FIRST>r w AM-Korea-Cheney     06-22 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Cheney,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Urge Phased Troop Withdrawal from South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic lawmakers Thursday urged Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney to reject any agreement with South Korea that
would require the United States to maintain troops in that nation at
current levels.
   ``Some of us on the committee think that no such assurance should
be given,'' Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., told Cheney, who testified
before the Senate Appropriations defense subcommittee.
   ``On the contrary, negotiations ought to begin for a phased
withdrawal from South Korea,'' Johnston said.
   Members of the panel cited a recent letter that South Korean
Defense Minister Lee Sang-Hoon sent to Cheney asking the United
States to promise not to withdraw the more than 43,000 U.S. troops
stationed there.
   The minister told South Korea's national assembly defense
committee that he would ask the United States to sign a joint
communique with that commitment when he travels here next month.
   Johnston and three other Democrats _ Dale Bumpers of Arkansas,
Jim Sasser of Tennessee and Patrick Leahy of Vermont _ wrote to
Cheney urging him to reject any preconditions for a U.S. troop
withdrawal.
   The senators said Cheney's meeting next month with the Korean
official would be an ideal opportunity to ``begin discussions on
reducing our military presence in Korea.''
   The United States spends $2.6 billion a year to maintain its
troops in South Korea.
   Bumpers said at the hearing that South Korea's gross national
product is seven times that of North Korea, its population is twice
that of North Korea and it only spends 5 percent of its GNP on
defense.
   ``I have become increasingly convinced that debate ought to begin
about our presence in Korea,'' he said.
   Cheney said the United States has no plans to reduce the U.S.
commitment to Korea, but that cuts in troop levels are possible,
``just as there is a proposal to reduce our troop level in Europe.''
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee called last month for a reduction of the South Korea-based
forces to 10,000.
</TEXT>
