<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle-Cambodia     06-22 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle-Cambodia,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Calls for Aid to Non-Communist Movements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is continuing to seek
increased aid to non-communist rebels in Cambodia, Vice President
Dan Quayle said Thursday, asking congressional critics not to be
``paralyzed by a memory'' of Vietnam.
   The United States wants a transitional government in Cambodia
with ``a key role'' by opposition leaders Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
the former ruler of the country, and Son Sann, Quayle said in
remarks to the conservative Heritage Foundation.
   State Department officials have acknowledged slim chances of
getting new aid through Congress where some members are concerned
that the aid could fall into the hands of the communist Khmer Rouge.
   But the vice president said that beefing up aid to the
non-communist forces to try to influence what will happen after the
impending departure of the occupying Vietnamese would reduce the
chances of the Khmer Rouge returning top power.
   ``By doing nothing, we would increase the likelihood of continued
civil war and the potential for a return to power by the murderous
Khmer Rouge,'' Quayle said.
   ``The unacknowledged but all-too-tangible presence in the debate
over Cambodia is the ghost of Vietnam. But, my friends, it is now
time to lay this ghost to rest,'' he said.
   ``No great nation can long afford to be paralyzed by a memory. We
must not permit the non-communist resistance in Cambodia to
becoemthe last casualty of the Vietnam war.''
   On the other hand, the vice president said, ``We have learned
that America cannot fight others' battles for them.''
   The Khmer Rouge gained notoriety for the brutality of their
regime from 1973 to 1978 when more than 1 million people died under
leader Pol Pot.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III has said that it would be a
fact of life that the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of the current
insurgent groups, would have a role in a future Cambodian government.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., is pushing an effort in Congress to
boost military aid for the non-communists from the current $7
million a year to as much as $30 million.
</TEXT>
