<HEAD>Man Charged, Cop Faces Punishment in Taped Arrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead, 4th graf, `After Officer ..., to CORRECT sex of Renee
Myles.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who taped his brother's arrest won a
recommendation for disciplinary action against one of the policemen
involved, but faces felony charges of illegally recording the
incident.
   The charges stem from the March 15 arrest of Renee Myles on a
federal drug charge in West Tampa, according to a June 14 report to
Police Chief Austin C. McLane by the police department's internal
affairs division.
   Two of the suspect's brothers began arguing with a policeman.
One, Frank Myles, feared violence and switched on a tape recorder
apparently concealed in a bag he was carrying, the report said.
   After Officer John M. Yaratch asked Renee Myles for
identification, he argued with the other brother, David Myles.
Yaratch then forced Renee Myles down on a car and handcuffed David
Myles.
   Yaratch yelled expletives at the man, then requested
identification from Frank Myles, the report said.
   Frank Myles ``made an aggressive move'' toward the officer, who
grabbed the man's arm and forced him against a car, the report said.
   Frank Myles later played the tape for the officer's superiors.
   The report recommended disciplinary action against Yaratch.
   Frank Myles was arrested March 25 on two felony counts of
illegally recording a conversation, and released from the
Hillsborough County Jail.
   Except in criminal investigations, it generally is illegal in
Florida to tape-record conversations between two people without both
parties' consent. If convicted on both counts, Myles faces up to 10
years in prison and $10,000 in fines.
   The state attorney's office said the matter is still under
investigation. The internal investigation of Yaratch is completed,
but a decision on possible disciplinary action against him is
pending, officials said.
</TEXT>
