<FIRST>r a AM-PTL-Taggarts     06-22 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL-Taggarts,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selected For Trial Of Former PTL Aides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was selected Thursday in the trial
of two former aides to PTL founder Jim Bakker after a day that
included such questions as whether they recognized Jaguar, Cartier
and other luxury brand names.
   David Taggart, 32, and his older brother and housemate, James,
35, are accused of not paying $494,000 in income taxes from 1983 to
1987. They also are charged with using more than $1.1 million of PTL
money to pay personal bills, including $55,000 in purchases from the
Cartier jewelry store in New York.
   A jury of eight women and four men was selected to hear the
Taggarts' trial, which is scheduled to begin July 5 and is expected
to take about a month. Four alternate jurors also were picked.
   The Taggarts' trial will be a prelude to the August trial of
Bakker and Richard Dortch. The two former PTL leaders are accused of
diverting more than $4 million in PTL money for their own benefit.
   David Taggart went to work at PTL in 1978 when he was 21 as an
administrative assistant to the television ministry's music
director. The young piano player soon became Bakker's most trusted
aide, and perhaps PTL's second most powerful executive.
   David Taggart, according to PTL records, drew more than $620,000
in pay in the 15 months ending March 1987 _ the same month Bakker
resigned in a sex and money scandal. James Taggart _ then PTL's
interior decorator _ received nearly $300,000 during that period.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Potter asked some potential jurors if
they regularly contributed to a church or a religious organization.
He also asked if they were familiar with certain brand names such as
Gucci, Jaguar, Cartier and Mercedes Benz. He then asked if they buy
most of their clothing and jewelry in discount stores or expensive
shops and if they normally pay with cash, credit cards or checks.
   It was not known whether any prospective jurors were excluded on
the basis of their answers to the questions.
   The Taggarts' wardrobes included mink coats, designer clothes and
expensive jewelry. They bought a $660,000 condominium on New York's
Fifth Avenue and a $317,000 two-story stucco house in southeast
Charlotte.
   For Christmas in 1986, they gave each other black Jaguar cars
worth $87,765.
   Federal prosecutors are trying to prove the Taggarts conspired to
defraud the IRS by using PTL credit cards to get cash advances,
ranging from $5,000 to $25,000, and then using the money to pay
personal bills.
   The Taggarts also are accused of using blank PTL checks to pay
off their American Express bills. One check was for $50,000, another
for $45,000, the indictment said.
</TEXT>
