<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Guiliani     06-22 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Guiliani,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Another Foot in the Presidential Mouth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told a Republican fund-raiser
Thursday night that his party had a good chance of winning the
city's mayoral election, and then mangled the name of the GOP
frontrunner.
   He intended to praise Rudolph Giuliani, the former top federal
prosecutor in New York whom polls show is leading a field of three
GOP candidates seeking to wrest the seat from Democrats.
   First, Bush told Republicans this year offered a ``great
opportunity'' to win ``the most powerful local office in America.''
   ``And accordingly, I would like to commend our three mayoral
candidates, Rudolph Gi-a _ Gi-a _ ,'' he said.
   Then he continued: ``Gi-o-hani-uh.'' He paused, and exclaimed:
``Rudy.''
   ``Sorry about that,'' he apologized.
   He then went on to praise the other two GOP candidates who will
compete in September's primary: businessman Ron Lauder and educator
Herbert London.
   Giuliani seemed unconcerned.
   ``Well, we're happy. I appreciated the Rudy part,'' he told
reporters. ``Our posters all say Rudy.''
   ``I think we're making progress, when people come up to me on the
street and say: `Hello, Rudy, how are you doing?'
   ``If you haven't taken Latin, sometimes the name Giuliani can be
a little difficult,'' he added.
   It wasn't the only difficulty of the evening.
   The White House put out an official transcript of the president's
remarks, which sanitized his performance through getting the
Giuliani's last name right _ and then the transcript misspelled the
candidate's first name as ``Rudolf.''
</TEXT>
