<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Lebanon,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Lebanese Formally Charged in Aoun Assassination Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Thursday formally charged
six Lebanese men with conspiring to assassinate Lebanese Christian
army commander Gen. Michel Aoun.
   The six were arrested in the southern port of Larnaca last month
after scuba divers stumbled across two shoulder-fired SA-7
anti-aircraft missiles hidden underwater near the coastal airport.
   The missiles lacked only their firing pins, which were discovered
along with a cache of weapons in a seaside apartment where most of
the men were arrested. The weapons included five Kalashnikov rifles,
17 magazines and 28 hand grenades.
   In addition to the conspiracy charge, they face seven other
charges including illegal weapons possession. Five of the men are
accused of illegally entering Cyprus.
   Police said the seven planned to shoot down a Lebanese helicopter
that was to carry Aoun to Larnaca airport for a flight to Morocco
for an Arab summit in late May. Aoun did not attend the meeting.
   The six are identified as Tawfiq Wadih Ashaar, 27; Idris Jamal
Jaber, 27; Wadih Salim Salamon, 27; Ruston Najib Sirhan, 29; Salal
Khafarsi, 27; and Emil Gharali, 27.
   The preliminary hearing is set for June 30. All six have been in
custody in Nicosia Central prison.
