<HEAD>Outgoing Greek Premier Hospitalized For Respiratory Infection, Doctors
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with doctors saying prime minister
suffering from respiratory infection, to spend night at hospital. Pickup
5th graf `Papandreou led...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andreas Papandreou, the outgoing premier,
was hospitalized Thursday after doctors said he was suffering from a
respiratory infection.
   Papandreou, 70, who underwent triple bypass heart surgery in
September, was reported by his doctors to be in excellent condition
after he entered the General State hospital in the Athens suburb of
Holargos.
   ``His admission was for reasons of a fuller examination and his
condition is excellent. His sickness does not prevent execution of
his duties,'' said a statement signed by doctors Dimitri Kremastinos
and Nicos Gannos.
   Wearing a jacket and tie and accompanied by his mistress, former
airline hostess Dimitra Liani, Papandreou smiled and waved to about
200 supporters gathered at the entrance to the hospital.
   Papandreou's four children, George, Nicholas, Andreas and Sophia,
as well as former ministers in his outgoing socialist
administration, were among the well wishers.
   Hospital administrative director, Giorgos Papastratis, told
journalists that Papandreou would spend the night and that a medical
announcement on his condition would be released Friday.
   Papandereou led Greece for eight years, but his Panhellenic
Socialist Movement failed in elections Sunday to win a third
consecutive four-year term, taking 125 seats in the 300-seat
Parliament.
   The conservative New Democracy emerged the winner with 145 seats.
The Coalition of the Left and Progress, an alliance of the Greek
Communist Party and the small Eurocommunist Left, won 28 seats.
