<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Ferry     06-22 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Ferry,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Corporate Manslaughter Charge Over Ferry Sinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court issued manslaughter summonses Thursday for
a shipping company, three of its former directors and four seamen
over the 1987 Zeebrugge ferry disaster in which 193 people died.
   A corporate manslaughter conviction can carry an unlimited fine,
while the seven men face a maximum sentence of life imprisonment.
   The decision to prosecute P and O European Ferries was believed
by experts to be unprecedented. It capped more than two years of
court and police proceedings, a public inquiry that blamed the ship
owners, and an inquest that returned a verdict of unlawful killing.
   There was no immediate comment from the ferry company or the men
summoned.
   The Herald of Free Enterprise, a car-and-passenger ferry,
capsized outside the Belgian port of Zeebrugge in March 1987.
   Lawyers have disclosed that about two-thirds of the families
affected by the disaster have accepted a compensation package from P
and O, from $7,700 to the six-figure range, depending on the
family's circumstances and the contribution the victim made to the
family's income.
   Published reports have estimated the final payout will be at
least $6 million and as much as $23 million.
   An unidentified family that lost its breadwinner father was
granted $294,000 in a test case compensation settlement in the High
Court in January 1988.
   Facing prosecution are the ship's captain, David Lewry; First
Officer Leslie Sabel; Senior Master John Kirby, and Boatswain Mark
Stanley.
   Also summoned were Jeffrey Develine, Wallace Ayres and John
Alcindore, directors of owner Townsend Car Ferries Ltd., which is
now called P and O European Ferries. The corporate manslaughter
charge is against P and O European Ferries.
   The men summoned must appear before magistrates Aug. 1. The trial
is expected to begin next year.
   ``It's a pretty untested part of the law,'' said a spokeswoman
for the Crown Prosecution Service, which obtained the summonses at
Bow Street Magistrates Court in London.
   The spokeswoman, commenting on condition of anonymity, said that
except for a couple of cases in the 1920s, the state had never
brought a charge of this sort against a company.
   ``It's a complicated question because it is absolutely
unprecedented for this sort of case to go ahead,'' said Michael
Zander, professor of law at the London School of Economics.
   Maurice de Rohan, head of an association of families of the
disaster victims, welcomed the move, as did the opposition Labor
Party's transport spokesman John Prescott.
   ``It makes clear to all directors of companies that they have
corporate responsibility to see that the highest levels of safety
pertain in their areas of operation and they don't just blame the
workers,'' he said.
   The ship with an estimated 543 people aboard capsized because its
bow doors were open, letting in water that destabilized it, a public
inquiry concluded.
   Stanley, who allegedly left the doors open, was directly blamed,
while Lewry and Sabel were accused of serious negligence.
   Of Townsend Car Ferries Ltd., the inquiry report said: ``From top
to bottom, the body corporate was affected by the disease of
sloppiness,'' and guilt rested with ``all concerned in management.''
   An inquest jury returned a verdict of unlawful killing, and
police conducted a lengthy investigation.
   Last year, in an action brought by the families, a court ruled
that companies could be prosecuted for manslaughter.
</TEXT>
