<FIRST>u i AM-Angola 4thLd-Writethru a0788 06-22 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0788,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola's President, Rebel Chief Shake Hands, Agree To End Long Civil
War</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout with details, background. CORRECTS that cease-fire
to begin at midnight Friday. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NTOTO WAKU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINSHASA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos of
Marxist Angola and rebel leader Jonas Savimbi shook hands Thursday
and agreed to end 14 years of civil war, reports said.
   The accord came at the end of an African summit on Angola
attended by 14 African heads of state.
   It provides for a cease-fire in Angola to start at midnight
Friday (7 p.m. Friday EDT), according to Zairian officials quoted by
the French news agency Agence France-Presse.
   The meeting between dos Santos and Savimbi was their first since
the civil war began in 1975. Savimbi heads the U.S.-backed National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, known as UNITA.
   The reconciliation follows a U.S.-brokered regional peace accord
signed in New York in December under which South Africa agreed to
grant independence to Namibia and halt aid to Savimbi's rebels in
exchange for the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops backing dos
Santos' government.
   Angola, Cuba and South Africa signed the accord. The rebels are
not party to the agreement.
   Thursday's peace announcement was called the Declaration of
Gbadolite, after the town in northern Zaire where the summit was
held. It is the hometown of President Mobutu Sese Soko of Zaire and
lies 700 miles northeast of Kinshasa, the capital.
   A commission headed by Mobutu is to be established to bring about
national reconciliation in Angola.
   The historic handshake followed five hours of delay during which
hard talks took place, Zairian officials were quoted as saying.
   President Moussa Traore of Mali, head of the Organization of
African Unity, which held the summit, was quoted as saying in a
closing speech that a new page had been turned in African history:
   ``This brotherly handshake between Dr. Jonas Savimbi and
President dos Santos symbolizes the end of civil war in Angola,
which will open up a new era ... devoted to economic and social
development.''
   Reports said a snag developed until Savimbi agreed to remain in
his bush headquarters until elections, expected to be held in two
years.
   Earlier, he had refused to go into exile in the United States.
   ``We can now give Angola hope for peace, unity and development,''
Zambia's President Kenneth Kaunda said, according to the official
Portuguese news agency LUSA.
   In Washington, 19 members of Congress on Wednesday urged dos
Santos to negotiate wtih the rebels ``as the only means to end the
tragic civil war in Angola.''
   Kaunda said Savimbi promised at the meeting to abide by a
previous agreement to remain out of peace negotiations, according to
LUSA.
   That agreement broke a deadlock and brought Angola's government
to the conference table.
   Savimbi agreed in May he would not demand a role in any
transitional government on condition democratic elections are held
within two years.
   Major obstacles included dos Santos' insistence on maintaining
one-party rule while offering the rebels some positions in his
administration.
   The government offered rebels an amnesty and clemency, but the
guerrillas replied that the offer suggested their war was criminal
and so was unacceptable.
   Savimbi garners most of his support from the rural southern area
toward Namibia _ the Ovimbundu tribe, the biggest in Angola, and the
Ovambo. Dos Santos' power base is around northern Luanda, but his
followers are more diverse, coming from several smaller tribes.
   Dos Santos arrived ready to reconcile. Before leaving Luanda
earlier Thursday, he commuted death sentences of 50 rebels condemned
for high treason and terrorism between 1981-87, Angola's official
ANGOP news agency reported. On Wednesday, it said, the government
released 700 rebel prisoners who accepted an amnesty.
   Savimbi's guerrillas, armed by South Africa and the United
States, have been fighting to share power with Luanda's Cuban-backed
government since Angolan independence.
   Washington continues to arm the rebels and may have encouraged
the rebels to negotiate.
   Herman Cohen, assistant secretary of state for African affairs,
said from Washington on Thursday that the United States ``helped
develop'' the Zaire summit.
   ``We may have a breakthrough,'' Cohen forecast earlier Thursday.
   Angola is twice the size of Texas, with 481,354 square miles, but
has only 8 million people. Most of them live in tribal villages and
rural areas. Nearly all the Portuguese fled in 1975, leaving Angola
more than 90 percent illiterate and badly in need of capital and
skilled workers.
   Oil fields in the Angolan enclave of Cabinda supply more than 90
percent of the nation's export earnings. Angola also has diamonds,
minerals and rich agricultural land, but the civil war has seriously
disrupted the economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
