<DOCNO> AP890622-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EcclesiaSentencing     06-22 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecclesia Sentencing,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Defendants Receive Maximum Sentences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four workers in a disciplinary program
for ghetto children received maximum 20-year sentences Thursday for
beating their leader's 8-year-old daughter to death.
   Ecclesia Athletic Association leader Eldridge Broussard Jr.,
making his first appearance in court during the trial, pleaded
unsuccessfully for the release of the four pending an appeal.
   Willie K. Chambers, 35, of San Diego and Brian J. Brinson, 31,
Frederick P. Doolittle, 28, and Constance Z. Jackson, 38, all of Los
Angeles, were convicted of first-degree manslaughter May 12 in the
death of Dayna Broussard.
   Dayna endured hundreds of blows for stealing food from another
child Oct. 13, according to testimony.
   Several children forced to witness the discipline session
testified that Dayna was slammed against a wall, kicked, tripped,
slapped, dropped on the floor, shoved, bitten, spit upon and hung
out a window.
   Jackson, who beat five other Ecclesia children with an electrical
cord, was convicted June 5 of five counts each of second-degree
assault and first-degree criminal mistreatment.
   Clackamas County Circuit Judge John Lowe sentenced Jackson to 10
years in prison, to be served after the manslaughter sentence, on
that conviction. She will be eligible for parole in seven years.
   Defense lawyers asked that their clients receive light sentences
since none had criminal records. But prosecutor Alfred J. French III
urged the maximum penalty for all four.
   Chambers, who got the stiffest penalty of the four, will be
eligible for parole in 10 years.
   The 50 or more blows dealt by Chambers were mainly to blame for
the girl's death, Lowe said.
   Chambers described Dayna during the trial as ``a strong-willed,
strong-bodied world-class athlete,'' Lowe recalled. ``But she was
not yet a world-class athlete. She was an 8-year-old girl.''
   Jackson was convicted of striking and biting Dayna.
   ``It took more guts for Dayna Broussard to bite you in the leg
than for a prisoner of war to spit in the face of her captors,''
Lowe told her.
   Brinson and Doolittle, who held the girl down, will each have to
serve 40 months before being eligible for parole.
   ``No human being could have participated without asking, `Hasn't
this gone far enough?''' Lowe said of the two.
   Defense attorney Ron Thom said the sentences will be appealed.
   Broussard, who testified under a 1987 law that allows crime
victims or their families to speak at sentencing, broke down once
during his rambling, 20-minute testimony.
   ``I'm walking a tightrope,'' he explained to the court.
   ``When I don't show any emotion, I'm inhuman,'' Broussard said.
``(When I do express my feelings), people think I'm faking. I would
like to assure you my daughter's loss is serious to me.''
   He declined to comment after the sentencing.
   Broussard, 35, formed Ecclesia in Los Angeles' tough Watts area
to steer ghetto children away from drugs and crime and toward
rigorous athletic training.
   He criticized the news media Thursday for calling his
organization a cult, and portraying him as ``a madman or someone who
doesn't have any sense.''
   Broussard was in Los Angeles at the time of the beating at a
farmhouse east of Portland. He has denied all along that Dayna was
beaten, saying that children in the group were spanked as part of
the group's strict disciplinary policy.
   Fifty-three children 6 weeks to 16 years old were taken into
state protective custody after Dayna's death. They are living with
foster parents or with relatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0742,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Dissents on Flag-Burning Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 22nd graf: ``In remarks,'' to remove ``prepared for'' qualification;
SUBS last two grafs with five new grafs to render quotes as delivered;
give Doonesbury quip and volunteerism remark.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush issued a strong personal dissent
Thursday to the Supreme Court decision overturning flag-desecration
laws, declaring that ``flag burning is wrong, dead wrong.''
   Bush, who made the flag a major issue in his 1988 campaign,
commented as he unveiled a nationwide volunteer program and asked
Congress to appropriate $100 million for it over the next four years.
   Meanwhile, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater defended the
administration's response to the crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators in China.
   ``We feel the administration has spoken out loudly, strongly and
without reservation on this issue,'' Fitzwater said. ``We've spoken
out forcefully, more than any other country in the world.''
   The president also met with homeless youths in a center near
Times Square, where one young woman told him the minimum wage was so
low that it was more profitable to sell drugs.
   ``It's hard to get good jobs,'' a 20-year-old Covenant House
resident identified only as Monique said, suggesting that it was
more profitable to sell drugs. ``Working in McDonald's _ at the
minimum wage _ it just doesn't pay.''
   Bush vetoed a bill that would have raised the minimum wage from
$3.35 an hour to $4.55, saying that figure was too high.
   In a speech to New York business and community leaders, Bush
departed from his prepared text on the volunteerism program to
comment on Wednesday's 5-4 Supreme Court ruling.
   He stopped short of directly criticizing the court, saying he
understood the legal basis of the decision.
   ``But, I have to give you my personal, emotional response,'' Bush
said. ``Flag burning is wrong, dead wrong.''
   He was applauded vigorously by the luncheon crowd of about 1,000
when he concluded: ``The flag of the United States is very, very
special.''
   Bush frequently symbolically wrapped himself in the flag during
last year's campaign, even giving a speech outside a New Jersey flag
factory.
   He repeatedly attacked his Democratic opponent, Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis, for having vetoed a school pledge of
allegiance law.
   The court's decision restricts the power of states to punish
those who burn or otherwise desecrate an American flag.
   Bush borrowed from another campaign theme, his ``thousand points
of light,'' in continuing to trumpet the theme of volunteerism he
has heralded all week.
   He announced that he would serve as honorary chairman of a
``Points of Light Foundation'' to oversee volunteer efforts, and
that New Jersey Gov. Tom Kean would head the foundation's advisory
committee.
   Bush said he would ask Congress for $25 million a year over the
next four years to support the non-profit independent organization,
which will solicit matching funds from the private sector.
   Kean, who said Bush had asked him to head the committee Wednesday
night, said specific uses for the funding had not been decided.
   ``This is what I mean when I talk of a thousand points of light:
That vast galaxy of people and institutions working together to
solve problems in their own back yard,'' Bush said.
   He first used the ``points of light'' phrase at last summer's
Republican convention.
   The president called on all individuals, businesses and
institutions to join in the volunteer effort, saying corporations
should set up literacy programs to make sure each employee can read
and that restaurants and grocery stores should distribute surplus
food to soup kitchens and local shelters.
   In remarks at a New York State Republican dinner, Bush turned to
politics, saying that New York voters, ``in particular minority and
ethnic voters, are shifting from automatic loyalty to the other
party and voting Republican more and more often.''
   ``We are justly proud of how far we've come as a party _ so far
that we now have a good chance of winning the mayor's office in New
York City, the most powerful local office in America.''
   Former U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani is a leading candidate in
the Republican effort to oust incumbent Democratic Mayor Ed Koch.
   At a 100th anniversary celebration for the Wall Street Journal,
Bush praised the publication.
   ``In a changing world that offers 64 channels of cable
television, the six columns of the Wall Street Journal are as
familiar as the morning coffee at our breakfast tables,'' he said.
   He called the Journal ``one of America's most trusted
publications,'' but joked that ``not every article was a Pulitzer
Prize winner. In 1967, a front page story on China predicted the
communist government wouldn't last the year.''
   The president said he actually likes ``because you don't carry
Doonesbury,'' the comic strip that frequently lampoons Bush. The
Journal carries no comic strips.
   He also returned to his main theme of the day of volunteerism,
noting that some of the nation's top corporate executives were in
the audience.
   ``It is my request _ I believe, your obligation _ to donate the
services of the talented and the enterprising within your ranks.
Many are doing this now. Everyone should do this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
