<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-ChemicalSpill     06-22 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Chemical Spill,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Spill Forces Bush to Change Travel Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fuel truck spill forced President Bush to
change his route out of New York City Thursday night.
   Air Force One flew from Newark International Airport in New
Jersey to John F. Kennedy Airport in Queens borough of New York
because of concerns by security officials about the accident near
the Newark airport, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told
reporters.
   Bush delayed the departure of his motorcade from a banquet in
downtown Manhattan to let Secret Service escorts and New York City
police chart a new course to the Kennedy Airport.
   ``There has been an accident involving two fuel trucks near the
Newark airport,`` Fitzwater told reporters outside the building
where the president and Mrs. Bush had attended the 100th anniversary
dinner of the Wall Street Journal.
   Fitzwater said he was not sure what the trucks carried but
``whatever they are they are considered toxic, especially when
considered mixed.''
   ``For those reasons we have been advised to move Air Force One
and the press plane to another location,'' he added.
   Bush had flown to Newark on Air Force One Thursday morning to
visit a shelter for runaway youth and to call for a crusade to spur
volunteerism in a speech before a civic group.
</TEXT>
