<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany     06-22 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Defends China's Version Of Crackdown, Criticizes Hungarian
Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of East Germany's Communist Party, one of
the most rigid in the Soviet bloc, on Thursday defended China's
official version of the crackdown on pro-democracy activists.
   Joachim Herrmann, a member of the party's policy-making
Politburo, also denounced democratic reform in Hungary and backed
the Berlin Wall.
   Herrmann, who also serves as secretary of the party's Central
Committee, made his comments in a Politburo report he read to a
Central Committee meeting on foreign policy.
   Speaking about the violent suppression of student demonstrators
in China, Herrmann said East Germany has published all official
Chinese statements with the purpose of denying ``Western horror
stories'' and to present ``objective information.''
   Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources say the death
toll in the June 3-4 crackdown may have been as high as 3,000. The
Chinese government's most recent report says 100 soldiers and 100
civilians died. Most East Germans are able to watch West German
television.
   Herrmann, whose speech was distributed by the government-run news
agency ADN, said the ``peaceful student demonstrations'' in Beijing
were intended to be used for a ``counter-revolutionary overthrow of
people's power in China.''
   The Politburo makes all key decisions in East Germany and its
report expresses the views of the country's aging leaders, led by
Erich Honecker, head of the party.
   The party has strongly resisted Soviet-style economic and
political reforms, and Herrmann's speech reaffirmed the country's
leading hard-line position in the Soviet bloc.
   The Politburo report said East Germany will remain true to its
own policies and made no hints at any reforms.
   Hungary's Communist Party and opposition groups have agreed to
hold multi-party elections by next summer. Last week, hundreds of
thousands of Hungarians turned out for an emotional reburial of Imre
Nagy, the communist leader executed after leading a revolt crushed
by Soviet troops in 1956.
   ``Under the flag of `renewing socialism,' forces are at work that
strive for the removal of socialism. In this connection, the
developments in Hungary fill us with great concern,'' Herrmann said.
   He accused Western leaders whom he did not identify of stepping
up ideological and economic pressure on communist countries in an
attempt to make them reject communism and turn to capitalism.
   Herrmann said the Berlin Wall will continue to protect East
Germany from ``economic plundering, from the penetration of criminal
elements ... and from drug smuggling.''
   He said the Berlin Wall will remain as long as the ``reasons that
led to its construction remain.'' East Germany claims it built the
wall to prevent a possible attack or infiltration from the West.
   However, Western governments agree that East Germany built the
wall at Soviet insistence to stop the massive flow of refugees from
East to West.
   President Bush, in a speech during a visit to West Germany this
month, challenged East Germany to tear down the Berlin Wall.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev noted that ``nothing is
eternal'' and that the wall was not ``a great problem'' in East-West
relations, but he did not call for its removal when he visited West
Germany last week.
</TEXT>
