<HEAD>Babysitter Says Hurt Referred to Jennings as His Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former babysitter testified Thursday that actor
William Hurt referred to the mother of his son as his wife while
having lunch with the child in a pizza parlor in the summer of 1985.
   Linda Patrick, who said she had met Hurt for the first time,
testified on the fourth day of a trial to determine whether the
actor had a common-law marriage in South Carolina with former
ballerina Sandra Jennings.
   ``How do you like working with my wife?'' she quoted Hurt as
asking about Jennings, mother of Hurt's son, Alexander, now 6.
   The babysitter said that occasionally when she went for walks
with the boy, people would come up and say, ``How is Mrs. Hurt?''
That comment was stricken from the record because it was not given
in response to a question.
   Jennings, 32, bases her claim of a common-law marriage on four
weeks she spent with Hurt in Beaufort, S.C., from Dec. 9, 1982, when
he learned he was divorced from actress Mary Beth Hurt, to Jan. 10,
1983, when Hurt and Jennings left the state. Hurt was filming ``The
Big Chill'' there at the time.
   Jennings now seeks to have the court declare that she and Hurt
are married so she can get a ``divorce'' and a share of his assets,
estimated by her lawyer, A. Richard Golub, to be about $10 million.
   Patrick was another of several witnesses who have testified that
Hurt called Jennings his wife, but no one has said he made such a
reference during the four-week period in South Carolina on which
Jennings' claim is based.
   South Carolina recognizes common-law marriages; New York does not.
   The trial continues on Monday, when it is expected to conclude.
</TEXT>
