<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv23   06-22 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 23,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Friday, June 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ready To Fight or Cooperate?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Will an economically integrated Europe, scheduled
for 1992, cooperate in world trade for the benefit of everyone or
fight to maintain a privileged position for itself?
   On either side of the Atlantic the almost automatic answer varies
little: Why of course Europe will pursue an open trade policy.
Doesn't everyone know that free trade _ trade without artificial
barriers _ benefits everyone?
   The automatic response and the eagerness to assure, however, may
be only a veneer covering vast uncertainties. An economically
unified Europe could be an amiable giant or, if provoked, a muscled
bully protecting his turf.
   In the abstract, every important trading nation professes an
almost theological belief in free trade. But each also is aware of
the benefits, however temporary, of limiting the flow of foreign
goods into its markets.
   Which course will Europe take?
   By the end of 1992, members of the European Economic Community
plan to remove almost all barriers to each other's trade, investment
and movement of labor, creating a common market of 320 million
people.
   Obviously, they wouldn't do so if they didn't believe in mutual
benefits for each other. Instead of a dozen relatively weak markets
for goods, the united market would be an economic entity comparable
to the United States.
   Having achieved that, will they then seek to protect their
``free'' market from others? Will they restrict Japanese and
American access, or will they express their faith in open
competition by leaving their market doors ajar?
   While the latter seems the most likely route, the underlying
uncertainty is aroused again and again by incidents that, isolated
from the bigger picture, seem of far less importance.
   This week in Geneva, for example, some European trade negotiators
felt the United States had violated the spirit of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade by threatening trade sanctions
against Brazil, India and Japan.
   Those sanctions have not been imposed, and there is some question
about whether Uncle Sam really intends to do anything at all about
what he perceives to be unfair trade practices by these nations.
   The mere threat, however, was sufficient to raise tempers _ and
in trade talks, whenever tempers rise the threat of retaliation soon
follows.
   A simple French television commercial, now two years old but
still replayed in the minds of wary Americans and Japanese, also
demonstrates how close those uncertainties are to the surface.
   The commercial, sponsored by the French government, showed a
skinny boxer faced down by a huge American football player and a
massive and menacing Japanese sumo wrester.
   The fate of the skinny French boxer seemed bleak, but he did not
run. No need to, because soon he was surrounded by 11 other boxers
who helped rout the huge American football player and the massive
Japanese wrestler.
   In short, scratch a free-trader on either side of the Atlantic or
anywhere else in the world and you might find a protectionist.
   The latter might bury their sympathies for the sake of public
decorum, but seldom do they bury them so deep that they cannot be
aroused and resurrected immediately.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday, June 22.</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv23   06-22 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 23,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs,June 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sexual Harassment Troubles Churches As Women Clergy Increase</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shocked at its extent, churches are grappling
with a newly recognized problem in their own domain _ sexual
harassment of women, particularly female clergy.
   Concern about it has risen as increasing numbers of women have
entered the ordained ministry, traditionally a profession of males
and largely limited to them until modern times.
   The trouble, however, has surfaced among lay women as well as
clergywomen.
   It has turned up in ``every setting of the church,'' declared the
board of directors of the United Church of Christ's Coordinating
Center for Women in Church and Society, after reviewing reports
about it.
   One of the center's research projects found that of 138 women
clergy surveyed, 45 percent of them said they had been sexually
harassed in the workplace, that is, in church precincts.
   ``It's a startling figure,'' said Marilyn Breitling of St. Louis,
the center's executive director. ``The harassment was not identified
by type, but no matter how you define it, that's an inordinately
high number.
   ``We were shocked.''
   However, there has been little or no awareness of the problem
until recently, she said, but it now is drawing increased attention
in major Protestant denominations, most of which now ordain women.
   ``It was very, very hidden and people did not talk about it, but
now they're beginning to talk about it in a straightforward way, and
seek ways to deal with it,'' she said in a telephone interview.
   Especially in church, ``you expect to be treated with respect and
dignity,'' she said. For church colleagues ``to intimidate, take
advantage, harass or molest is just unconscionable.
   ``Unfortunately, those kind of things are happening. Harassment
is occuring even in the church. The church needs to speak to that
problem in its own life, just as it speaks to things in the culture
at large.''
   Among lay women, the center's survey found 20 percent of them
reported incidents of sexual harassment within the church, less than
half the proportion of women clergy doing so.
   The 1.7-million-member United Church through its antecedant
Congregationalism (merged in 1957 with the Evangelical and Reformed
Church) pioneered women's ordination, beginning in the l850's.
   Sixteen percent of the denomination's 10,000 clergy are women.
   Other Protestant bodies, including Presbyterians, Lutherans,
United Methodists, Episcopalians and others, have begun ordaining
women only since the 1950's. More than 20,000 women now are among
U.S. clergy.
   Sexual harassment has aroused concern in several denominations.
The Presbyterian Church (USA) last week called for development of a
church-wide policy on sexual misbehavior in the church household.
   In most denominations, ``all of us are very much concerned about
the issue,'' said Ann Dubois, a Louisville, Ky., Presbyterian
specialist on women in church employment.
   A special study about it is under way in the Northeast.
   ``It's no respecter of denominations,'' Mrs. Breitling said.
``It's a very common experience. It's also one we've avoided dealing
with. But the issue is coming to the fore in most every
denomination.''
   The United Methodist Church at its l986 governing conference said
sexual harassment has been documented in congregations, agencies,
seminaries and other institutions. One limited survey found one in
eight United Methodist women reported being sexually harassed in
church environs.
   The denomination called for grievance procedures for victims and
penalties for offenders. It also launched a denomination-wide study
on the extent of church sexual harassment.
   The United Church's women's center proposes a resolution for the
denomination's General Synod June 29-July 4, saying women
volunteers, seminarians, pastors and lay employees report ``varied
experiences of sexual harassment.''
   That is a ``disappointing fact in an institution that is based on
values of equality and respect for all persons,'' the measure says.
It calls for gathering of more data and developing guidelines about
the matter.
   The resolution identifies two types of sexual harassment, one
being the ``imposition of unwelcome sexual activity, suggestion or
behavior in a relationship of unequal power.''
   That refers to such situations as between pastor and associate
minister or intern, or between clergywomen and members of the church
board of trustees when superiors manipulate women into demoralizing
affairs.
   A second type of harassment cited is the creation of a ``hostile,
intimidating atmosphere in the workplace'' that offends or disturbs
women personnel, even if there is ``no direct damage to victims.''
   ``Even if it's seemingly harmless inuendo, it can be offensive
and create an unpleasant work situation,'' Ms. Breitling said.
``There are a lot of variations and complex relationship questions.''
   While open, friendly hugs or pats between mutually respecting
associates are not considered in the harassment category, she said
objectionable activity generally is distinguishable by victims.
   As one woman put it, ``I've been hugged, and I've been `groped'
and I know the difference.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
