<FIRST>r f PM-GATT-WorldTrade     06-22 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GATT-World Trade,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Criticism of Trade Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. official has rejected criticism from
negotiators in world trade talks that U.S. policy undermined efforts
to liberalize international trade.
   Delegates at a special meeting of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade condemned provisions in the 1988 U.S. trade act
which call for penalties against countries deemed to be especially
protectionist.
   Arthur Dunkel, director-general of the 96-nation organization,
issued an appeal Wednesday that governments should not take action
outside GATT's international trade rules as unilateral measures had
been tried before and failed, the spokesman said.
   Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Rufus Yerxa told the special
closed session of the GATT council that the United States ``would
not apologize for actions taken in trying to pursue its trade
objectives,'' and said the Bush administration was committed to the
current four-year round of global trade-freeing talks, according to
a partial text of his speech released to journalists.
   But EEC ambassador Tran Van-Thinh warned in the closed meeting of
the possible ``sinking of the GATT because of an error of U.S.
judgment,'' a GATT spokesman said.
   Last month the U.S. administration singled out Japan, Brazil and
India for priority action under the so-called 301 section of its
trade act because of alleged serious violations against fair trade.
   The three countries face 100 percent tariffs on selected exports
to the United States if they do not remove the offending barriers to
U.S. goods within 18 months.
   Yerxa told the meeting Wednesday that the United States had taken
no action under the new procedure other than ``to identify trade
liberalizing priorities'' in areas which are ``significant barriers
to world trade.''
   Arguing that the United States was ``remarkably open'' in the
face of a huge trade deficit, he said that 60 percent of all Third
World exports of manufactured goods go to the United States, twice
as many as the European Economic Community and five times as many as
Japan received.
   Brazilian ambassador Rubens Ricupero said the U.S. action
``undermines and puts in jeopardy the whole Uruguay Round,'' and
``has already wasted and ruined the precious capital of goodwill''
built up during the talks.
   Indian representative Bal Krishan Zutshi said the implementation
of the 301 provisions would ``emasculate the multilateral trading
system.''
   Japanese ambassador Joshio Hatano cited U.S. disregard of the
system within the GATT for settling trade disputes.
   ``To be judge, jury and executioner at the same time is not
acceptable,'' he told the meeting.
   Copies of the texts from the Brazilian, Japanese and Indian were
made available to journalists.
   The GATT spokesman said that Dunkel told the meeting that GATT
had been established in 1948 after ``unilateralism and bilateralism
had been tried and failed.''
   Dunkel told the meeting if the drafters of the founding agreement
were still alive, ``they would have asked in despair, do world
economic relations have to go through the same cycle again? Can the
present generation of trade policy makers not learn from the
experiences of a previous one?'' the spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
