<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-Boeing     06-22 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Boeing,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Allows Boeing 737-400 Jets To Fly With Power Curb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Civil Aviation Authority has lifted its
grounding order on 12 Boeing 737-400 jets operated by British
airlines as long as modifications are made to cut the engines' power.
   The planes were grounded nine days ago after two incidents in
which 737-400s were forced to make emergency landings because fan
blades broke in their CFM 56-3C engines.
   The engines are manufactured by CFM International, a joint
venture between SNECMA of France and General Electric Co. of the
United States.
   Britain's CAA said Wednesday it was imposing power cuts that
effectively lower the engines' thrust to that of a previous
generation of the make.
   Airlines were also ordered to replace the engines' fan blades and
discs. Regular visual inspections of fan blades and the front face
of the engine discs will also be required, the CAA said.
   The spokesman, speaking anonymously, said airlines were already
making the modifications and some 737-400s could be back in
operation on Thursday.
   The grounding order was made after fan blades broke on a DanAir
jet at Gatwick Airport on June 9 and on a British Midland Airways
aircraft at Heathrow Airport on June 11.
   Fan blade problems were also thought to have contributed to the
engine failure which led to the crash in January of a British
Midland 737-400 near East Midlands Airport in Leicestershire,
killing 47.
   The Civil Aviation Authority had originally said it did not
believe that lowering the engines' power would solve the problem.
But a CAA spokesman said the agency had been convinced by tests
showing the fan blade failure occurred at a certain level of thrust.
   ``We are putting the clock back to the previous standard and we
are satisfied that restores the necessary safety margin,'' he said.
   British airlines using 737-400s said they had managed to keep
flying on schedule by using spare aircraft or borrowing
replacements. In addition to British Midland and DanAir, 737-400s
are operated by Novair, Air Europe and Air UK-Leisure.
</TEXT>
