<SECOND>PM-Brunswick,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brunswick To Sell Industrial Products Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SKOKIE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brunswick Corp. says it will sell its
1,300-employee industrial-products division as part of its strategy
to concentrate on recreational, defense and aerospace products.
   The division manufactures Vapor brand door-operating systems for
buses and trains at plants in Niles, Ill., and Montreal, as well as
Vapor air-conditioning systems in Montgomery, Ala.
   The unit also supplies the energy industry with oilfield valves
and controls manufactured by its TXT-Cooper operation in Houston.
   The industrial-products division had sales of about $150 million
in 1988 but suffered a decline in operating earnings.
   ``It's not a highly profitable business, but they definitely make
money,'' Brunswick spokesman Ross Stemer said in a telephone
interview Wednesday.
   Stemer would not reveal the unit's operating income for 1988.
   Brunswick as a whole reported sales of $3.28 billion last year
and net income of $193 million.
   Stemer said Brunswick was already holding discussions with
prospective buyers, but had not set a deadline for selling the
division. He said the unit might be sold as a whole or in pieces.
   Brunwick, based in this north Chicago suburb, is an international
leader in marine power, pleasure boating, recreational, defense and
aerospace products.
   Its brands include Mercury and Mariner outboard motors, Bayliner
and Sea Ray pleasure boats, Zebco fishing gear, Brunswick bowling
equipment and Circle Seal controls.
</TEXT>
