<DOCNO> AP890622-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FedResignation     06-22 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed Resignation,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Governor Heller Quits, Citing Salary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   H. Robert Heller, citing financial hardships in
living on his $82,500-a-year government salary, says he will resign
as one of the seven members of the Federal Reserve Board.
   An expert in international economics, Heller said Wednesday he
would return to California to become an executive vice president of
Visa International, the giant credit card company.
   In a meeting with reporters, he refused to disclose his exact
salary at Visa, saying only that it would be a ``pretty sizable''
increase that would represent a multiple of his government pay.
   Heller specifically cited Congress' rejection earlier this year
of a proposed federal pay raise as one factor in his decision to
leave. Under the proposal, which would have boosted congressional
salaries as well as those of top officials, the pay of a Federal
Reserve governor would have risen to $125,000.
   His resignation will give President Bush his first opportunity to
appoint someone to the Federal Reserve Board. The other six members,
including Chairman Alan Greenspan, were appointed by former
President Reagan.
   Economists said it was unlikely Heller's surprise departure would
affect policy at the central bank.
   Heller generally espoused supply-side monetary views emphasizing
economic growth, appearing at times to be at odds with the tough
anti-inflation leanings of former Chairman Paul Volcker.
   Bush, who early in the year complained that the central bank was
risking a recession by a too-tight money policy, was likely to
appoint a replacement very close to Heller's philosophy, analysts
predicted.
   ``I would expect the appointment will be someone who is at least
as dovish on inflation as Heller was,'' said Allen Sinai, chief
economist of the Boston Co.
   The replacement by law must come from a Federal Reserve regional
bank district not now represented on the board. Heller came from the
San Francisco region, which will now be vacant. Other regions not
now represented on the board are Philadelphia, Cleveland, Atlanta,
St. Louis and Minneapolis.
   Heller joined the board in August 1986 and his replacement will
fill a term that lasts until Jan. 31, 1996.
   In his resignation letter, Heller said he was leaving for
``personal considerations.'' He told reporters he had taken a
significant pay cut to join the government and that with two
children approaching college age he found that ``financially, it
gets tougher and tougher.''
   Before joining the Federal Reserve, Heller served as a senior
vice president and director of international economic research for
Bank of America in San Francisco.
   Heller, who was born in Germany and is a naturalized American
citizen, said the Visa job offered him the chance to return to San
Francisco and to use his international experience in dealing with
Visa's operations in 185 countries.
   Heller, 49, was generally recognized as the international expert
on the board and several economists said they expected that Bush
would take that and ideological considerations into consideration
when choosing a replacement.
   ``I think the White House would want somebody ... willing to
ensure that economic growth is maintained at some expense on the
inflation front,'' said Samuel Kahan of Kleinwort Benson Government
Securities Inc. in Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
