<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   06-22 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Asks Court to Cut Pilot Pay, Increase Work Hours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines attorney says the carrier's move
to end its contract with striking pilots and cut wages is a matter
of economics, but the pilots union says it reflects management's
anti-labor attitude.
   ``The albatross around Eastern's neck is not labor costs, but an
inept and rapacious management,'' the Air Line Pilots Association
said in a statement late Wednesday.
   Eastern on Wednesday asked the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York
to terminate the contract its pilots had been working under before
the Machinists union in March led a massive work stoppage that
crippled the airline.
   The Miami-based carrier also is seeking approval for a permanent
increase in the number of hours a pilot may work each month and
about $50 million in temporary wage and benefit concessions.
   ``This is not a union-busting tactic,'' said Eastern attorney
Harvey Miller. ``This is an economic problem.''
   Eastern officials said the new conditions are supported by pilots
who have continued to fly during the strike and are similar to cuts
taken by management and other non-union employees during the
3-month-old strike.
   The pilots union said Eastern's actions came as no surprise.
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo ``is following basically
the same pattern of harsh treatment for workers that he established
when he took Continental Airlines into bankruptcy and abrogated its
labor contracts there in 1983,'' ALPA's statement said.
   Lorenzo abrogated union contracts with employees of Continental,
like Eastern a Texas Air subsidiary, after he put Continental into
bankruptcy protection. The carrier, based in Houston, is now
non-union.
   But the pilots union said Wednesday it expects Lorenzo to have a
``much more difficult time'' doing the same with Eastern because
Congress tightened the bankruptcy laws after the Continental episode
to make it harder for companies to cancel contracts through
bankruptcy reorganization. Now a company must show it is negotiating
in good faith.
   Miller said Eastern sought termination of the pilots' contract,
which expired a year ago, in order to move ahead with rebuilding
plans because the union had balked at negotiating a new contract.
Eastern had about 3,600 pilots before the strike, but plans to
rebuild into a smaller carrier with about 1,700 pilots.
   Under Section 1113 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, the court has 14
to 21 days to schedule a hearing and 30 days to rule on Eastern's
request.
   Eastern is seeking to cut the pilots' pay by 10 percent for six
months, 5 percent for the next six months and to delay vacations
until next year. Wage and pension-plan concessions would be restored
by half on Jan. 31, 1990, and in full by August 1990.
   The airline also is asking for permanent work rule changes. The
airline wants to be able to schedule pilots to fly 68 hours a month
in 1990 and 60 hours a month thereafter, compared with the
pre-strike 46 hours. Federal regulations allow a pilot to fly an
average of 85 hours a month, with a maximum of 100 hours.
   The Machinists went on strike March 4 after federal mediation
failed. The pilots' contract is still open to negotiation and
normally would have to go through federal mediation, but Miller said
the airline can seek to end the contract because the company is in
Chapter 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
