<FIRST>r f PM-UAWConvention Bjt   06-22 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAW Convention, Bjt,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Director's Defeat May Not Signal End of UAW Dissident Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Convention to convene at 3 p.m. EDT. PMs lead unlikely.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The strongest United Auto Workers
dissident movement in 40 years has lost a seat on the union's
executive board, but the UAW's leadership may be hearing more from
the New Directions group.
   Jerry Tucker of St. Louis was defeated for re-election Wednesday
as director of UAW Region 5 in eight south-central states, losing to
Roy Wyse of the Kansas City area.
   Tucker and New Directions have criticized UAW President Owen
Bieber for allegedly stifling dissent within the UAW and losing
sight of the 1 million-member union's roots by making to cooperative
labor agreements with automakers.
   Bieber and members of his Administration Caucus have denied the
charges. But the New Directions effort has gained widespread
rank-and-file support and is the most serious challenge to the UAW's
leadership since the mid-1940s, when Walter Reuther was solidifying
control of the then-fledgling union.
   After the regional director election, one New Directions member
asked Bieber to set aside the entire vote and hold another election
within two months.
   That brought catcalls and mild obscenities from Wyse supporters.
Bieber ruled the motion out of order.
   On his way out of the caucus, Victor Reuther, brother of Walter
Reuther and a backer of Tucker's efforts, said a similar motion
could be brought before the convention today.
   Tucker had little to say immediately after the loss, other than
that he had not decided about whether he would take the election
challenge to court. Tucker was chosen director of Region 5 in a
federally supervised election Sept. 1, 1988, after he challenged an
earlier election in court. He lost that contest by an extremely
narrow margin.
   Wyse, appointed by Bieber as an assistant director in Region 5
three years ago, said after his election that union members ``saw
through the New Directions movement. They saw they had questions but
no answers.
   ``I think it's the beginning of the end for the New Directions
movement,'' he said.
   Wyse said he would try to reconcile the two camps in his huge
region. But, he added: ``It will take a while. There are some scars
out there that need to be healed.''
   That was evident in the packed hotel room where the caucus was
held. Both sides wore jackets with their candidates' names on the
back _ Tucker's forces in blue and Wyse's in white.
   Earlier Wednesday, the Administration Caucus's slate of top union
officers was elected to three-year terms without opposition.
   Bieber won his third term as the union's president. Incumbent
Secretary-Treasurer Bill Casstevens was elected to a full term after
succeeding the late Raymond Majerus, who died Jan. 14, 1988.
   Delegates also elected four vice presidents _ two incumbents and
two to succeed the retiring Donald Ephlin and Marc Stepp.
   Bieber will assign responsibilities to his new vice presidents.
It's expected that Stephen Yokich will move from the union's Ford
Department to head the General Motors Department, succeeding Ephlin;
newly elected vice president Ernie Lofton will succeed Yokich; and
Stan Marshall, also elected as vice president Wednesday, will follow
Stepp as director of the Chrysler Department.
   Vice President Odessa Kommer, the union's most senior vice
president having been elected first in 1974, probably will keep many
of her responsibilities, including oversight of the union's
relations with a number of automotive supplier companies.
</TEXT>
