<FIRST>r f PM-Time Bjt   06-22 0865</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, Bjt,0895</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount, Time Trade Punches in Buyout Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. has gone to court
to block Time Inc.'s proposed $14 billion buyout of Warner
Communications Inc.
   But a cable operator that is 82 percent-owned by Time said
Paramount is running into opposition from local officials over its
own plans to acquire the operator's cable franchises in connection
with a hostile $10.7 billion bid for Time.
   Meanwhile, Paramount asked the New York Stock Exchange to
investigate Time's bid for Warner on the ground that the companies
may have violated exchange rules. The exchange said it would comply
with the request.
   Those were among the developments Wednesday in what is shaping up
as a fiercely contested takeover battle that could produce one of
the world's largest communications companies no matter who wins.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Time rose
$4.75 a share to $157.25 on Wednesday after losing $19 in the
previous three sessions.
   Warner fell $1 a share to $58.50 while Paramount lost 12{ cents a
share to $59.25.
   Paramount filed a 49-page amendment to an earlier suit in
Delaware Chancery Court on Wednesday in which it said Time acted
improperly in rejecting Paramount's buyout offer and launching its
own takeover bid for Warner.
   The complaint said the offer for Warner ``amounts to a
multibillion dollar abuse of Time's stockholders for the purpose of
protecting the secure and prosperous future of Time and Warner
management.''
   Paramount also asked that the court nullify results of the
upcoming election of four Time board members. Time's chairman and
chief executive, J. Richard Munro, and its president, Nicholas J.
Nicholas Jr., are nominees.
   Paramount said the pending election is a sham because no opposing
candidates have been nominated.
   In response to the amended complaint, Time said in a statement
that Paramount's allegations were without merit.
   Time said it would ``respond to the complaint in the proper forum
_ Delaware Chancery Court _ and demonstrate clearly its position and
the merits of its case.''
   In its amendment to the suit, Paramount also claimed that a stock
swap recently completed between Time and Warner violated NYSE rules
that require shareholder approval for such a transaction.
   If the Big Board finds that Time or Warner had violated its
rules, it could bar the merged company from trading its shares on
the exchange.
   A hearing on Paramount's suit is set for July 11.
   Paramount, an entertainment and publishing concern, launched a
$175 a share tender offer for Time's stock on June 6, only 2{ weeks
before Time and Warner shareholders originally were to vote on a
merger of the companies.
   Time, a leading magazine and book publisher and cable programmer
and operator, rejected Paramount's offer Friday, saying it was
inadequate and highly conditional and that securing regulatory
approvals for cable system transfers alone would take a year or more.
   Time also said it had revised its merger agreement with Warner to
provide a $70-a-share buyout of the movie, record and cable concern.
   While shareholder approval was needed for the original merger,
Time's shareholders are not being asked to vote on the acquisition
of Warner's stock.
   Meanwhile, the cable operator American Television and
Communications Corp. said Wednesday local opposition is growing to
Paramount's plans for acquiring cable franchises associated with
Time.
   ATC, based in Stamford, Conn., has said Paramount's acquisition
of Time is illegal because the change in control would place ATC in
violation of many of its cable franchise agreements.
   It said officials from the states of Kansas and Hawaii and 16
cities including Indianapolis, Denver, Kansas City, Mo., and
Charlotte, N.C. have complained to federal officials that
Paramount's takeover plan abrogates the local right of prior
approval for cable franchise ownership in their areas.
   ATC also said that Paramount has indicated in a court filing in
Connecticut that it won't meet the July 5 deadline set in its tender
offer for Time.
   Asked for a response, Paramount said it intends to extend the
expiration date of its tender offer until after the Delaware court
decision.
   Paramount also said it expects to get cable franchise approval
``where required by state and local law in an orderly and
expeditious way.''
   In its amended complaint in the Delaware court , Paramount argues
that Time's management ``launched a massive campaign to block the
Paramount offer'' before Time's board made its public statement on
the merits of the offer.
   The complaint said that before the board acted, Time wrote to at
least 22 state attorneys general, urging them to oppose any action
by Paramount to get quick approval of its offer.
   Paramount said Time failed in moving the date of its annual
meeting to June 30 from June 23 to adjust the May 1 record date for
eligibility to vote, even though the company acknowledged that a
large number of shares have since changed hands. It also noted the
meeting will not deal with any aspect of the Time-Warner merger plan
but only election of directors, who are unopposed.
   ``The board's action make one thing clear: Time is being run
solely for the benefit of its management,'' the suit said.
</TEXT>
