<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-22 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell in early trading today against
all European currencies and the Japanese yen.
   Gold prices were higher, moving up on the dollar's weakness.
   Traders said they were puzzled by the dollar's direction.
   ``We're all trying to determine what kind of consolidation phase
this is. It doesn't fit any of the patterns,'' said one analyst in
Milan, Italy.
   ``Frequent reversals and sharp rallies are both possible,'' said
another analyst in Milan.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before the European markets open,
the dollar closed at 141.40, down 3.55 yen from Wednesday's close.
Later in London, it was trading at 140.75 yen.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe, compared with
Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.9525 West German marks, down
from 1.9680; 1.6830 Swiss francs, down from 1.7005; 6.6250 French
francs, down from 6.6795; 2.2002 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2375;
1,418.55 Italian lire, down from 1.439.50; and 1.1920 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.19675.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5615, compared with $1.54675
late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at $370.70 an ounce, up from $366.75 late
Wednesday. At mid-morning, the city's five major gold dealers fixed
a recommended price of $370.40.
   In Zurich, gold was selling at $370 this morning, up from $366.40
late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong gold closed at $370.49, up from $366.57 late
Wednesday.
   Gold moved up $5.75 in New York trading on Wednesday following a
late rally on the New York Commodity Exchange that pushed the price
as high as $372.40. Dealers said gold was reacting to a weaker
dollar.
   Silver bullion traded in London today at $5.34 a troy ounce, up
from $5.28 late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
