<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     06-22 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today,
while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index fell slightly.
   The dollar closed at 141.40 yen, down 3.55 yen from Wednesday's
close of 144.95 yen. It opened at 141.75 yen, its high for the day,
and fell as low as 140.35 yen.
   It was the dollar's lowest close since 140.65 yen on June 5. It
had climbed to 151.30 a week ago.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 20.31
points, or 0.06 percent, ending at 33,324.97. The index, a
111.81-point gainer the previous day, inched up in early trading
today, then turned downward.
   Kenji Ishizuka, a dealer with Daiwa Securities in Tokyo, said the
market lost energy and became directionless after its early gains.
   ``Following last week's large losses, the market's energy has not
come back yet,'' he said. Affected by large swings in the dollar-yen
exchange rate, the Nikkei lost more than 1,100 points last week.
   Most investors retreated to the sidelines in the afternoon
session, making trading thin, Ishizuka said.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 550 million
shares, down from Wednesday's 600 million.
   On the foreign exchange market, traders said expectations for a
higher dollar had disappeared after its sharp downswing in New York
overnight, triggered by reports of new government efforts to hold it
below 140 yen.
   Masafumi Koyama, an analyst with the Bank of Tokyo, said any
rumors or remarks suggesting a lower dollar could be a strong
dollar-selling incentive now.
   ``A majority of Japanese investors sold the dollar, trying to see
how far they could push it down to reach an appropriate dollar-yen
rate,'' he said.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly sold dollars to help push the U.S.
currency down, but neither the amount nor the intervention itself
had been confirmed, Koyama said.
   ``The market took the central bank action as showing its
intention to eventually push the dollar below the 140 yen mark,'' he
said.
   Koyama said it still was too early to determine the market trend.
   ``That's why many investors have been avoiding major moves, and
just making position adjustments,'' he added.
</TEXT>
