<FIRST>r f PM-EmissionsTalks     06-22 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emissions Talks,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Automakers Discuss Pollution Steps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may not have envisioned such a
summit, but his clean-air proposals have the Big Three automakers
talking to each other.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. have been
discussing ways to beat Japanese and European competitors to market
with cleaner-running cars, but have not decided whether to
collaborate in their efforts.
   ``I don't know if that's possible or not,'' Ford spokesman Dick
Judy said Wednesday.
   Ward's Automotive Reports said Wednesday it would report in its
upcoming edition that the big U.S. automakers might seek an
antitrust waiver for research on emissions controls, alternate fuels
and fuel economy steps to meet new regulations proposed by Congress
and the Bush administration.
   Congress granted an antitrust exemption under the National
Cooperative Research Act for joint research begun by the Big Three
in 1988 on composite materials, Ward's said in a news release.
   Judy confirmed that General Motors, Ford and Chrysler executives
met to talk about environmental and energy questions.
   Ford Chairman Donald Petersen and Vice Chairman Harold A. Poling
hosted the June 6 meeting in Dearborn, Judy said. GM Chairman Roger
Smith and Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald Greenwald attended, he said.
   ``It was a discussion of everyone's points of view on subjects
which have been made public in recent congressional testimony,'' the
spokesman said.
   He cited testimony by Helen Petrauskas, Ford's vice president for
environmental and safety engineering, that the company could support
pooling of industry and government research efforts on
anti-pollution and fuel-saving technologies.
   Judy said he did not know of any further meetings among the
automakers.
   U.S. Department of Transportation, National Transportation Safety
Board and Environmental Protection Agency spokesmen said the
agencies were not involved in the automakers' discussions.
   GM spokesman Jim Crellin said the executives met to discuss
mutual clean-air and energy policy concerns. ``It was a private
meeting, and we are not discussing the subjects,'' he said.
   Chrysler spokeswoman Karen Stewart said the discussion involved
non-competitive environmental and energy issues. She also would not
elaborate.
