<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirBags     06-22 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Bags,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Bags Standard On Chrysler 1990 Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As automakers adopt inflatable air bags as a means
of meeting tighter requirements for safety restraints, Chrysler
Corp. says it will install driver's-side air bags on all its 1990
cars.
   About 1 million Chrysler cars will have the devices in the coming
model year, the No. 3 automaker said Wednesday.
   General Motors Corp. said driver's-side air bags will be standard
on 15 of its 1990 car lines, or about 500,000 cars. Ford Motor Co.
said it will install them on nine major lines, an expected 1 million
cars.
   ``Part of it is meeting the passive restraint requirements,''
Chrysler spokesman Ben Dunn said, adding that company surveys show
safety is a top concern among customers.
   In addition to air bags, Dunn said Chrysler is equipping 17 of
its U.S.-built 1990 models with rear-seat lap and shoulder belts
rather than just lap belts. The automaker also will offer antilock
braking systems on 26 of its more than 30 car and truck lines in
1990, he said.
   Starting in 1990, federal regulations require front-seat passive
restraints in cars, comprising either manual safety belts
supplemented by driver's-side air bags or passive belt systems, GM
spokeswoman Toni Simonetti said.
   Passive restraints don't require an action such as buckling a
seat belt. Passive belt systems are partly anchored to the car door
so the belt wraps around the occupant when the door is closed.
   By 1993, air bag protection or passive belts will be required for
front seat passengers as well as drivers, Simonetti said.
   Passenger-side air bags are in the works but are harder to
design, she and Dunn said.
   ``The driver is in a fixed position, plus you have a natural home
for the air bag in the steering wheel assembly,'' Dunn said. ``On
the passenger side you have to engineer it to travel a greater
distance, and you don't know what position the passenger might be
in.''
</TEXT>
