<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 0844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Disney     06-22 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Disney,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Plan Enacted at Disney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Walt Disney Co. has adopted a ``poison
pill'' anti-takeover defense but says it does not know of any
prospective bids for the company.
   The plan adopted by Disney's board of directors and announced
Wednesday would entitle present stockholders to buy new stock at
half price in the event of a hostile takeover attempt. Such plans
dilute the holdings of a potential buyer, making a buyout without
management consent prohibitively expensive.
   The plan is similar to those adopted at many American
corporations in recent years, and has been under consideration at
Disney for several months, said spokesman Tom Deegan.
   ``It was not as a result of anything that has happened in the
last several weeks,'' Deegan said. He was referring to the three-way
buyout battle among Paramount Communications, Time Inc. and Warner
Communications Inc., and to a trend toward consolidation of media
giants.
   ``While we are not aware of any effort to acquire control of the
company, the stockholder rights plan represents a sound and
reasonable means of safeguarding the interests of all
stockholders,'' Disney said in a news release.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
