<HEAD>Hospital Corp., British Company Reach Tentative Sale Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital Corp. of America has tentatively
agreed to sell 10 hospitals and seven nursing homes in the United
Kingdom to a British health care group, HCA officials announced
Thursday.
   The $142 million sale to BUPA Health Services Ltd. must be
approved by HCA's board of directors. The two reached an agreement
in principle but have no definitive purchase agreement, the
Nashville health care giant said in a news release.
   The sale is expected to be finalized within 45 days.
   ``There can be no assurance that the conditions will be satisfied
and that the transaction will be consummated,'' the written
statement said.
   The facilities are owned by a British HCA subsidiary called HCA
United Kingdom Ltd. BUPA Health Services is a subsidiary of British
United Provident Association Ltd.
   Hospital Corp. is a wholly-owned subsidiary of HCA-Hospital Corp.
of America, formed in the recently completed, management-led
leveraged buyout of the company.
