<HEAD>Rain Pressures Corn, Soybean Futures; Wheat Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain in the western Corn Belt prompted early
selling of corn and soybean futures today on the Chicago Board of
Trade but wheat futures opened slightly higher on signs of Soviet
buying interest.
   A slow-moving cold front triggered scattered showers that dropped
amounts ranging from a trace to 1{ inches of rain Wednesday in
western Iowa, eastern Kansas and southern Minnesota.
   The storm system is expected to weaken as it makes its way east.
   Soybeans and soybean meal for near-term delivery opened slightly
higher in line with stronger European demand for soybean meal.
   The Soviet Union's apparent interest in new purchases of U.S.
wheat gave the wheat market a boost.
   ``They've got an official tender up right now for about 100,000
metric tons,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1{ cents higher with
July at $4.00} a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2{ cents lower with July
at $2.63{ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 4 cents lower with July at
$1.59{ a bushel; soybeans were 6} cents lower to { cent higher with
July at $7.39 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were moderately higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .23 cent higher with August at 70.15
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .65 cent higher with
August at 81.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .08 cent to .38 cent
higher with July at 49.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.63 cent to 1.18 cents higher with July at 34.20 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower while pork futures finished
mixed on Wednesday.
