<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SteelTalks     06-22 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steel Talks,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Announces Accord With Inland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Steelworkers said it reached a
tentative contract settlement early today with Inland Steel
Industries Inc.
   The agreement would cover four years beginning Aug. 1, according
to Jack Parton, the union's chief negotiator with Inland.
   Parton said details would be withheld until the union can explain
the contract to its 12,000 members at the nation's fourth-largest
steel producer.
   The accord was announced as other union bargainers and officials
at National Steel Corp. recoiled from the rank-and-file's surprise
rejection of a tentative, 50-month contract agreement.
   USW members at Bethlehem Steel Corp. overwhelmingly accepted
terms similar to the National settlement.
   National told its 7,000 employees in a letter sent Wednesday the
offer is the best they can expect from a company that trails the
major producers in profits per ton. Customers are already pulling
orders, the company said.
   National's contract expires July 31, and no further bargaining
sessions are scheduled. United Steelworkers negotiator Buddy Davis,
who continues to recommend the offer, said strike plans are being
prepared.
   ``The agreement you turned down would have increased your hourly
compensation, counting inflation, by $6.57 per hour by 1993,''
National Vice President Richard P. Coffee said in an open letter to
USW members.
   ``It would have cost National Steel $95.3 million more a year for
represented employees alone by the end of the contract. That's $7.5
million more than we made in 1988, and 1988 was the most profitable
year for National Steel since 1979,'' he said.
   National rebutted complaints that USW members got more money in
the early stages of their 50-month contract with Bethelehem Steel
Corp.
   ``They gave up more in 1986, and they are catching up to you
now,'' Coffee said.
   Like the Bethlehem agreement ratified recently by union members,
the National offer would have restored past concessions and raised
hourly wages by $1.50 over the contract term.
</TEXT>
