<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-ChildCare 4thLd-Writethru   06-22 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, 4th Ld-Writethru,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Defeats GOP Child Care Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; lead with vote on Democratic leadership
plan expected within 20 minutes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today defeated a White House-backed
child-care plan offered by Republicans as an alternative to a
broader program sponsored by the chamber's Democratic leadership.
   The GOP plan, defeated on a 56-44 vote, relied almost exclusively
on tax credits, an approach Democrats said would not address the
need for more child-care openings and improved quality of services.
   The Senate then immediately took up the Democratic leadership
plan, which combines direct subsidies to help parents and states pay
for child care with a tax-relief package similar to that proposed by
the Republicans.
   The leadership plan was expected to win approval but, under an
agreement between the parties, would still be subject to amendments.
A final vote was not expected until Friday.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said President
Bush had refused to discuss a compromise on child care, forcing the
partisan showdown.
   ``We've expressed an interest in talking to the White House all
along,'' Mitchell told reporters before the Senate convened. ``The
president and his aides have adamantly refused.''
   Today's votes came a week after the start of debate dominated by
floor speeches by co-authors of the revised Act for Better Child
Care, Sens. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
defending it against Republican attack.
   The Dodd-Hatch bill would authorize $1.75 billion for fiscal 1990
to help parents and states pay for child care.
   Seventy percent of the money would help parents pay for child
care, while the remaining 30 percent would be available to the
states for programs designed to improve the availability and quality
of care.
   The revised ABC bill, in the form of an amendment offered by
Mitchell, includes two tax changes. One would provide up to a $500
credit to low-income families to pay for children's health insurance.
   The other would make the existing dependent care tax credit
refundable to low-income families, some of whom otherwise do not
benefit from the provision because they have no federal tax
liability to which to apply the credit.
   In promoting their alternative, Republican senators have argued
that the ABC bill's subsidy provisions would result in state
bureaucracies that would limit parental choice in child care, a
position Dodd and Hatch have vigorously contested.
   ``We have a decidedly different approach to what is a real
problem,'' said Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind. ``The word `choice' is the
critical distinction.''
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., said the Dodd-Hatch plan would ``give
to government the decision as to what kind of child care shall be
provided.''
   The GOP package would also make the dependent care credit
refundable. Its other major provision would expand the existing
Earned Income Tax Credit to provide addition tax relief to
low-income families with children under age 5.
   Hatch, calling that inadequate, said Wednesday the expanded
credit would provide $750 to a poor family with two eligible
children while child care for the two would cost about $6,000 a year.
   Also, he said, using the GOP tax credits alone likely will not
solve child-care problems because parents would not be required to
spend the money on child care.
   Democrats have also attacked the GOP plan for cutting off
eligibility for the expanded credits at age 4, saying children twice
that age and more need child care. The Dodd-Hatch bill allows
payments for children up to age 13.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0301 </DOCNO>
