<FIRST>r f BC-Gateway     06-22 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gateway,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle for British Supermarket Group Heats Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The takeover battle for British supermarket group
Gateway Corp. PLC intensified Thursday as a sweetened offer from
Isosceles PLC was quickly countered by a competing bidder.
   The New York investment firm Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co. and the
Great Atlantic &amp; Pacific Tea Co. raised their bid for Gateway to the
equivalent of about $3.26 billion after Isosceles, a group of
dissatisfied Gateway shareholders, increased their's to about $3.19
billion.
   The U.S. group is trying to rescue Britain's third largest food
retailer from its two-month old takeover fight against Isosceles.
   Gateway, which controls about 11 percent of the $54.6 billion
U.K. grocery market, has supported the Americans.
   Wasserstein Perella and A&amp;P, collectively bidding as Newgateway,
have indicated that if their takeover succeeds they would keep much
of Gateway intact, except for Herman's sporting goods, which would
be sold.
   Isosceles had planned a more radical reorganization and intended
to sell off Gateway food stores.
   The latest Wasserstein Perella and A&amp;P bid is 235 pence ($3.66
dollars) a share, which values Gateway at 2.01 billion pounds ($3.26
billion).
   The Isosceles offer was raised to 230 pence ($3.586) a share from
210 pence ($3.274) a share. Isosceles' total offer for Gateway's
approximately 890 million shares would come to 2.05 billion pounds
($3.19 billion).
   Isosceles said Associated British Foods PLC had agreed to sell
its 15.1 percent holding of Gateway shares at the new price. This
raises Isosceles' stake in Gateway to 41.9 percent.
</TEXT>
