<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Integrated-Bass     06-22 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Integrated-Bass,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bass Makes Offer to Integrated Resources, Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas investor Robert Bass has talked with
Integrated Resources Inc. about investing in the financially
troubled real estate and insurance concern in exchange for a
controlling stake, a source said Thursday.
   Integrated is meeting with several interested parties, including
Bass, about receiving a large capital infusion after the company
last week announced plans to refinance $955 million in short-term
debt, the source, who asked not be identified, said.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that a Bass-led group
could be willing to pump as much as $200 million into Integrated
conditional on Integrated stock and bond holders accepting a
restructuring..
   Integrated had announced it would put up almost all of its $7.8
billion in assets and sharply cut back operations after defaulting
on oustanding bonds and commercial paper because of a cash shortage.
   The Bass group would emerge with much of the equity while the
company's common stock would be diluted, the Journal said.
Bondholders would have the security of of a new investor.
   An Integrated spokesman, David Caouette, declined to comment on
the newspaper report.
   After a delayed opening on the New York Stock Exchange,
Integrated was up 75 cents a share at $4.75 in mid-afternoon
trading. The company's stock has plunged from $15 last week and $40
in 1986.
   Bass, whose widespread holdings include the American Savings
Bank, Bell &amp; Howell and various media, cable television and real
estate properties, is believed to be interested in Integrated's
network of financial consultants who sell a wide variety of
investments ranging from insurance to real estate.
   The New York-based concern has 35 subsidiaries and 750,000
investor accounts.
   The Journal said Bass believes he would be able to calm the
concerns of Integrated Resources' bankers long enough to allow the
company to develop its financial products.
   Bass does not think the company's real estate problems are so
great, and he also believes the company's newer products like
insurance and leveraged buyout fund investments are sound, the paper
reported.
   Under its proposed restructuring, Integrated would replace $955
million in short-term debt with secured borrowings. The company also
said it would cut back its operations substantially.
   The company, which has $1.1 billion in capital, also said it
would concentrate on its core businesses of money management and
mutual funds, variable insurance products and limited partnerships.
   Its debt to be restructured includes outstanding short-term bank
debt, domestic and European commercial paper and notes outstanding
under loan-sale programs.
   About 50 banks are providing short-term loans to Integrated and
the company said it has about 50 to 75 holders of commercial paper
and notes under loan-sale programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
