<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-Takeovers     06-22 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Takeovers,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Take Control of Three S&amp;Ls in Ga.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators took control of three
savings and loans in Georgia on Thursday, bringing the total under
government management to 226 in 32 states.
   The three are First Federal Savings and Loan Association,
Americus; Habersham Federal Savings Bank, Atlanta, and Great
Southern Federal Savings Bank in Savannah. They have combined assets
of about $1.03 billion.
   In a legal maneuver to protect the institutions' assets from the
claims of subordinated debt holders, the government seized the
assets and transferred them to newly created entities, called First
Savings of Americus, Habersham Federal Savings and Loan Association
and Great Southern Federal Savings and Loan Association.
   Since early February, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has
been taking over the most deeply insolvent S&amp;Ls in preparation for
congressional passage of President Bush's S&amp;L bailout. The goal is
to uncover fraud and conserve assets until regulators have the money
to close the institutions or subsidize their sale to new owners.
</TEXT>
