<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-22 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Tumble On Iowa Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices closed sharply
lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as unexpectedly heavy
showers drenched some of the driest croplands in Iowa.
   Wheat and oat futures also retreated, largely in sympathy with
the corn and soybean markets.
   Rainfall amounts varied widely in the western Corn Belt, but one
report of a four-inch dousing in western Iowa apparently convinced
traders that the severely dry conditions there were finally easing.
   ``It's very typical of a weather market to exhibit this sort of
extreme price volatility on a day-by-day basis,'' said Ted Mao,
grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
``There's more of this type of volatility ahead.''
   The cold front that triggered the showers was expected to weaken
as it moved east.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.98} a bushel; corn was 4{ cents
lower to 1{ cents higher with July at $2.62 a bushel; oats were 5
cents to 6{ cents lower with July at $1.57 a bushel; soybeans were
14 cents to 22\ cents lower with July at $7.23{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
