<FIRST>d f BC-DenverSkyscraper     06-22 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Denver Skyscraper,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>54-Story Denver Building For Sale For $300 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 54-story former Mountain Bell Center in
downtown Denver _ one of the largest in the city and 91 percent
occupied _ is on the sale block for $300 million, officials said.
   BetaWest Properties Inc., the real estate arm of U S West Inc.,
has hired the New York investment banking firm of Morgan Stanley &amp;
Co. to sell the six-year-old building. The building was renamed 1801
California when Mountain Bell changed its name to U S West last year.
   The Rocky Mountain News reported Thursday that real estate
officials said BetaWest's asking price, at about $250 per square
foot, is too high, and they believe the building likely would sell
for $250 million to $270 million.
   BetaWest bought the building in September 1987 from Prudential
Insurance Co. for $196 million in the largest-ever single-property
transaction in the Rocky Mountain region. About 60 percent of the
building's occupied space now is leased by U S West.
   Ray D'Ardenne, senior vice president for Equitable Real Estate
Management Inc., said Morgan Stanley earlier this year offered the
building to his firm, but the price was too high.
   He said it is not unusual for a building the size of 1801
California to be sold through a Wall Street firm.
   ``With a deal that size, you have to have access to capital
markets, and those guys have access,'' D'Ardenne said.
</TEXT>
