<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Atlanta     06-22 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Atlanta,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Invited To Set Up Headquarters in Atlanta</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia official has asked strikebound Eastern
Airlines to think about moving its headquarters from Miami to
Atlanta, home of Eastern's chief rival, Delta Air Lines.
   Georgia Industry and Trade Commissioner George Berry said he sent
a proposal to Eastern President Phil Bakes several weeks ago, but
hasn't received a response.
   ``I'm sure there would be all kinds of options for them to
consider if they showed an interest'' in moving to Atlanta, Berry
said.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., has
done little to refute speculation recently that the airline may move.
   ``There's a good physical facility here,'' he said earlier this
week. ``Miami is important to Eastern.''
   Lorenzo did not rule out a move, however, saying, ``We're going
to have to see what makes sense as we go along.''
   Atlanta was Eastern's first operations base and has long been its
largest flight hub. It is at the forefront of Eastern's proposed
plan to rebuild as a smaller carrier and sell around $1.8 billion in
assets to pay debts.
   The plan calls for the Atlanta hub to be fully rebuilt to more
than 300 daily flights. Atlanta would be the center of operations
for the airline, which would be about 65 percent of its pre-strike
size.
   Before the strike that started March 4, about 6,700 of Eastern's
30,000 employees were based in Atlanta.
   The walkout by the Machinists union, joined by pilots and flight
attendants, nearly grounded Eastern and forced it to seek bankruptcy
protection from creditors on March 9.
</TEXT>
