<FIRST>r f AM-SupercomputingAwards     06-22 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Supercomputing Awards,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supercomputer Center Names High School Winners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The winners of a national competition
designed to introduce high school students to supercomputers were
announced Thursday by the Cornell National Supercomputing Facility
at Cornell University.
   The winning teams in the 1989 Superquest competition were Clear
Lake High School of Houston; Illinois Mathematics and Science
Academy, Aurora, Ill., Montgomery Blair High School, Silver Spring,
Md.; and North Carolina School of Science and Mathematics, Durham,
N.C., said CNSF Director Lawrence Lee.
   The winners will conduct supercomputer studies of airplane wings,
eye surgery, traffic lights, black holes, robots, medical X-rays,
brain-like computers, colliding galaxies, advanced maps, concert
halls and island ecology, among other things, Lee said.
   The winners will receive about $200,000 in workstations and
equipment from International Business Machines Corp., which along
with the National Science Foundation sponsors the one-of-a-kind
competition.
   The winners also will attend a 2{-week, expense-paid training
course at the Cornell supercomputing center in July. The winning
teams of a teacher-coach and three or four students will return to
their schools to carry out their projects but will continue to have
access to Cornell's supercomputer, one of five in the nation.
   The winning teams will deliver presentations on their projects to
an audience of scientists and engineers at Cornell on July 21.
   Supercomputers are powerful computers able to handle billions of
bits of information simultaneously. The Cornell supercomputer
facility provides supercomputing to more than 1,900 researchers at
more than 100 universities around the nation.
   The proposed projects range from the fanciful to the
mind-bending. Emily Meng-pae Wu of City High in Iowa City, Iowa, won
individual recognition for her proposal to study the biomechanics of
basketball shooting.
   Christopher Alan Adler of Thomas Jefferson High School for
Science and Technology in Fairfax County, Va., an honorable-mention
team, proposed to study ``the dynamics of higher order discrete
Volterra-Lotka predator-prey models.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
