<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-22 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Hit by Rumor and Lack of Buying Interest; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar sank against major foreign currencies
Thursday in a slide deepened by a rumor, quickly denied by the White
House, that President Bush had been shot.
   The dollar managed to recover some lost ground after the White
House denial. Currency dealers said the rumor circulated in foreign
exchange markets for 45 minutes to an hour.
   But a lack of buying interest in the dollar plus dollar sales by
central banks to prop up the sagging British pound contributed to a
generally weak day for the dollar, dealers said.
   William Mikus, a vice president at Salomon Brothers Inc., said
the Bush rumor ``probably pushed the dollar through 140 yen,
triggering a lot of stop-loss sales,'' which were aimed at limiting
losses by unloading dollars in case the currency declined further.
   Bob Morrissey, a senior trader at the Bank of Boston's New York
office, said trading was thin and choppy with the market on guard
for possible central bank intervention.
   A report by a Washington-based consulting group that Japan, the
United States and West Germany were determined to bring the dollar
lower by selling the American currency has been denied by central
banks but has left traders extra wary, Morrissey said.
   The British pound was hammered during the day by reports of more
railway strikes following Wednesday's 24-hour shutdown of the
national rail network over a pay claim.
   The pound recovered a bit in European trading when the Bank of
England, Britain's central bank, intervened in the market by buying
pounds to hold up the exchange rate. Late Thursday in London, one
British pound cost $1.5525, more expensive for buyers than late
Wednesday's $1.54675.
   Sterling was weighed down by renewed selling later in New York.
The Federal Reserve, possibly acting on behalf of the Bank of
England, was believed to have sold dollars and bought pounds,
currency dealers said.
   A pound was quoted at $1.5585 late in New York compared to
$1.5553 Wednesday.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar fell to 141.40 Japanese yen from
144.95 late Wednesday. In London late Thursday the dollar was
trading higher at 140.90 yen, but it slid to 139.30 yen later in New
York, down from 142.55.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.9515 West German marks, down from 1.9610; 1.6820
Swiss francs, down from 1.6905; 1.19135 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19325; 6.6215 French francs, down from 6.6565; and 1,417.75
Italian lire, down from 1,423.50.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with levels late
Wednesday were: 1.9590 West German marks, down from 1.9680; 1.6860
Swiss francs, down from 1.7005; 6.6325 French francs, down from
6.6795; 2.2005 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2375; 1,418.50 Italian
lire, down from 1.439.50; and, 1.1925 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19675.
   Gold prices pulled back slightly in the United States after
rising on markets abroad. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a bid of $370.25 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m. EDT, down $1
from Wednesday's late bid.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $371 a troy ounce, down $1.40 from Wednesday's
settlement price.
   Gold bullion closed at a bid of $369.75 a troy ounce in London,
the major European market, up from $366.75 late Wednesday. The
closing price in Zurich was $370.60 bid, up from $366.40.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid of $370.35, up from
$365.95.
   Silver bullion prices rose. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.292 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $5.285. Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of
$5.34 a troy ounce, up from $5.28.
</TEXT>
