constitutional convention was seen as an endorsement for his
leadership over the criticism of a vocal dissident faction.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former New York Federal Reserve Bank board
member has admitted illegally passing on confidential interest rate
data in the first insider trading case involving government
securities.
   In a plea agreement, Robert A. Rough, 50, pleaded guilty
Wednesday to a single bank fraud charge and the government in
exchange dropped two insider trading charges and four related counts.
   As part of the plea deal, prosecutors also agreed to recommend a
prison term of under one year for the former banker. Rough faces a
maximum five years in jail and $10,000 fine. Sentencing is set for
Aug. 18.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines asked the U.S. Bankruptcy Court to
terminate its contract with the striking pilots union as it sought a
permanent increase in pilots' work hours and about $50 million in
temporary concessions.
   Eastern attorney Harvey Miller said Wednesday the company was not
requesting abrogation of its union contract, but was requesting
permission to move ahead with Eastern's rebuilding plan because the
pilots union has balked at negotiating a new contract. Prior to the
strike, the pilots had been working under the old contract even
though it had expired a year earlier.
</TEXT>
