<TEXT>
   Seven semiconductor makers and users
said they plan to join forces in an unprecedented venture to produce
computer memory chips and reduce dependence on Japanese suppliers.
   The plan, disclosed Wednesday, calls for the venture named U.S.
Memories Inc. to be funded by microchip makers and their major
customers.
   Companies which contributed ``seed money'' to plan the
corporation include Advanced Micro Devices Inc., Digital Equipment
Corp., Hewlett-Packard Co., International Business Machines Corp.,
Intel Corp., LSI Logic Corp. and National Semiconductor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner will
keep an open mind during his review of the proposed sale of
