<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-22 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Signs Of Soviet Buying Send Sugar Futures To 11-Month High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reports of sugar purchases by the Soviet Union whipped the sugar
futures market into a bullish frenzy Thursday, with prices reaching
an 11-month high on speculation that the surprise transactions
implied further buying down the road.
   On other markets, corn and soybean futures wilted as rain arrived
in Iowa; coffee futures rallied; and energy, precious-metals and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Sugar futures settled .50 cent to .94 cent higher on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange with the contract for delivery in
July at $1.399 a pound, the market's highest level since July 25.
   The rally was fueled by trade reports that the Soviets had bought
2 cargoes of refined white sugar and one cargo of raw sugar on the
open market. One cargo equals 10,000 to 12,000 metric tons.
   The Soviet Union usually does its sugar buying in the fall and
winter, and had stated repeatedly earlier this year that it
completed its sugar buying for all of 1989.
   ``A lot of people in the business view this as the tip of the
proverbial iceberg, meaning the Soviets will come in and do even
more shopping,'' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst who follows the
sugar, coffee and cocoa markets for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Analysts predicted new Soviet purchases would total at least
100,000 metric tons and could run as high as 300,000 metric tons.
   Some speculated the Soviets were forced to enter the world market
because of slow shipments from Poland or because the Russian
sugar-beet crop was smaller than expected.
   Or they may simply have observed the market's sharp upward move
over the past several weeks and decided to lay in supplies before
prices go higher.
   ``They look at supply-and-demand figures as much as everyone
else,'' said analyst Kim Badenhop of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
Inc. in New York.
   Corn and soybean futures fell sharply on the Chicago Board of
Trade as showers drenched some of the driest croplands in Iowa.
   Rainfall amounts varied widely in the western Corn Belt, but one
report of a four-inch dousing in western Iowa apparently convinced
traders that the severely dry conditions there were finally easing.
   Wheat settled { cent to 3{ cents lower with July at $3.98} a
bushel; corn was 4{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with July at
$2.62\ a bushel; oats were 5 cents to 6{ cents lower with July at
$1.57 a bushel; soybeans were 14 cents to 22\ cents lower with July
at $7.23{ a bushel.
   Coffee futures rallied strongly on the Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange on buying supported by indications of tight near-term
supplies and by the International Coffee Organization's announcement
of a 1.5-million-bag cut in export quotas of high-quality mild
arabica coffees. A bag of coffee equals 60 kilograms or about 132
pounds.
   The export cut was triggered by a drop in coffee prices.
   Coffee settled 1 cent to 2.72 cents higher with July at $1.1899 a
pound.
   Unleaded gasoline futures climbed sharply on the New York
Mercantile Exchange following an Energy Department report that
refuted Tuesday's American Petroleum Institute report showing a
substantial rise in U.S. stocks of gasoline. The rally spilled over
to the crude-oil and heating-oil markets.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent lower to 10
cents higher with August at $19.30 a barrel; heating oil was .64
cent to 1.02 cents higher with July at 48.62 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .56 cent to 1.89 cents higher with July at
60.99 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures set back a bit on New York's Commodity Exchange
following the strong gains of the previous session. Silver inched up.
   Gold settled $1.40 to $1.60 higher with August at $374.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.5 cent to 0.7 cent higher with July at $5.303 a
troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures finished little changed in listless
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .33 cent lower with August at 69.97
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .50 cent higher with
August at 81.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .15 cent lower to .13
cent higher with July at 49.20 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .05 cent lower to .17 cent higher with July at 33.67 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
