<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MethanolCars 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Methanol Cars, 1st Ld-Writethru,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Executive Blasts Bush Proposal on Non-Gasoline Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT million to billion. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A representative of the major oil companies on
Thursday attacked President Bush's clean-air proposal involving
methanol-powered cars, saying it could add to public health risks
without significantly improving air quality.
   Charles J. DiBona, president of the American Petroleum Institute,
told a House panel the oil industry was unhappy with Bush's proposal
for requiring the use of cars powered by methanol to reduce certain
smog-causing pollutants.
   ``Methanol fuel use is unlikely to result in significant air
quality improvements, raises serious public health concerns because
of methanol's high toxicity, and will not enhance national energy
security significantly,'' DiBona said.
   The oil industry produces about 110 billion gallons of gasoline a
year. It currently does not have the capacity to produce large
quantities of alternative fuels.
   Bush said his proposals, announced June 12 as part of a broad
package of measures aimed at making the air cleaner, would combat
smog in urban areas by reducing emissions of carbon monoxide, while
also limiting toxic pollutants such as benzene. It would require
that 500,000 alternative-fuel cars be built by 1995.
   DiBona told a subcommittee of the House Banking, Finance and
Urban Affairs Committee that consumers will pay more per mile for
methanol than gasoline, will need to fill up more frequently because
methanol burns less efficiently, and may have more problems starting
their cars in cold weather because methanol needs more heat to start
burning.
   ``Under a methanol mandate, consumers would have to bear these
costs and yet not receive a significant overall improvement in air
quality,'' DiBona said.
   DiBona also said limited domestic supplies of natural gas _ the
cheapest source for methanol _ meant Bush's proposal could undermine
national security. This is because the extra supplies of natural gas
would come, at least in part, from the Middle East, thus adding to
American dependence on an unstable region, he said.
   DiBona also criticized Bush's proposals for reducing gasoline's
volatility, or its ability to evaporate into the atmosphere, and for
requiring gasoline pump controls aimed at reducing the amount of
vapors escaping into the air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890622-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-22 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Edge Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices finished mostly higher
Thursday, led by gasoline futures after a government report showed a
drop in gasoline supplies, contradicting an earlier industry figure.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, slipped a
penny to close at $19.30 a barrel, after gaining 43 cents on
Wednesday. Other crude contracts closed narrowly higher.
   Among refined products, the July contract for unleaded gasoline
rose 1.89 cents to close at 60.99 cents a gallon, after a 0.7 cent
decline on Wednesday. August unleaded gasoline gained 1.61 cents to
58.30 cents a gallon and September closed at 55.79 cents, up 1.43
cents.
   Heating oil also advanced, with the July contract settling 0.64
cent higher at 48.62 cents a gallon. Contracts for delivery later in
the year posted higher gains.
   Traders said crude prices started out strong amid news of an oil
production slowdown in the North Sea due to pipeline problems.
   But the market's attention turned to gasoline futures after a
Department of Energy report showed that gasoline inventories
declined last week. The report contradicted an American Petroleum
Institute report released on Tuesday showing a rise in gasoline
inventories.
   Gasoline futures prices dipped on Wednesday after the API, which
represents major oil producers and refiners, reported that gasoline
stocks rose by 1.6 million barrels to 221.1 million barrels last
week despite an increase in demand as the summer driving season
picks up.
   But the DOE report released late Wednesday showed that total
gasoline supplies were down 1.3 million barrels to 218.7 million
barrels.
   ``The new numbers were surprising because usually the two reports
are pretty close,'' said Bob Baker, analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. ``It was a factor that affected prices.''
   Both reports showed a decline in crude and heating oil
inventories for the week and a drop of some 30 million barrels in
total oil supplies, including crude and products, from last year.
</TEXT>
