<FIRST>u f AM-UAWConvention     06-22 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Convention,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissidents Will Expand Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Directions dissident movement in
the United Auto Workers union, stung by defeats here, will expand
its scope and hold a convention this fall, the group's leader said
Thursday.
   Jerry Tucker, who on Wednesday lost a re-election bid to the
union's 21-member International Executive Board, said a steering
committee would be formed to guide the movement's efforts.
   He also said a convention would be held this fall at a time and
place yet to be set and that a limited organizing effort, calling
for $30-a-year membership fee, would be expanded nationwide.
   However, Tucker said the New Directions had no immediate plans to
form a formal dissident group within the UAW, such as the Teamsters
for a Democratic Union did within the Teamsters in 1976. The TDU and
New Directions share some goals, such as increasing individual
member participation in union affairs, and have the same attorney,
Chip Yablonski of Washington.
   ``It's an accelerating and a broadening of what's been going
on,'' Tucker said after the New Directions forces held a caucus at a
hotel near the convention.
   Roy Wyse, who defeated Tucker in an election for director of
Region 5, said Wednesday that his election was the ``beginning of
the end for New Directions.''
   But, Tucker countered Thursday, ``I think Brother Wyse will soon
find that New Directions is accelerating ...''
   New Directions has suffered a defeat on the convention floor
every day since the UAW's triennial constitutional convention opened
Sunday. It made challenges to delegation members being seated, then
a resolution calling for direct election of top national officers
and a move to restrict joint labor-management programs on plant
floors.
   All those efforts failed. But Tucker and his backers remained
optimistic about the future of their organization and its effect on
UAW administration.
   ``They know they have to deal with us for the next three years,''
said New Directions member Ed Tweed of Local 596 in Lake Orion,
Mich. ``We know they will go in (to factories) and pay more
attention in each local. If they do that we have to get the credit
for it.''
</TEXT>
