<FIRST>u f AM-Newmont     06-22 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newmont,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newmont Mining Selling Half Of Peabody Holding Co. Inc.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newmont Mining Corp. announced Thursday it has
signed a definitive agreement to sell 50.03 percent of Peabody
Holding Co. Inc. to Salomon Brothers and Shearson Lehman Hutton for
$75 million cash.
   The agreement is part of the Denver-based gold company's
previously announced plan to recapitalize Peabody, a major coal firm.
   The sale, expected to occur in the third quarter of this year,
will be complete when Peabody has redeemed shares held by others for
a total redemption price of $575 million and has paid a $425 million
dividend to Newmont.
   The agreement gives Newmont the option to reacquire the 50.03
percent interest from Salomon and Shearson after four years, and it
allows Newmont to name a majority of the Peabody board.
   Newmont, which will retain a 49.97 percent interest in Peabody,
will use its $500 million in aggregate proceeds from the Peabody
recapitalization and sale to reduce its debt, said Gordon R. Parker,
Newmont chairman, president and chief executive officer.
   Parker said Peabody will refinance most of its own existing
indebtedness as part of the recapitalization.
   Besides its interest in Peabody, Newmont also owns 90 percent of
Newmont Gold Co. and 75 percent of Newmont Australia Ltd.
   Newmont, the biggest U.S. gold miner, is 49.3 percent owned by
Britain's Consolidated Gold Fields PLC. On Thursday British
conglomerate Hanson Trust PLC made a $4.8 billion buyout offer for
Gold Fields. The developments were not directly related.
</TEXT>
