<FIRST>u f AM-SteelTalks     06-22 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Talks,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inland, USW Reach Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Steelworkers union said it reached a
tentative four-year contract settlement Thursday with Inland Steel
Co. that raises wages in each of the first three years, improves
pensions and avoids any worker concessions.
   ``We're going to recommend it, and it does meet all the goals our
members helped formulate. I think they'll accept it,'' said Jack
Parton, director of USW District 31 and chief negotiator with the
nation's fourth-largest steel producer.
   Inland originally wanted concessions, including the right to
schedule workers for a 12-hour work day, Parton said. The company
also wanted the employees to help pay medical insurance premiums.
Both demands were withdrawn by company negotiators.
   Incentive pay will be increased in the fourth year, and the
agreement also improves pension benefits and resolves differences
over the status of maintenance jobs, he said.
   Inland's workers gave no wage concessions in the 1986
negotiations, so there was no restoration of past sacrifices.
   The talks began March 7, earliest among four major producers who
shared July 31 contract expirations. By a self-imposed settlement
deadline of March 31, Inland still was demanding concessions and had
offered no wage increase, Parton said.
   ``We hadn't had a raise in about eight years, when inflation was
22 percent. The company made a big buck. Management got raises. They
deserve raises, but so do we,'' Parton said.
   By late May ``we still couldn't convince our counterparts that
our members were entitled to share in those profits,'' he said. ``We
started preparing for a strike.''
   The 12,000 USW members at Inland were hearing late in the
bargaining that a sticking point remained over wage increases in the
first year, and their fellow union members at National Steel Corp.
this week surprised negotiators by rejecting a 50-month offer in
part because it offered less money up front than workers accepted
from Bethlehem Steel Corp.
   The Inland settlement came around 4 a.m. in Chicago, where the
company is based.
</TEXT>
