<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 1905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneySupply     06-22 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Supply,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply rose in mid-June but a narrower money measure fell, the
Federal Reserve Board reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose $4.8 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,084.8 billion in the week ended June 12 from
$3,080.0 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, rose $7.5 billion to a seasonally
adjusted $3,970.8 billion from $3,963.3 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, slipped $6.6
billion to a seasonally adjusted $769.5 billion from $776.1 billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In judging its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures.
   The Fed in February reaffirmed a provisional target for 1989 of 3
percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent
growth in M3. The Fed has not set a target for M1 growth since early
1987.
   For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $3,078.0 billion, a 1.2
percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13
weeks. M3 averaged $3,957.0 billion, up 3.4 percent, while M1 fell
4.5 percent to an average of $778.8 billion.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York said bank borrowings from
the Federal Reserve System at the discount window, excluding
extended credit, averaged $546 million a day in the week ended
Wednesday, up from $471 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the monetary
base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at
Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation,
was $289.9 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, up from
$289.2 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
