<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Coffee     06-22 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Coffee,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Coffee Export Quota Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Coffee Organization on Thursday
slashed the quota for exports after a sharp fall in world prices.
   The association of producers and consumers, which regulates the
$10 billion annual world trade in coffee beans, cut 1.53 million
bags, reducing the global allocation for the current year to 55.34
million bags.
   ``No further cut is possible,'' a statement said.
   One bag contains 60 kilos or 132 pounds.
   Most of the reduction will be borne by Brazil, Colombia, Mexico,
El Salvador and the other producers of the prized arabica type of
bean, most of them Latin American.
   The cut became inevitable when the price of coffee fell below the
organization's $1.30-a-pound indicator price for arabica coffee.
   The organization of 74 countries tries to keep the average price
of the two basic coffee types, arabica and robusta, within a band of
$1.10 to $1.40 a pound by balancing supply with demand through quota
adjustments at fixed prices.
   Despite previous quota reductions that affected only robusta
producers, the average price of both types last week dropped below
$1.10 a pound.
   Robusta coffee is the poorer and less popular type produced
throughout most of Africa and in Indonesia.
</TEXT>
