<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-89 2044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAWSalaries     06-22 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Salaries,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-UAW Convention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bieber Making $91,469 Plus COLA This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3 percent raise for United Auto Workers
union President Owen Bieber and the union's other top officers was
approved Thursday by delegates to the union's constitutional
convention.
   The raise, retroactive to June 1, boosted Bieber's annual salary
as head of the 1 million-member union to $91,469.42.
   Bieber and the other officers also will receive quarterly
cost-of-living adjustments and 3 percent lump-sum payments on June
1, 1990 and on the same day in 1991. For Bieber, each lump-sum
payment works out to at least $2,744.08.
   The formula of a 3 percent raise, COLA adjustments and lump-sum
payments for the union's 21 top officers is the same as that
negotiated for UAW members in 1987 at General Motors Corp. and Ford
Motor Co. Last year, the UAW negotiated a contract with Chrysler
Corp. calling for two 3 percent lump sum payments that brought wages
for all Big Three workers into balance.
   UAW Secretary-Treasurer Bill Casstevens' salary went to
$83,078.35 with two annual lump-sum payments of at least $2,492.35.
   Salaries for vice presidents Stephen Yokich, Ernie Lofton, Stan
Marshall and Odessa Kommer rose to $79,800.56 a year, plus two
annual payments of at least $2,394.02. Pay for the union's 15
regional directors rose to $71,409.48 with lump sum payments of at
least $2,142.28.
   The salary increases came as delegates to the convention, which
concludes Friday, approved a report from the constitution committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
